<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE - 3D Stereo Microscopy : Silverfish</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#000000" text="#00ff00">

<a name="top">

<P>
<center><h1>3D Silverfish</h1></center>
<em><center>Wait for image to load... its true 3D and therefore worth it!</center></em>
<br>

<center><IMG SRC="3dsilver.jpg" width=311 height=246></center>
<p>
<h4>


Andrew Syred of Microscopix, one of our crew here working their spare time to show you the astonishing
world of Amateur Microscopy, has produced yet another remarkable image. Did you ever see a flash of silver
darting around the bathroom, and just as you looked, whatever you saw - was gone?
<p>
Chances are that it was a silverfish, <em>Lepisma saccharina</em> to be really precise and scientific. These 
beautiful insects are Bristletails (Order Thysanura). Tiny insects fairly abundant in our houses which 
mostly come out at night. They like to feed on starch-based materials: flour, paper, which really amazes me
because you don't find much of these things to eat in the bathroom?!
<p>
They like a moist environment so I guess that's what attracts them to the small room. I wonder is the spillage
from our nightly tooth-brushing, or possibly the chemicals we use in the bath gives them something suitable
to eat. Does anyone out there know the answer?
<p>
Now don't go drowning these life-forms or squishing them. In their own way they are quite beautiful creatures,
well designed, and in most cases - they stay out of your way. Your house is home to many other life forms which, in
most cases, do little harm; and since we are taking up a lot of the planet surface, we can afford to give other creatures
a bit of rent-free space even if you initially find them a bit repulsive. Such feelings are caused by your own fear
of the things you don't fully understand. Learn a bit about other creatures and such feelings rapidly disappear.
 

<p>
<em>The Editor</em>
</h4>
<H3>
<center>
<A HREF="3dfront.html#select">3D Image Selector</A>
</center>
</h3>

<br>
<h4>
<center>Comments and errors to <a href="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">The Editor</A></center>
</h4>
