<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE - 3D Stereo Microscopy : Microscopes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#000000" text="#00ff00">

<a name="top">
<center>

<h4>Microscopy UK: "Pioneering Microscopy on the Web!"</h4>
<img src="title.gif">
</center>
<p>


<P>
<center><h1>3D MICROSCOPE IMAGES</h1></center>
<center><h3>THE BUSINESS END OF A SCOPE</h3></center>
<p>
<br>

<CENTER><img src="3dlens1.jpg"></CENTER>
<br>
<h4>
This is a good old sturdy Vickers Microscope, or at least the part of it
where the specimen slides are placed for study. You can see the turret is 
holding four objective lenses of different powers of magnification. Also,
note that the stage is a circular one - commonly used on a <em>petrological</em>
microscope designed to study rocks and minerals. 
<p>
A more common sliding x-y stage can however be attached to this one for 
easier study of other subjects.
<p>
A lot of the material seen on micscape will have been <em>sourced</em> via a 
camera attached to this 'scope'.
<p>
</h4>
