<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE - 3D Stereo Microscopy : Sea Urchin</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#000000" text="#00ff00">

<a name="top">

<P>
<center><h1>3D Sea Urchin</h1></center>
<em><center>Wait for image to load... its true 3D and therefore worth it!</center></em>
<br>

<center><IMG SRC="3durchin.jpg" width=307 height=236></center>
<p>
<h4>
This is not a microscopic life form but what the heck, it looked good, is related to what
our site is about (looking more closely at life on our planet), so we decided to include it
anyway. Another 3D image from Andrew Syred of a Sea Urchin, <em>Echinus Esculentus</em> to be precise.
In fact, what you are looking at is not the complete animal, but its shell - called a <em>teste</em>.
<p>
I looked around my bookshelf to see if I can write something up to interest you about this 
creature but could not find anything. So it's over to you! Anyone like to send us a few lines
to fill in this blank space? If so, why not <a href="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">drop me a note</A>
and I'll put the lines in here with your name as well.
<p>
<em>The Editor</em>
</h4>
