<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>MICROSCOPY UK / MICSCAPE - Article: Darwin - The Microscopist? </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<A HREF="top"></A>
<H1><CENTER>Micscape Article</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Darwin - The Microscopist?</H2>
<h4> by David W Walker.</h4>
</CENTER>
<hr>
<p>
<I>A brief review of Darwin's microscopes and the investigations he made with them. You can also visit Darwin's house in Kent.</I>
<p>
<IMG SRC="../images/darwf1.gif" ALT="" HSPACE=8 ALIGN=LEFT>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Cary">The Cary Microscope</A><BR>

<LI><A HREF="#Beagle">The Beagle Microscope</A><BR>

<LI><A HREF="#Simple">Darwin's simple and compound microscopes</A><BR>

<LI><A HREF="#Comments">Comments on Darwin's microscopical work</A><BR>

<LI><A HREF="#Micro">Darwin the Microscopist?</A><BR>

<LI><A HREF="#Ref">References and sources of information</A><BR>
</UL>
<BR><BR>
<A NAME="Cary"></A>
Charles Darwin's well known works were concerned primarily with organisms that were far from microscopic, therefore it may come as some surprise that some of his lesser known works were largely based on microscopical observations. These works include studies and publications on Cirripedes (barnacles), insectivorous plants and the fertilisation of orchids.<P>

<B>The Cary Microscope</B><BR>

Exhibited in the old study at Darwin's House in Downe, Kent is a microscope of the Cary type, and is signed CARY, LONDON. Evidence suggests that it was possibly bought in 1831, before the <I>Beagle</I> voyage. It is designed as a pocket microscope, because it can be dismantled and neatly packed in a velvet-lined box (6.25x3.75x3 inches).<P>

The rectangular stage uses small slides ca 2.5 x 0.5 inch and predate the 3 x 1 inch standard slides used today which were introduced about 1840.<P>

The stage is mounted on a sleeve which can be manually slid up and down the pillar to give coarse focussing. Fine focussing is achieved by  rotating a knurled collar at the top of the pillar. The body of the microscope can also be moved at right angles to the long axis of the stage by a rack and pinion movement on the microscope arm.<P>

The microscope is designed to take either a compound body or to be used with a single lens. A compound microscope of this era would typically have a two-lens eyepiece, an intermediate field lens (although not present in Darwin's microscope) and a single lens objective.<P>

The focussing mechanism of this microscope was apparently awkward to use, and Darwin may have had this instrument in mind when he stated in a letter written in 1848<P>

<I>'the fiddling instrument sold in shops'</I>.<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<A NAME="Beagle"></A>
<B>The <I>Beagle</I> Microscope</B><BR>

<IMG SRC="../images/darwf2.gif" ALT="" HSPACE=8 ALIGN=RIGHT>

Before Darwin set out on the now famous <I>Beagle</I> voyage in December 1831, he sought the advice of Robert Brown regarding a suitable microscope to take with him. Robert Brown was a pioneering botanist and microscopist who is perhaps best remembered for first describing the random motion of colloidal particles now named after him - Brownian motion. Brown had sailed as a naturalist aboard the <I>Investigator</I> which surveyed the northern and southern coasts of Australia in 1801.<P>

On the advice of Brown, Darwin only took with him a simple microscope on the <I>Beagle</I>, which presumably he acquired during his final stay in London. This microscope is shown on the stamp on the right. It is signed<P>

<I>BANCKS & SON 119 New Bond Stst. Instrt Makers to His Majesty.</I><P>

Robert Bancks (or Banks) was an instrument maker to George IV, and had also made instruments for scientists such as Robert Brown and Sir William Hooker. It should be remembered that the description 'simple microscope' refers to the single lens construction, but does not infer they were not capable of serious research work. The single lens microscope was a good general purpose microscope and gave as high a resolution and magnification as were attainable at the time. However, most of their use would have been for low power dissection.<P>

The construction of the microscope differs in a number of respects to the Cary microscope. The main pillar was fixed rather than having a ball and socket joint and the stage was circular, allowing a watch glass or flat glass disc to be attached. This was much more practical for the examination and dissection of specimens than the narrow slide holder of the Cary.<P>

Darwin would have used the microscope extensively during his voyage, although he may have been unfamiliar with it's use. This, together with the profusion of unfamiliar marine organisms he would have encountered, may have prompted his son Francis to remark:<P>

'<I>His zoological notes of that period give an impression of vigorous work, hampered by ignorance and lack of appliances: and his untiring industry in the dissection of marine animals, especially of Crustacea, must have been of value to him as training for his Cirripede work</I>.'<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>

<A NAME="Simple"></A>
<B>Darwin's simple microscope built to his own design</B><BR>

Ten years after his return from the <I>Beagle</I> voyage, Darwin began a major systematic work on living and fossil Cirripedes (barnacles). Darwin had a simple microscope built to his own design, which was intended to be more practical. It did not possess fine focussing and had a larger stage than the Beagle microscope to take shallow dishes for aqueous dissections.<P>

Judging from Darwin's letters to his friends and colleagues, he was very pleased with this microscope. For instance, in a letter to Henslow (the Professor of Botany at Cambridge when Darwin studied there), he remarked<P>

it is <I>'wonderfully superior for coarse and fine definitions than any I ever before worked with. If I had had it sooner, it would have saved me many an hour.'</I> <P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>

<A NAME="Compound"></A>
<B>Darwin's Compound Microscope</B><BR>
<IMG SRC="../images/darwf3.gif" ALIGN=LEFT hspace=12>By the middle of the nineteenth century, the achromatic compound microscope had been developed to a stage where the optics were superior to that of a simple microscope.<P>

In 1846 Darwin bought a compound microscope because of his need for higher magnifications (shown left). (A larger 24 bit image of Darwin's compound microscope <b>was</b> available in jpeg format as the monthly image download in Issue 1 of Micscape).<P>

It is signed on the foot of the microscope 'Jas SMITH LONDON'. This microscope has many of the features typical of a compound microscope of the time, and which are recognisable in today's models ie coarse and fine focussing, mechanical stage and provision for substage condenser. The fine focussing was achieved by turning the milled screw in front of the nosepiece. It used the English ten-inch tube with an additional graduated draw tube which could be further extended by six inches primarily to increase magnification.<P>

There is some uncertainty as to the objectives Darwin used with the microscope, but from his writings he is known to have had objectives ranging from about 5x to 80x giving magnifications of at least up to 800x with the appropiate eyepieces.<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>

<A NAME="Comments"></A>
<B>Comments on Darwin's microscopical work</B><BR>

Darwin was often helped by his sons in his microscopical work, and especially by his third son Francis. The illustrations for his published work were also carried out by Francis, and for his Cirripede volumes by George Brettingham Sowerby, a professional illustrator.<P>

Darwin learnt to be proficient at dissection, but when he required sections, these were carried out by Francis. It was not until the last year of Darwin's life that he learnt to section using a hand-held razor.<P>

Although histological staining techniques were introduced in about 1850, he did not adopt these techniques. This was despite the fact that his son Francis would have been familiar with such techniques through his medical training.<P>

Most of Darwin's work would have been routine eg counting seeds using the simple microscope or examining pollen grains with the higher powered compound microscope. His patience in such tasks is evident from a remark in his <I>'..Forms of Flowers..'</I>.<P>

<I>'..the observations are extremely troublesome, and will not soon be repeated - thus I was compelled to count under the microscope above 20,000 seeds of Lythrum salicaria'.</I><P>

The simple dissecting microscope built to his own design would have been used for his work on Cirripedes, and also his work on the fertilisation of orchids. For the latter work, Darwin preferred to dissect the flowers rather than use serial sectioning and staining - techniques with which he was less familiar.<P>

He also used the compound microscope with low power eyepiece and stage removed for examining potted plants <I>in situ</I>.<P>

Darwin carried out studies on insectivorous plants, and he is thought to have made some of the illustrations in his book on this subject. He was particularly interested in the cellular changes observed in the tentacles of <I>Drosera</I> (Sundew) and other plants as a result of feeding. The last two papers that Darwin presented to the Linnean Society, London in 1882, just before his death, were related to this topic.<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>

<A NAME="Micro"></A>
<B>Darwin the Microscopist?</B><BR>
In conclusion, can we say that Darwin was a microscopist? From his work we are left with the impression that Darwin regarded microscopy as a means to an end ie to further his studies of nature, rather than becoming deeply involved in the technical aspects of microscopy. It is probably more accurate to state that Darwin was a naturalist who used a microscope.<P>

Perhaps we can end with another of his son Francis' remarks about his father.<P>

<I>'He was a Naturalist in the old sense of the word, that is a man who works at many branches of science, not merely a specialist in one.'</I><P><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>


Why not find out more about Darwin and his work by<A HREF="http://www.nhm.ac.uk/tring"> visiting Darwin's home</A>, now a museum at Down House, Downe, Kent, UK.</A><P>

<A NAME="Ref"></A>
<B>References and sources of information</B><BR>

1) <B>W A S Burnett and L V Martin, Microscopy, 1992, vol 36, part 8, 604-627.</B><BR>
An excellent article which discusses Darwin's microscopes in some detail. Microscopy is the Journal of the Quekett Microscopical Club.<P>

The above Web article was inspired by and broadly based on this article.<P>

<I>The <A HREF="../../amateurs/qmc/mainqmc.html">Quekett Microscopical Club</A> Journal 'Microscopy' regularly has authoritative articles on all aspects of the history of light microscopy and microscopists.<P></I>

2) <B>Single Lens: The Story of the Simple Microscope by B J Ford</B>, Heinemann, London, 1985. 182 pages. SBN 434 26844 5.<BR>
An easy to read but authoritative account of the contribution Anton van Leeuwenhoek and others made to science using a single lens microscope.<P>

3) <B>Collecting Microscopes by G L'E Turner</B>, Christie's International Collectors Series, Mayflower Books, New York 1981. 120 pages. ISBN  0 8317 5950 X.<BR>
A beautifully illustrated book written by one of the foremost authorities on the history of the microscope.<P>

4) <B>The Microscope Past and Present by S Bradbury</B>, Pergamon Press, London, 1968. 272 pages. Library of Congress Catalogue Card No. 68-24061.<BR>
A fascinating and scholarly account of the history and development of the microscope.<P>

5) <B>Some lesser known publications by Charles Darwin</B>.<P>

A Monograph on the Subclass 'Cirripedia' 2 vol. 1851-54 (reissued as vol 11-13 of The Works of Charles Darwin 1988).<P>

On the Various Contrivances by Which British and Foreign Orchids are Fertilised by Insects... 1862.<P>

Insectivorous Plants 1865.<P>

The Different Forms of Flowers on Plants of the Same Species 1877.<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="#top">Back to Top of Page</A></CENTER><P>


