<BODY>
<center>
<hr>
<h2>www.microscopy-uk.org.uk : Biology for Schools</h2>
<hr>
</center>
<center><h1>Leaf Vein</h1></center>
<img src="leaf.gif" align=left >
This image shows a vascular bundle from the midrib of a leaf. The <strong>xylem -{1}</strong>
is situated above the <strong>phloem</strong> towards the upper surface. Beneath this point,
<strong>cambium -{2}</strong> is present - which will have originally divided to produce xylem
and <strong>phloem -{3}.</strong>
<p>
The very large cells surrounding the whole structure are <strong>parenchyma cells -{4}.</strong>
<p>
Note that the colours and shades in this image are not truly representational of the true
colours of a 'stained' plant tissue. This is a result of reducing the number of colours in the image
to reduce file size.
<br>
<br>
