<HTML><!--Author:	D & I WalkerDate:	December 6th, 1995--><HEAD><title>Micscape - Microscopy Club</title><center><H3>NORTHAMPTONSHIRE NATURAL HISTORY SOCIETY<BR> AND FIELD CLUB</H3></center></HEAD><BR><BODY><a name="topns"><UL><LI><A HREF="#about">About the Society</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#activities">Activities and the Microscopy Section</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#info">Further information</A><BR></UL><A NAME="about"></A><B>About the Society</B><BR>The Society was formed in 1876 with the aim of promoting interest and research into natural history and allied sciences especially related to Northamptonshire.<P><B>The Society is home to the Gordon Osborn International Sand Collection,</B> which featured in an article in the Daily Telegraph weekend supplement. This collection is looked after by one of the Microscopy Section members.<P>                                                                      <B>The Society also has a good collection of Myxomycetes</B> (slime moulds), and this has been revised by a national expert.<P><B>What interests are catered for?</B><BR>There are Society sections whose interests cover the following subjects:<P><UL><LI>ARCHAEOLOGY AND HISTORY<LI>ASTRONOMY<LI>BOTANY<LI>CONCHOLOGY... THE STUDY OF SHELLS<LI>ENTOMOLOGY... THE STUDY OF INSECTS<LI>GEOLOGY<LI>ICHTHYOLOGY... THE STUDY OF FISH<LI>METEOROLOGY<LI><B>MICROSCOPY</B><LI>NATURAL HISTORY WALKS<LI>ORNITHOLOGY<LI>PHOTOGRAPHY<LI>ZOOLOGY</UL><br><center><a href="#topns">Go back to top of page.</a></center><P><A NAME="activities"></A><B>Activities</B><BR>Talks and lectures are given by members and guest speakers. Field and indoor meetings are held all year round. Observing and recording is undertaken by individuals and groups and the reference collections are constantly updated.<P>A varied programme is available and members may take part in the activities of any or all of the sections. There is a place for those who are interested in attending talks and presentations as well as those keen to undertake research.<P><B>The Microscopy Section</B><BR>Two meetings are held every month, one is a practical session and the other is either a talk or a less formal discussion. Occasional field trips are also arranged.<P><B>Where are meetings held?</B><BR>The Society has its own premises in the centre of Northampton, the Humfrey Rooms where meetings are held. There is a spacious meeting hall equipped with video, slide and film projectors. In addition, there is a photographic dark room, laboratory, basement and storage areas. There is a library and numerous reference and natural history specimen collections. The astronomy section also has an observatory on the outskirts of town.<P><B>How often are meetings held?</B><BR>Most sections meet about twice a month which means that there are usually several meetings taking place each week.<P><br><center><a href="#topns">Go back to top of page.</a></center><p><A NAME="info"></A><B>Where can I get more information?</B><BR>Further information, including subscription rates, can be obtained by writing to the <B>General Secretary</B> at the address shown below, or by coming along to any of our meetings at the Humfrey Rooms where prospective members will be made most welcome.<P>Letters to the <B>Microscopy Section</B> however should be addressed to the <B>Hon. Sec. Microscopy Section</B>, at the address shown below.<P>NORTHAMPTONSHIRE NATURAL HISTORY SOCIETY & FIELD CLUB<BR>THE HUMFREY ROOMS<BR>10 CASTILIAN TERRACE<BR>NORTHAMPTON<BR>NN1 1LD<BR><P><br>


<CENTER><H4><A href="#toprms"> Return to top of Page</a></h4></center>
<center><h3><strong><a href="../../index.html">Go to Microscopy UK Front Page</A><BR>
<a href="../mainpeop.html">Return to People & Clubs selection</A></strong></h3></center>



<h5>
Microscopy UK are offering space in this section for the any amateur 
microscopical society to advertise their activities.
<P>
This service is provided for two reasons. First and foremost, if you live 
near the societies' base, why not join the society and support their activites!
<P>
Secondly, we hope it is of interest to our international readers to see the
scope of the activities provided for the amateur microscopist. We hope 
that Microscopy UK may provide a forum for the friendly exchange of ideas, tips and articles between amateur microscopists worldwide.
<A HREF="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">Please contact us</A> if you 
are involved with an amateur microscopy society anywhere in the world, and 
you have some ideas or contributions to share.
</h5>
<P>


