<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>www.microscopy-uk.org.uk: Biology for Schools -  Sebaceous Gland
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>
<hr>
<h2>www.microscopy-uk.org.uk: Biology for Schools </h2>
<hr>
</center>
<center><h1>Sebaceous Gland in human skin</h1></center>
<img src="sgbig.gif" align=left >

Sebaceous glands are found throughout human skin where they assist the hair follicle in 
maintaining the healthy condition of skin hair. You are observing a vertical section
of human skin taken from just below the surface. 
<p>
Sebaceous glands produce an oil called <strong>sebum</strong>, whick keeps the skin hair
supple and waterproof. The duct of the gland is shown <strong>-{3}</strong>. Below this,
it is possible to see cells breaking down and releasing the sebum <strong>-{1}.</strong>
<p>
At the base of the gland, complete cells can be seen with their nuclei 
intact <strong>-{2}.</strong> These glands are most numerous on the head,
face, chest and back of humans.
<p>

<H3>
<center>
<a href="../mainscol.html#mammal">Return to School Section</A>
</h3>
</center>

<HR>

<P>
<center><H5> Please report any errors to:  <a href="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">The Editor</A></H5></center>

