<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE : Root fillings - teeth </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center><img src="../images/nitemar1.gif" alt=""></center>
<p>
<center>
<h2><I>Welcome to the <b>dark side</b> of Micscape and microscopy. Hold on tight to
the arms of your seat, get the smelling salts (or better still - a glass of brandy) ready,
for we are about to experience...  A Nightmare on Mic Street</I></h2>
<h4><i>Part 1: The root of the problem.</i><br>
by Maurice Smith.</h4>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
<br>
<h3>What fills us with fear?</h3>
For some it is the thought of going to the dentist, for others it is spiders, injections,
or the fear of madness or going blind. The microscope in its various disguises can help us
examine these nightmares close-up. In this mini series, I will take you month by month, through
some of our common nightmares. <i>Did you think Microscopy was about quiet, studious, safe things?</i>
I hope not. 'Scoping' can take us nearer to beauty or closer to the savage truth of reality. For our 
first example, let us consider that good old torturer we've come to know and <i>love</i> - the dentist... 
<p>
<b>The Phantom</b><br>
Day by day we hack, chop, and grind away at our food. When we are young it is more a case of sweet things which invisibly 
contribute to the damage of
<img src="../images/nitemar2.gif" alt="" hspace=12 align=right>
our teeth. Gradual decay inevitably leads us to the dentist to get things patched up.
As we grow older our teeth become more brittle. We may peek in the bathroom mirror and pride ourselves on having clean straight teeth,
but things look quite different when seen at 50x to 100x magnification, as <b>(Fig.1)</b>
shows. You can see the hair-line crack in the enamel of the tooth above the reference point <b>(A)</b> and the chipped edge
to the right - <b>B</b>. In fact, this image was taken of my front teeth just after I had finished having a complete
overhaul of my teeth and gums.
<p>
Most of us can face an occasional bit of 'drilling' and 'filling' but there is a single phrase 
which is guaranteed to strike terror into the hearts of the bravest... <i>a root filling</i>.
<p>
<b>The final solution</b><br>
There comes a time when there is little left to fill. The advance of decay attacks the living heart of the tooth and it is doomed.
Or is it? After all - it's only the nerve screaming at us that the rot has gone too far. Why not just take it out? The nightmare begins!
We stare at the ceiling waiting... searching for that invading drill to hit the soft spot and <i> touch the nerve </i>.
<p>
<b>Fortunately, modern methods practised by a good dentist, should result in little discomfort and no real pain at all.</b> I have often wondered
what was actually involved in this 'seemingly' final solution. Last time I went down the dentist, I took the time to find out. I bet you 
would love to know too. No..? Too late. I am about to show you!
<p>
<b>A Microscope in disguise</b><br>
Perhaps it's cheating a bit to call the dentist's x-ray camera a disguised microscope but through combining digital sampling techniques
with computers, it is possible to do much more with the tiny x-ray pictures. The next time your dentist sticks a mini x-ray plate in your
mouth and asks you to hold still while he puts on his lead-lined apron, you may well remember the following images. 

<img src="../images/nitemar3.gif" alt="" hspace=12 align=left>

To understand what a root-filling is, we first need to study the nerve cavity (pulp) and root of a comparatively healthy tooth. In <b>(Fig.2)</b>
you can see an x-ray image of several teeth. Most of them have been capped with man-made material. Observe the pulp indicated by <b>(A)</b> deep inside
the healthy tooth. The dark patch along with the fine dark lines running up into the root and jaw represents the lifeline to the tooth. Here, the blood
vessels and nerve endings serve the whole tooth. It is when decay penetrates this region beneath the outer enamel and dentine, that real pain begins.
To perform a root filling, the dentist must evacuate this area of decayed tooth <i>and</i> the living nerves and vessels, then fill the cavity with alloy, resin,
or pure metal such as gold.
<p>
<b>Getting to the point</b><br>
<img src="../images/nitemar4.gif" alt="" hspace=12 align=right>
The dentist's drill should have little difficulty removing the decay and entering the soft cavity (pulp) but how are the fine canals
containing the vessels and nerves to be emptied of their contents without leaving debris behind that could lead to problems?
Easy - <b>rake them out</b> - or said more accurately: put fine metal wire rasps down the nerve canals and <i>scrape</i> them out.
You can see in <b>(Fig.3)</b> two such tiny tools inserted through the exposed pulp and up into the two nerve canals. Although this image
has been reduced in size you can just see the zig-zagged edge of the tool indicated by <b>(A)</b>.
<p>
What's that you say? A bit too small to see properly. Okay, here's another one then <b>(Fig.4).</b> The tooth here is a different one. It has only
<img src="../images/nitemar5.gif" alt="" hspace=12 align=left>
a single root and nerve/blood vessel canal. The slender rasp, pushed deep into the tooth, is indicated by <b>(B)</b>. Above this you can see 
another tooth which has been filled; evident by the bright white chunk of alloy embedded in its crown <b>(A)</b>. Below the filling, a dark
line runs centrally down to the root of the tooth. This is a normal nerve/blood vessel canal still alive and serving the tooth. As a final point to
mention: once the pulp, nerve (and the blood vessels) are destroyed or removed, the tooth itself effectively dies but remains usable. In some cases
it may turn black; this discolouration is due to any remaining pulp tissue (blood cells etc.) left in the tooth system. If this is totally removed then
discolouration should not ensue - (enamel itself having no life of its own).
<p>
<br>
<i>Note: my thanks to Jack Grennan B.D.Sc. for his kind help in preparing this article.</i>
<br>
<center>
<h3><i>Drop in next month - if you dare - for another ...<br>
Nightmare on Mic Street!
</I></h3>
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<br>
<br>

<center>
<H3>
<A HREF="../../index.html">Microscopy UK Front Page</A><br>
<A HREF="../indexmag.html">Micscape Magazine</A><br>
<A HREF="../libindex.html">Article Library</A><br>
</H3>
</center>

<P>
<hr>
<center>
<H5>Please report any errors to: <em><A HREF="mailto:dave@diwalk.demon.co.uk">The Micscape Magazine Editor</A></em></H5>
</center>

<ul>
<h6>&COPY;www.microscopy-uk.org.uk and their contributors. Originally published in <font size=2><a href="../indexmag.html">&reg;Micscape Magazine</A></font>,<br> the official web
magazine of <font size=2> <a href="../../index.html">Microscopy UK</A> - 'Home' of Amateur Microscopy on the Web!</font></h6>
</ul>


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B19-58</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA060-000332-B013-109</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.microscopy-uk.org.uk:80/mag/articles/kombucha.html 194.88.132.107 19970115054041 text/html 17794
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 05:46:39 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.5
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Microscopy-uk / MICSCAPE Article - Kombucha Tea</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#dddddd" LINK="#B900ED" VLINK="#BC003F">
<center><img src="../images/komtit.gif" width=576 height=237></center>
<p>
<em>
<strong>Introduction</strong><br>
An overview of an ancient  'homebrew' activity which has been carried out in peasant households throughout the Eastern World for many centuries. As a kind of health insurance/cure-all medicine, its consumption has been spreading across the planet,  hitting America where it was immediately embraced, hyped and revered by millions, and it now seems to be gaining popularity in Britain. As written by a <strong>VERY newly</strong> enlightened enthusiast with only limited experience of brewing the beverage and  the information she has gleaned from the internet and a publication called <strong>'KOMBUCHA - The Miracle Fungus' by Harald W. Tietze.</strong> The views expressed at the end of the article are personal, and any inaccuracies in the 'science' must be forgiven! </em>
<p>
<strong>The Legend</strong><br>
Tea drinking originated in China and Japan more than 2000 years ago. The legend of Bodhidharma tells of how during seven years of meditation he dozed off. When he awoke he was so ashamed of himself that he cut off his eyelids and tossed them to the ground. Where they fell two beautiful shrubs sprouted - the first tea plants. This begs the question: if two shrubs sprouted where the eyelids fell, what bodily part would you need to toss to the ground to give rise to something as slimy and (frankly) unattractive as a KOMBUCHA culture!?
<p>

<center><H3>Well, what is it and what does it actually look like?</h3></center>

 <strong>"Let's see if I can show you. It's in here... somewhere!"</strong>
<p><img src="../images/kompota.jpg" border=1 width=200 height=162 align=left hspace=8>
It is a colony of bacteria and yeast living together symbiotically in a matrix of mycelium-like threads. The overall appearance is that of a mushroom (hence its misnomer popularly adopted by most people) covering the entire surface of its life-giving medium and taking on the boundary shape of the container it is living in. Its mature thickness is 8 - 10mm or so, and  the colour varies, according to what type of tea it is brewed on, from pure white when grown on green tea to a caramel brown when grown on black tea. 
<p>
The important components are apparently the tropical yeasts <em>Schizosaccharomyces pombe, Saccharomycodes ludwigii</em> and <em>Pichia fermentans</em>, but the most important of all is the slimy vinegar bacteria <em>Acetobacter xylinium</em>, which creates a slippery mass out of cellulose in the symbiotic process, holding the whole colony together in a mat. The three images below show (at 400x), from left to right,
<strong>the bacteria cells (isolated), the yeast cells (isolated), and a yeast colony.</strong>
<p>
<center><img src="../images/kombact.jpg" border=1 width=117 height=161> <img src="../images/komyeast.jpg" border=1 width=117 height=161> <img src="../images/komycol.jpg" border=1 width=117 height=161></center><BR><BR>
This tough zooglea cannot readily be torn with the fingers when handling, so if it needs to be re-shaped for any reason (ie to be cultured in a smaller container, for example) scissors are needed to cut it with. Its upper surface is smoother than the underside which has a more slimy, loose texture, often with dark thread-like 'veins' and streamers hanging down. Sometimes gas pockets form as on bladder wrack seaweed which help it to stay afloat, although it seems to be able to function perfectly well if it sinks to the bottom of the liquid as no light is needed.
<p>
<strong>Where does the name come from?</strong><br>

It is known by many names; from many of them it can be seen that the origins lie in the East - China, Japan, Manchuria, Russia and India. It is known as Combucha (Japanese word for tea sponge or tea fungus), Kombucha (Germanized form of the Japanese name and used internationally), Tea Kvass (Russian), Olinka (Bohemian and Moravian monasteries), Kargasok tea (the Japanese brought the culture from Kargasok, Russia), Manchurian Mushroom (Manchuria) as well as many other names. According to some literature it was introduced to Japan by the Korean doctor Kombu in 414BC, and became known then as 'Kombu's cha'.
<p>

<strong>What is its purpose in life?</strong><br>

Well, it appears to have been put on this planet to serve mankind (isn't everything!?), producing by a lactic acid fermentation process a delicious beverage rich in beneficial acids, vitamins, amino acids, enzymes, antibiotic, antiseptic and detoxifying substances and a small amount of alcohol (0 - 1%).
<p>
When utilised by the human body this ferment has an <strong>immune system boosting and detoxifying effect</strong>; it does not target specific body organs but influences the entire organism positively through metabolic stabilisation and pH balancing. It enables any toxins present (built up over many years of absorbing contaminants such as preservatives, fungicides, pesticides and insecticides in our foods, air pollution and stress-related toxins) to become water-soluble and kidney-manageable through their conjugation with one of the constituents in particular, glucuronic acid. 
<p>
This acid binds the toxins in the liver which in turn sends them to the kidneys for elimination. Toxins bound in this way are not able to be reabsorbed by the intestines or the urinary system but are instead safely eliminated with the urine (they would otherwise be stored 'locked-up' out of harms way giving rise to excess fatty tissues and cellulite). In a healthy body large amounts of glucuronic acid are naturally produced by the liver for the purpose of carrying out this detoxifying task anyway, but if the liver is not 100% happy with its lot and perhaps suffering the effects of contaminated nourishment, (drugs, booze, junk foods) and the by-products of twentieth century stress, it may be necessary to obtain a top-up in the glucuronic acid department by way of drinking Kombucha tea.
<p>

<strong>"Ah, got it at last!"</strong>

<strong>What happens when I drink it?</strong><P>
<img src="../images/komlifta.jpg" border=1 width=200 height=162 align=left hspace=8> 
Firstly, you will probably enjoy the taste which ranges from a sweetish, rather fragrant, lightly tea-flavoured drink when immature, through to a less-sweet, slightly tart sparkling apple wine flavour when more fully brewed. This is the stage at which most people consume and enjoy the tea. Eventually it takes on  a more acid, fizzy, cider vinegar nature the longer it is brewed, finally reaching a strong vinegar stage at which it can apparently be used as such. As the overall effect on the consumer is primarily one of bodily 'flushing' and detoxification, the benefits can manifest themselves in a thousand different ways according to your particular bodily imbalances. This leads to a myriad of claims made by consumers, from preventing/curing cancer to eliminating wrinkles and restoring grey hair to its original colour! 
<p>
Don't be put off by these apparently unlikely claims, reflect instead on the possibility that a strengthened immune system might be more able to fight off or combat diseases more readily than a body weakened and burdened with pollutants. If the internal environment is non-welcoming to diseases like cancer, then perhaps they will not be able to invade and flourish. <em>(As for the wrinkle and grey hair claims, I am still desperately evaluating..!)</em>
<p>

<strong>How do I brew my own?</strong><br>
<dl>
<dt>Firstly, a few tips:-
<p>
<dd>a)	It is a simple process requiring little or no special equipment, although I have found that one particular (fairly expensive) item does help in my case. The temperature of the medium ideally needs to be kept constant somewhere between 23 and 28 degrees C, and as my house is devoid of an airing cupboard which usually satisfies this requirement, I use an aquarium heater actually in the fermentation vessel itself.
<p>
<dd>b)	The ratio between the surface area exposed to the air and the volume of the liquid effects the nature of the resulting tea to some extent, ie the greater the surface area of a small amount of liquid the more acid the tea and the more quickly it matures. If you want a milder Kombucha I recommend you use a vessel such as a bread crock which holds around  5 - 7 litres (10 - 12 pints) with a diameter of about 22mm (8").
<P>
<dd>c)	No metal should come into contact with the colony or its medium, therefore it should be brewed in glass if possible and no metal spoons or utensils used for measuring any of the ingredients. 
</dl>
<p>
<strong>Ingredients:-</strong><br>
(multiply up to fit your particular vessel)<br>
<ul>
<li>2 litres (3 to 4 pints) water, preferably filtered
<li>160 grams (5oz) white granulated sugar*
<li>2-4 teaspoons (or teabags) tea**
<li>1 healthy Kombucha culture
<li>2 tablespoons cider vinegar 
(only necessary for the very first brew if no mature tea is<br>
available. If it is then add 200 mls [1/3 pint] in order to
acidify the medium slightly)<br>

</ul>
<em><strong>*White granulated sugar</strong> really is the type Kombucha prefers even though you may be loathe to use it. By the time you consume the tea the sugar should have been completely utilised and therefore you won't actually be consuming it yourself anyway, so for the wellbeing of the colony  it is better to use it at this stage. As you get more experienced with the brewing process you can experiment with other types including honey if you want to, keeping a spare Kombucha in reserve in case the original doesn't thrive.
</em>
<p>
<em><strong>**The type of tea</strong> used can be black or green, although I have found that when using green the flavour is rather bland. The colony is apparently happier on black as it provides a more nutritious solution, but again experimentation can be interesting with all sorts of teas including herbal as long as they are relatively low in oils which may interfere with the microbial growth. The terms 'black' and 'green' teas relate to the method of drying after picking, black tea being 'fermented' (a rather misleading term simply meaning that the tea is spread out in a layer 10cm thick in a damp room with a low ventilation rate and a controlled temperature, and oxidation allowed to convert the juices in the leaf enzymically). This produces the characteristic blackening effect and stronger flavour, whereas green tea is briefly steamed after the 18 hour wilting process to destroy the remaining enzymes and then dried slowly at a lower temperature; in this way it retains the green colour and has a milder and more delicate flavour.
</em>
<P>

<strong>Method:-</strong><br>
<ul>
<li>Boil the water and pour onto the tea and sugar, stir and leave to brew for 15 minutes. 
<li>Strain into the brewing vessel and allow to cool to room temperature.
<li>Add the vinegar or Kombucha tea, stir thoroughly
<li>Lay the colony onto the surface <strong>smooth side up.</strong>
<li>Cover with muslin or a loosely-woven cloth and place the vessel in place that can maintain a steady temperature of somewhere between 23 and 28 degrees C.
<li>Leave undisturbed if curiosity will allow, and after 6-9 days of fermentation taste the liquid to see if it has reached the required acidity. 
</ul>
Experience will enable you to determine the time needed with your particular set of conditions and flavour requirements, but remember that <strong>the more 'zingy' and acidic it is, the more beneficial acids there are present. </strong>Strain (do not overstrain or you will remove the yeast which is rich in the B vitamins) and bottle and store in the fridge.  Be sure to leave a good headspace in the bottles as the fermentation activity will continue at a reduced rate giving the sparkling quality to the drink. Check for and release excess pressure periodically.
<p>
 The colony can immediately be used to brew another batch, or stored in the fridge in some of its tea until required. It will be found to have replicated itself in the form of another layer ABOVE the original; this can be separated and used for another brew, stored in the fridge in reserve or passed on to someone else. 

<p>
Eventually you will be overrun by these offspring and may have to resort to throwing them out, but before you do please consider registering with the Kombucha Network at the address at the end of this piece if you are prepared to supply other potential K-brewers with colonies through the post. The recommended daily dose appears to vary widely, but a wineglassful three times a day would seem to be a sensible starting point. The first is best on an empty stomach before breakfast and the other two as an aperitif before lunch and dinner. 
<p>

<img src="../images/kompana.jpg" border=1 width=200 height=163 align=right hspace=8>
<strong>Here is a good look at the 'daughter' of my first culture. It might look a bit alien and repulsive to some of you,  but just remember what your intestines or heart looks like, and of course - as ugly as these are - they do a pretty good job, eh?</strong>
<p>
<br>
<center><h3>A few personal thoughts:-</h3></center>
<em>
In addition to any health benefits derived from Kombucha tea drinking itself I believe the whole process of brewing the beverage is a therapeutic one. The paraphernalia of obtaining your first culture, preparing its medium,  making sure it lives happily in a pollution-free environment, checking its temperature periodically, waiting for exactly the right moment to harvest the tea,  (and if you are an American, singing to it or playing classical music to it!) etc, probably gives the 'owner' a feeling of well-being and achievement which adds to the stress-relief and subsequent benefits gained. The added bonus at the end of the process is that it rewards you not only with a quantity of the delicious elixir but also produces a 'baby' ( - ahhhhhhhhhh, how sweeeeet!) to keep or give away, so there is also a sharing element which gives rise to even MORE feel-good factor!
<p>
Who cares how it works - there are testimonials from around the world describing how 'miracle cures' have been effected as a result of  friendships with Kombucha.  Perhaps the placebo effect is coming into play, or possibly other health-improving offshoots such as the fact that you shouldn't smoke in the vicinity of the colony as it inhibits its growth - possibly encouraging you to give up smoking - what could be better for the human body than removing this particular form of pollution whether it be by abstinence or glucuronic acid absorption?!
<P>
The clean semi-tartness of the flavour possibly sharpens the taste buds so that you might steer away from over sweetened drinks and foods over time - that can only be beneficial too. Drinking it on an empty stomach with up to 1% alcohol and in the presence of dissolved carbon dioxide probably does as much good as anything in the light of the current trend for copying the red wine drinking habits of the French to try to achieve their nationally low heart disease rates! However it does whatever it does I just know that I enjoy brewing and drinking it and that I shall continue to do so. Is it taking over the kitchens of the world, has it already penetrated my brain and judgement..?!
<P>
<img src="../images/kombucha.jpg" border=1 width=271 height=202 align=left>

What else now... Oh! Yes: one of the lads here (Andrew) at Microscopy-UK 
stuck a sample into the SEM! This is what it looks like really close-up. You can see the yeast and the bacteria cells in this terrific image. That's it for now. I'll see if I can talk one of the boys into doing a bit more research into the microscopic 
composition of the Kombucha fungus, and follow up with another article on it next month. Bye, till then... <strong>Polly.</strong>
</em>
<br clear>
<p>
<strong>Credits:-</strong><br>
Text by 'Polly' Syred<br>
Images by Andrew Syred and Maurice Smith.<br>
<p>

<strong>Further Info:-</strong><br>

The Kombucha Network,<br>
PO Box 1887,<br>
BATH, BA2 8YA<br>

<p>
Also, try entering a key-word search on one of the web engines like Lycos!
For example, enter: <em>kombucha</em> and see how much is available!
<p>
 <strong>
One last word: as with any home brewing or food-making, cleanliness is important.
Ensure everything is washed properly, including your hands. If during the fermenting period,
the tea does not smell vinegary but instead smells foul, it is probably best to chuck it away.
It is unlikely for the tea to become infected by foreign bacteria or protozoa simply because
the kombucha creates an acid environment which makes it very difficult for other living things,
microscopic in nature, to survive for very long. </strong>

<p>

<center>
