    <HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>News Summaries</TITLE></HEAD><!-Default-><BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/newsban.map">	<IMG SRC="/MapServe/newsban.gif" WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/news/news.html"><BR>News &amp; Communications</A> | <A HREF="/news/jto/Latest_News.qry?Illicit=True&Alcohol=True&Tobacco=True&General=True">News</A> | <A HREF="/news/releases/Latest_News.qry?PressReleases=True&Summaries=On&Max=7&Last=30">Releases</A>| <A HREF="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/news">Archives</A> | <A HREF="/URLs/JTO/URL_Show.qry?header=news&filter=drugs&Category=Media&Summaries=on">Links</A></FONT><BR></CENTER><p><TABLE WIDTH = "90%" CELLSPACING = "0"><TR><TD WIDTH = "60%"><h2>Soros on Drug Policy</h2></TD><TD></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN = "2"><FONT COLOR = "BLACK">Billionaire philanthropist George Soros, <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPlate/1997-02/02/083L-020297-idx.html">writing in the Feb. 2 edition of the Washington Post</a>, shot back at his critics and pledged to devote even more of his money to the cause of U.S. drug policy reform.<br><br>Soros was heavily criticized by Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse chairman Joseph Califano and federal officials for his support of medical marijuana initiatives in California and Arizona. "I was denigrated in congressional  hearings chaired by Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), and in the New York Times, A.M. Rosenthal went so far as to imply that I represent a new kind of "drug money," Soros noted. "I must reject these accusations. I am not for legalizing hard drugs. I am for a saner drug policy. I am just as concerned about keeping drugs away from my children as any responsible parent. But I firmly believe that the war on drugs is doing more harm to our society than drug abuse itself."<br>     <br>"I have devoted much of my energies and resources over the past two decades to promoting the concept of open society in formerly communist countries. I have  started to pay more attention to my adopted country, the United States, because I feel that the relatively open society we enjoy here is in danger," said Soros. " ... Our drug policies offer a prime example of adverse, unintended consequences. There is perhaps no other field where our public policies have produced an outcome so profoundly at odds with what was intended. But those who are waging a "war on drugs" refuse to recognize this fact. They consider all criticism  subversive. To suggest the possibility that the war on drugs may be self-defeating is tantamount to treason in their eyes. This was confirmed by their reaction to the approval of the drug policy ballot initiatives in <br>California and Arizona."<br><br>"Our first priority should be to discourage children from using drugs. Even marijuana can be harmful to the mental and emotional development of youngsters," wrote Soros. "But demonizing drugs can increase their appeal to adolescents, for whom rebellion is often an important rite of passage to adulthood. And we must be particularly careful not to exaggerate the harmful effects of marijuana because it may undermine the credibility of our warnings about harder drugs."<br>     </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>02/05/1997</TD><TD ALIGN="RIGHT"><b>Source: Join Together Online</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><I>Distributed by <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">Join Together Online</A>.</I></P>    <P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle  ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A></FONT><BR><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="/">http:/