<HEAD>    <TITLE>Funding News</TITLE></HEAD><!-Default-><BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/fundban.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/fundban.gif" WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middleISMAP><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"></A><A HREF="/JTO/funding/funding.html">Funding News</A> | <A HREF="/posting/FundingNews.qry?Last=7&Function=LatestNews&Max=100&Summaries=Off">New?</A>| <A HREF="/posting/FundingNews.qry?function=LatestNews&Max=150&Last=60&ArticleType=2">Grants</A> | <A HREF="/posting/FundingNews.qry?function=LatestNews&Max=150&Last=30&ArticleType=3">Profiles</A>| <A HREF="/posting/FundingNews.qry?function=LatestNews&Max=150&Last=21&ArticleType=1">News & Tips</A> | <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/mny">Archives</A>| <A HREF="/jto/funding/links.html">Links</A></FONT> </CENTER><p><p><TABLE WIDTH = "60%"><TR><TD><h2>Marketing Prevention to Managed Care</h2></TD></TR></TABLE><TABLE WIDTH = "100%"><TR><TD WIDTH = "100%"><FONT COLOR = "BLACK">Managed care organizations (MCOs) have two primary goals -- to deliver services effectively and cheaply, and to reduce the demand for care. The latter provides tremendous opportunity for community-based prevention organizations that learn to market themselves as service providers to local HMOs and other health care companies, according to Michael Stoil, a senior analyst for Conwal Incorporated.<br><br>Conwal recently won a contract from the Ohio Department of Alcohol and Drug Abuse Services (ODADAS) to develop a marketing plan for community-based prevention programs, including AOD and violence prevention groups. While Stoil could not discuss the Ohio project prior to its unveiling at the <a href="mailto:dcoffice@nasadad.org">NASADAD/NPN</a> Prevention Research Conference (to be held Sept. 7 to Sept. 10 in Philadelphia), he spoke generally with Join Together about the challenges and opportunities facing MCOs and community-based groups that address substance abuse and related issues.<br><br>Stoil sees great potential for alliance between managed care and prevention organizations, because they share similar goals. "Managed care is interested in the same activities that lots of community-based organizations produce," Stoil told Join Together. "But the terminology is going to be different and the perspective is going to be different. The buzzwords are going to be behavioral health care and patient self-management."<br><br>A recent survey found that 40 percent of managed care organizations engage in some form of behavioral health promotion, provided in-house or through a contractor. The most prevalent service offering has been smoking cessation and education, but some MCOs also provide classes in stress management, parenting, and domestic violence prevention. <br><br>MCOs also provide alcohol education and adolescent substance abuse prevention classes. But few community-based prevention groups have been able to achieve the success of the <a href="http://www.jointogether.org/posting/FundingNews.qry?function=detail&FundingNews_Aid=627">Gloucester (Mass.) Prevention Network</a>, which has positioned itself as a key service provider for a local MCO. <br><br>Sometimes, notes Stoil, the MCOs corporate culture and mind-set can hinder such alliances. For example, he notes, California's Kaiser Permanente HMO would seem to be a prime target for marketing by community-based prevention groups, except that Kaiser traditionally has developed its own programs rather than contracting with outsiders. Such barriers can be difficult to overcome, but others are self-created by prevention groups themselves and would be well worth challenging, says Stoil. <br><br>"Probably the single largest barrier to marketing services to MCOs is the fear and loathing of managed care," he says. "We need to recognize that managed care is here to stay, and that most community-based HMOs are getting rid of their objectionable elements."<br><br>"Also, prevention groups have a very difficult time in defining their services and outcomes in terms that managed care companies can understand, and justify funding," Stoil adds. "Programs think that they are prevention agencies, but they're not. Prevention is an outcome. What groups do is community outreach and liaison, counseling and education. These are the things that managed care is interested in.<br><br>"Hopefully these activities will lead to prevention, but you can't prove that," says Stoil.<br><br>Stoil also says that there are very few prevention activities that are specific to alcohol and other drugs, and stresses that substance abuse prevention groups need to position themselves as providers of behavioral health promotion services via a holistic public health approach. "The whole point of managed care is to teach self-management and self-care," he states, "so primary prevention is the same thing that managed care wants. There's no reason to sell it as substance abuse prevention."<br><br>Michael Stoil, <a href="mailto:conwal@ix.netcom.com">Conwal Incorporated</a>, 6858 Old Dominion Drive, McLean, VA 22101, (703) 448-2300; fax (703) 448-3089.<br><br></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>02/03/1997</TD><TD ALIGN="RIGHT"><b>Source: </b>Join Together Online</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif" WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP><BR><BR></A><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A></FONT><BR><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="/">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT> </CENTER></BODY>
