<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Hot Issues</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
<BR>
<H1><CENTER>Hot Issues</CENTER>
</H1>


<IMG SRC="/gif/new.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"><B><A HREF="tx&crime/intro.html">Providing Substance Abuse Treatment Reduces Crime</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Addiction is at the heart of much of the crime that plagues our neighborhoods.  Yet state prisons treat only 13.5 percent of offenders with substance abuse problems. Thus, most offenders who need addiction treatment don't receive it and are released from prison back to the community -- still using, still dealing -- to commit further crimes.  This action kit shows how you can  educate residents and the media in your community about the need to join together to provide treatment -- both in prison and out -- for offenders who abuse alcohol and drugs.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE>




<B><A HREF="Alcohol/Alcohol_Index.html">Holiday Drinking and
Driving</A></B>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><BLOCKQUOTE>Alcohol-related crashes are a leading cause of death for young people in
the United States. This holiday season we should take the opportunity to
educate people in our communities about this fact and encourage them to
support prevention efforts to make our roads safer.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT>


<B><A
HREF="reality/intro.html">Reality Check: Helping Parents Talk to Kids
About Marijuana</A></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/gif/reality.gif" ALIGN=right WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="40" BORDER="0"><FONT SIZE="-1">Join Together partners with the <A HREF="http://www.health.org">Center
for Substance Abuse Prevention</A> to bring you CSAP's Reality Check
campaign. Young people are constantly bombarded with conflicting
messages from music, films and television. By informing and educating
adults about the issues that influence marijuana use, they will in turn
be better able to provide young people with information that will help
them make better choices.</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><A HREF="inhalants/Inhalant_Index.html">Inhalant Abuse</A></B>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><BLOCKQUOTE>When we think of drugs, most of us think of marijuana, heroine and cocaine. But today, the new drugs of choice for some kids are common -- but often deadly -- household substances such as white out, glue and paint. This Hot Issue Action Kit focuses on this rising problem. We suggest you use this material to raise public awareness in March, which is National Inhalant Awareness Month.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT> 


<B><A HREF="Prevention/Prevention_Index.html">Prevention
Works!</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Across the country community groups are making great strides in preventing alcohol and drug abuse and the related problems that result. But despite these successes, more remains to be done. In fact, two recent studies suggest that some of the gains we have made in reducing substance abuse are beginning to lessen. This means that we must strengthen the message that prevention works and encourage all sectors of society to join in community-wide efforts.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="TxWorks/TxWorks_Index.html">Treatment Works &amp; We Can
Prove It</A></B>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><BLOCKQUOTE>Several recent credible studies have found that providing substance abuse treatment is a cost-effective investment for communities.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT>


<B><A HREF="DomesticViolence/DV_Index.html">Domestic Violence and
Substance
Abuse</A></B>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><BLOCKQUOTE>Much national attention is focused on domestic violence these days. Many women who have silently suffered batterings by their mates are now beginning to speak out about their ordeals and encouraging others to do the same. What has not gotten as much media attention, however, is the fact that up to 50 percent of all spousal abuse cases can be linked to alcohol or drug abuse. You can help to get this message out. With the material provided in this kit, you can help reporters understand the connection between domestic violence and substance abuse and to realize how providing substance abuse treatment under health care reform is an essential step in reducing domestic violence.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT> 

<B><A HREF="Marijuana/Marijuana_Index.html">Increase in Marijuana Use
Among Young People</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Marijuana use is on the rise among teenagers across the country. Several recent studies have alerted us to this worrisome fact. Also cause for concern is the fact that anti-drug attitudes among young people are declining. Many high school students associate less danger with smoking marijuana today than their counterparts did several years ago. These findings are especially alarming since the use of marijuana--the most widely used drug--often leads to the use of other, more dangerous drugs.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="Homeless/Homeless_Index.html">Homelessness and Substance
Abuse</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Today, more than seven million people in the United States live on the streets or in shelters because they do not have a home. And nearly half of homeless people suffer from alcohol or drug addictions. These men and women live in our communities. You can help to reduce homelessness by making sure that all Americans have access to the health care they need -- including adequate substance abuse services.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="HIV/HIV_Index.html">HIV-Infection and Substance
Abuse</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">You probably know someone who is HIV-positive -- one in every 250 people in the United States has contracted this virus that ultimately leads to AIDS. This virus affects about one million people nationwide. And a number of men and women with HIV-infection have substance abuse problems that put them at risk for HIV -- either by injecting drugs or having unprotected sex. You can help many more people from becoming a statistic by making sure that all Americans have access to the health care they need including adequate substance abuse services.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="Elderly/Elderly_Index.html">Substance Abuse and Older
Americans</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Many people think of substance abuse as a problem that affects only young people. However, many older people also suffer from alcohol and drug addictions. In fact, senior citizens consume a disproportionate amount of prescription and over-the-counter drugs and have a higher risk of becoming dependent on these substances. And some older people drink heavily because they are lonely or bored. It is important that we recognize the dangers of substance abuse among older Americans and offer help to those who need it.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="National_Survey/into.html">Using the 1995 National Survey of Communities</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Join Together's third national survey of community anti-substance abuse efforts, conducted July through October, 1995, alerts us to the disturbing fact that sustance abuse problems continue to rise in many communities across the country. With the final version of the survey due in December, this action kit will give you a head-start on using these national findings to raise public awareness about substance abuse problems in your community.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="Tobacco/Tobacco_Index.html">Youth Access to Tobacco
</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT SIZE="-1">Although it is illegal in all states to sell cigarettes to anyone under 18-years-old, kids have easy access to tobacco products. Each day, three thousand youngsters in the United States become regular smokers. On an annual basis, this is about one million youth. And despite our efforts to get the message out that smoking is hazardous to kids' health, the fact is that tobacco use by kids continues to rise. In the past three years, smoking among eighth graders has increased by 30 percent. This finding sends a warning bell that we must reinvigorate our efforts to keep kids from using tobacco products.<BR> The <A HREF="Tobacco/Survey_Results.html">results</A> from our nationwide survey are available now.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><A HREF="Binge/Binge_Index.html">Binge Drinking on College
Campuses</A></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="Binge/beer.gif" ALIGN=right WIDTH="38" HEIGHT="50"
NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0"><FONT SIZE="-1">As college students head back to school, many of them will be affected by a serious problem: binge drinking. Today, nearly half of all college students binge drink. This drinking leads to a number of problems on campuses, such as violence, rapes, sexually-transmitted diseases and suicides. And even though it is illegal for anyone under 21 to consume alcohol, many minors getting served anyway. This is a pervasive problem not only for college communities but for our nation's future leadership.</FONT></BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><A HREF="/JTO/issues/Awaremonth/month.html">April: Alcohol Awareness
Month</A></B>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><BLOCKQUOTE>Sponsored by the National Council on Alcoholism and Drug Dependence, Inc. (NCADD) since 1987, this month-long campaign encourages local communities to take a closer look at how drinking -- America's number one drug problem -- affects young people. View, download or print a variety of campaign tools.</BLOCKQUOTE></FONT>

