<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>How to Use this Kit</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>Providing Substance Abuse Treatment Reduces Crime</CENTER>
</H2>



Addiction is at the heart of much of the crime that plagues our neighborhoods. Did you know that 60 to 70 percent of state prisoners have a history of substance use or abuse? Yet state prisons treat only 13.5 percent of these offenders. Thus, most offenders who need addiction treatment don't receive it and are released from prison back to the community -- still using, still dealing -- to commit further crimes and threaten our well-being and that of our children. <BR><BR>

That's why it is crucial that our communities provide treatment for offenders who need it. The nation's new drug czar General Barry McCaffrey, recently recognized this fact. <B>"We are not going to solve the nations crime problems by putting another million in jail"</B>, he said when he released the 1996 new drug strategy in early May. In fact, one of the five points in the 10-year strategy is to provide alcohol and drug treatment for prisoners with addictions. <BR><BR>

This goal collaborates with the recommendations of a recent Join Together policy panel that spent the past year examining how the criminal justice system deals with substance abuse. The panel's report, <A HREF="/JTO/policy/panels/cj/title.html">Fixing a Failing System</A>, recommends that police, courts, probation officers, treatment providers, and community groups work together to ensure that treatment and follow-up care are accessible for offenders with addictions. <BR><BR>

This latest Hot Issue Action Kit shows how you can use the panel's findings to educate residents and the media in your community about the need to join together to provide treatment -- both in prison and out -- for offenders who abuse alcohol and drugs. By partnering with the courts, probation and parole to make adequate treatment available, communities can reduce some of the related crime -- like assaults, burglaries, drug dealing, and drunk driving crashes that occur in our communities. <BR><BR>

While this panel focused its work on the adult population, you may want to also make the case for substance abuse treatment for juvenile offenders with addictions in your community. Many different sectors can join together around this problem and help devise effective alternatives to treat addictions and keep kids out of jail.<BR><BR>

<B>Included in this Monthly Action Kit you will find:</B>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>A <A HREF="fact.html">Fact Sheet</A> to help you make your case for treatment in the criminal justice system.<BR><BR>

	<LI><A HREF="others.html">What Others Have Done</A> to give you some ideas about alternative treatment options that have been successful in reducing recidivism.<BR><BR>

	<LI><A HREF="you.html">What You Can Do</A> to determine the relationship between crime and substance abuse in your community and to get residents to support treatment options.<BR><BR>

	<LI><A HREF="pitch.html">Sample Pitch Letter</A> to interest your local newspaper in looking at the link between crime and substance abuse.<BR><BR>

	<LI><A HREF="oped.html">Sample Op-Ed</A> to make the case for treating substance abusing offenders.<BR><BR>

	<LI><A HREF="resource.html">Resources</A> you can contact to learn more about the crime and substance abuse connection.<BR><BR>

	<LI><A HREF="panel.html">How to Convene a Local Policy Panel</A> to give you steps to convene a panel in your community.
</UL>


For more information contact <A HREF="mailto:diane@jointogether.org">Diane Barry</A> or <A HREF="mailto:lisa@jointogether.org">Lisa Falk</A> at (617) 437-1500.


<P><CENTER><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> </CENTER>
