<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>How to Use this Kit</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>CSAP's Reality Check Campaign</CENTER>
</H2>
Join Together partners with the <A HREF="http://www.health.org">Center for Substance Abuse Prevention</A>
to bring you CSAP's Reality Check campaign. This nationwide campaign, launched
in late June by Donna Shalala, Secretary of Health and Human Services, was
created to help parents talk to their kids about the dangers of marijuana
use.<BR>
<BR>
Young people are constantly bombarded with conflicting messages from music,
films and television. By informing and educating adults about the issues
that influence marijuana use, they will in turn be better able to provide
young people with information that will help them make better choices.<BR>
<BR>
<B>THE CAMPAIGN THEME:</B> Marijuana is a drug. Help Our Kids Understand.<BR>
<BR>
<B>CAMPAIGN GOALS: </B>Increase awareness; Help young people refuse marijuana
or quit if they already use; Involve adults caregivers and mentors; Change
pro-use norms.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCOPE OF THE PROBLEM:</B> As you surely know, marijuana use has been
gaining popularity recently. In just one year, the number of eighth graders
who use marijuana in the United States has doubled. That's why, NOW, more
than ever, it is crucial for parents to talk to their kids and discourage
them from using this drug. Unfortunately, many young people do not consider
marijuana to be dangerous.<BR>
<BR>
But contrary to this belief, the danger is there and it is getting worse,
especially as increasingly stronger blends of marijuana are crossbred in
this country. Even more alarming, some current forms of marijuana are &quot;spiked&quot;
with other illicit drugs like cocaine, crack cocaine, PCP and even embalming
fluid.<BR>
<BR>
<B>WHAT YOUR COMMUNITY CAN DO:</B> It is important to get this message out
to parents, and to help them feel comfortable about sharing these facts
with their kids. Some parents, who may have tried marijuana themselves when
they were younger, may not feel that they are in any position to discuss
this serious issue with their children. Nonetheless, it is crucial that
they find ways to start a dialogue about the danger of drugs with their
children.<BR>
<BR>
How can you help parents in your community keep their kids safe and drug-free?
This latest Monthly Action Kit provides you with the highlights of CSAP's
campaign and some tips on how to tailor it locally.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Included in this Monthly Action Kit you will find:</B> 
<UL>
<LI><B><A HREF="message.html">How to Get the Message Out</A> </B>to your
own community.<BR>
<BR>


<LI><B><A HREF="do.html">What Local Groups Can Do</A> </B>for specific community
activities suggestions.<BR>
<BR>

<LI>A <B><A HREF="facts.html">Fact Sheet</A></B> to use in your community
awareness and outreach efforts.<BR>
<BR>

<LI><B><A HREF="resources.html">Resources</A></B> you can contact for more
information about marijuana use.<BR>
<BR>

<LI><B><A HREF="pitch.html">Sample Pitch Letter</A> </B>to interest your
local newspaper in looking at this issue anew.<BR>
<BR>

<LI><B><A HREF="psa.html">Public Service Announcements</A> </B>you may freely
distribute to local radio stations. <BR>
<BR>

<LI><B><A HREF="oped.html">Sample Op-Ed</A> </B>to raise local awareness
about this serious problem.<BR>
<BR>


<LI><B><A HREF="parents.html">What Parents Should Know</A></B>, an information
sheet designed especially for parent education about marijuana.
</UL>
For more information about Join Together or our Monthly Action Kits contact
<A HREF="mailto:diane@jointogether.org">Diane Barry</A> or <A HREF="mailto:lisa@jointogether.org">Lisa
Falk</A> at (617) 437-1500. To receive CSAP's complete Reality Check Campaign
kit or for more information about marijuana, call the National Clearinghouse
for Alcohol and Drug Information at (800) 729-6686 or check out the Reality
Check web page at <A HREF="http://www.health.org/reality">http://www.health.org/reality</A>.
<BR>
