<TITLE>Domestic Violence and Substance Abuse</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<BR>



<H2>Domestic Violence and Substance Abuse</H2></center>



<P>Much national attention is focused on domestic violence these days. Many women who have silently suffered batterings by their mates are now beginning to speak out about their ordeals and encouraging others to do the same. What has not gotten as much media attention, however, is the fact that up to 50 percent of all spousal abuse cases can be linked to alcohol or drug abuse. You can help to get this message out. With the material provided in this kit, you can help reporters understand the connection between domestic violence and substance abuse and to realize how providing substance abuse treatment under health care reform is an essential step in reducing domestic violence.


<P>To help you inform the public and key groups in your community about the need for substance abuse treatment to reduce domestic violence, we have provided you with the following:


<UL>
	<LI>a <A HREF="DV_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> with statistics on the problem and how treatment would help;

	<LI>a <A HREF="DV_Press.html">Sample Press Release</A> and a <A HREF="DV_Op-Ed.html">Sample Op-Ed</A> article you or your board members can revise and send to your local newspaper;

	<LI>a list of <A HREF="DV_Resources.html">Resources</A> you can contact for more information on the problem, as well as tips on how to help you get other groups to join your efforts.
</UL>


<P><B>How to use these tools:</B>


<ol>
<li>Use the <A HREF="DV_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> to interest the media in this topic. -Use the statistics and some local ones of your own to help newspaper, television and radio  reporters to better understand the issue of domestic violence and its relationship to alcohol and drug abuse.

<ul>
<li>Visit local women's shelters and find victims of domestic violence who are willing to &quot;tell their stories&quot; to the media. Offer local reporters a list of area shelters and resources they can run with an article on this issue to guide other victims to seek help.


<li>Arrange an Editorial Board meeting with your local newspaper and use the statistics to show the link between alcohol and drug abuse and domestic violence and the need to treat both problems simultaneously.  Invite someone who runs a group for batterers join you. Also have a spokesperson  from your local emergency room talk about the victims he or she has seen and the scope of the  problem in your area. Include a treatment provider to talk about how treatment must encompass the  addiction as well as the battering. Encourage the newspaper to do a series or insert about this serious issue, which affects a large portion of its readership.


<li>Write a Letter to the Editor or an Op-Ed (<A HREF="DV_Op-Ed.html">see sample</A> included) using key facts to show the correlation between substance abuse and domestic violence and stressing the need for treatment.
</ul>

<li>Use the <A HREF="DV_Press.html">Sample Press Release</A> to get press coverage. -Revise the release by adding local examples of victims of domestic violence in your area.  Send the release to reporters at your local paper with your name and phone number listed as the  contact. Call to follow up. Be prepared to suggest story ideas, resources and other contact persons on this topic.


<li>Use the <A HREF="DV_Resources.html">Resource Sheet</A> to illustrate the scope of the problem and expand your coalition. 
<ul>
<li>Call the resources listed to gather more statistics on domestic violence, both locally and nationally. See how your community fits into the national picture.

<li>Get these groups to join your coalition.
</ul>
</ol>
<p><br><hr>

<CENTER>
<A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0"ISMAP ></A>
