<TITLE>INCREASE IN MARIJUANA USE AMONG YOUNG PEOPLE</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>



<H2>INCREASE IN MARIJUANA USE AMONG YOUNG PEOPLE</H2>
</center>

<P>Marijuana use is on the rise among teenagers across the country. Several recent studies have alerted us to this worrisome fact. Also cause for concern is the fact that anti-drug attitudes among young people are declining. Many high school students associate less danger with smoking marijuana today than their counterparts did several years ago. These findings are especially alarming since the use of marijuana--the most widely used drug--often leads to the use of other, more dangerous drugs.  Therefore, we must increase our efforts to prevent substance abuse -- especially among young people. To help you make this point, we have enclosed the following information:


<UL>
	<LI>a <A HREF="Marijuana_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> that shows the risks of marijuana use and includes the latest findings from several timely studies that reveal that marijuana use is on the rise among teenagers;

	<LI>a <A HREF="Marijuana_Pitch.nclk">Pitch Letter</A> to alert reporters to the fact that marijuana use is up among teens and to ask them to take a closer look at the problem in your area; and

	<LI>a <A HREF="Marijuana_Op-Ed.nclk">Sample Op-Ed</A> you can send to your local newspaper -- either as is, or with some local examples added.
</UL>


<P>


<P><H3>HOW TO USE THIS ACTION KIT:</H3>


<OL>
	<LI>Use the <A HREF="Marijuana_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> provided to show your local media the timeliness of running a series on marijuana use. 	Suggest that reporters interview local high school students about marijuana use in their school and ask the 	kids how accurately they think the national findings tell the story in your city or town. Your local 	newspaper may also want to convene a focus group of students to talk about their perceptions of drug use and 	why they think their peers do or don't use marijuana. Another possible angle you can suggest is for the 	newspaper to look at local prevention efforts and see how effective these are in reducing marijuana use. In 	addition, ask a talk radio station in your area to devote a drive-time show to the topic. Suggest that they 	interview students and educators about why they think marijuana usage is up and what people can do about 	this problem.

	<LI>Tailor the <A HREF="Marijuana_Pitch.nclk">Pitch Letter</A> with examples of local efforts to reduce marijuana use. Use this to interest your 	newspaper in the topic. Also provide names and phone numbers of different local substance abuse programs 	working in your area to educate teens about the risk of smoking marijuana. 

	<LI>Localize the <A HREF="Marijuana_Op-Ed.nclk">Op-Ed</A> for your community newspaper and ask them to run it. Call to follow-up after sending it. You can tailor it with a local example to make a stronger impact on readers in your community.

	<LI>Schedule an editorial board meeting with your local paper and ask them to write an editorial about the 	increase in drug use among students and suggest they include a list of action steps that parents can take to 	keep their youngsters drug-free.
</OL>

<p>

<P>	** We would like to know if these tools are helpful and if you have attracted media attention for your efforts.     	     	
	Please give us your feedback and any suggestions for improving A Message Each Month. . . <br> 
	You can call <A HREF="mailto:diane@jointogether.org">Diane Barry</A> or <A HREF="mailto:lisa@jointogether.org">Lisa Falk</A> at Join Together:  (617) 437-1500 or fax us a note at (617) 437-9394.
<p><hr>

