<TITLE>HIV-INFECTION AND SUBSTANCE ABUSE</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>



<H2>HIV-Infection and Substance Abuse</H2>
</center>

<P>You probably know someone who is HIV-positive -- one in every 250 people in the United States has contracted this virus that ultimately leads to AIDS. This virus affects about one million people nationwide. And a number of men and women with HIV-infection have substance abuse problems that put them at risk for HIV -- either by injecting drugs or having unprotected sex. You can help many more people from becoming a statistic by making sure that all Americans have access to the health care they need including adequate substance abuse services. 


<P>To get this message out to the public and to key groups in your community, we have provided you with the following:


<UL>
	<LI>a <A HREF="HIV_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> with statistics on the problem and how treatment would help; 
	<LI>a <A HREF="HIV_Press.html">Sample Press Release</A> and a <A HREF="HIV_Sample.html">Sample Op-Ed</A> article you or your board members can revise and send to your local newspaper; 
	<LI>a list of Resources you can contact for more information on the problem, as well as tips on how to help you get other groups to join your efforts.
</UL>


<P>How to use these tools:


<OL>
	<LI>Use the <A HREF="HIV_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> to interest the media in this topic. 
<UL>
	<LI>Use the statistics to get newspaper, television and radio reporters to understand the scope and magnitude of the HIV epidemic and to realize that it affects us all. 
	<LI>Arrange an Editorial Board meeting with your local newspaper and use the statistics to show the link between alcohol and drug abuse and risk for HIV-infection.  Stress how the spread of this virus can be curbed if people at risk receive treatment for their substance abuse problems. Ask a counselor at a local AIDS clinic to speak about the range of people who come in to be tested. Invite a spokesperson who is HIV-positive to join your group to talk about the importance of treating substance abuse problems to reduce the risk of HIV-infections. Encourage the newspaper to take a stand on this issue and write an editorial in favor of treatment. 
	<LI>Write a Letter to the Editor or an Op-Ed (<A HREF="HIV_Sample.html">see sample</A> included) using key facts to show the correlation between substance abuse and HIV-infection and pointing out the need for adequate treatment.
</UL>


	<LI>Use the <A HREF="HIV_Press.html">Sample Press Release</A> to get press coverage. --Revise the release by adding local examples of people who are HIV-positive in your area.  Send the release to reporters at your local paper with your name and phone number listed as the contact. Call to follow up. Be prepared to suggest story ideas and other contact persons on this topic.


	<LI>Use the Resource Sheet to illustrate the scope of the problem and expand your coalition.
<UL>
	<LI>Call the resources listed to gather more statistics about HIV nationally, as well as to define the scope of the problem locally. Contact groups listed or others you might know to understand the scope of HIV/AIDS in your area and examples of how treatment can help to reduce the spread of the problem. 
	<LI>Get these groups to join your coalition.
</UL>
</OL>


<P>We would like to know if these tools are helpful and if you have attracted media attention for your efforts. Please give us your feedback and any suggestions for improving our Hot Issue pages. . .  You can call <A HREF="mailto:diane@jointogether.org">Diane Barry</A> or <A HREF="mailto:lisa@jointogether.org">Lisa Falk</A> at Join Together:  (617) 437-1500 or fax us a note at (617) 437-9394.
