<TITLE>Youth Access to Tobacco Survey Results
</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>



<H2>JOIN TOGETHER<br>
TOBACCO PROJECT RESULTS</H2>


<P>
<B>HUNDREDS OF VOLUNTEERS CANVAS NEIGHBORHOODS NEAR SCHOOLS AND FIND OVER A THOUSAND TOBACCO OUTLETS!</B>
</center>

<P>
How easy is it for kids to buy cigarettes? That's what Join Together wanted to know when it launched its Tobacco Project in October of 1996.  To find out how accessible cigarettes are in places kids shop, Join Together asked community groups across the country to mobilize residents to count the number of outlets (ie. convenience stores, gas stations, restaurants and grocery stores) that sell tobacco products within a quarter-mile radius of a public school.  More than 500 volunteers from 27 states participated in this project. 


<P><H3>Here is what they found:</H3>


<P>Participants found over 1,200 tobacco retail outlets within a quarter-mile radius of 222 schools.  Just seven percent (7%) of the total number of schools surveyed reported that there were no outlets within the quarter mile radius.  This represents an average of six outlets located near each school.  As the chart on the next page indicates, the most common places where cigarettes were sold near schools were convenience and grocery stores.  


<P><H3>Other findings:</H3>


<UL>
	<LI>There were 76 stores selling tobacco products near one public school in Passaic, New Jersey. Many of these stores also sold candy and other items that appeal to youth.
 

	<LI>Loose cigarettes are available at some stores near a school in New Haven, Conn. Youth there say that some store clerks easily sell these to minors.
 

	<LI>Cigarette packs were readily accessible to teens at a store in Newport, New Hampshire and could easily be shoplifted. Students alerted the store owner to this fact and as a result, the rack displaying the cigarettes was moved behind the counter.


	<LI>High school students in Oshkosh, Wisc. say it is easy to purchase cigarettes from some stores located near the schools. The kids know which salespeople will sell to minors and they shop during the hours when those employee are working.


	<LI>Availability of tobacco products is widespread in Fayetteville, NC. However, this tobacco project revealed that there are no vending machines selling cigarettes near the school. Therefore, cigarette sales all come from outlets like convenience stores and gas stations.
</UL>


<PRE><P>
Type of Outlet        Number     Percentage

Convenience Store      300          24%

Grocery Store          261          21%

Gas Station            188          15%

Restaurant             153          12%

* Other                112           9%

Liquor Store           106           9%

Drug Store              72           6%

Vending Machine         44           4%

________________________________________
TOTAL                1,236         100%
</PRE>


<P>* On the survey form, teams recorded "other" tobacco outlets.  Some of these other tobacco retail outlets listed included laundromats, candy stores, card stores, bowling alleys, paper stores, take-out pizza / deli establishments, and thrift stores.  Clearly, children frequent these types of establishments, and sell products which appeal to children.  It is important to note that among youths aged 12-17 years who usually bought their own cigarettes in 1989, about 85% often or sometimes bought them from a small store, 50% from a large store, and 15% from a vending machine. These figures come from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Office on Smoking and Health.


<P>
<H3>Who participated in this Project?
</H3>

<P>Community volunteers acted individually, or formed teams, and canvassed their neighborhoods to measure the extent of cigarette availability within a quarter-mile radius of schools.  They counted the number of tobacco sales locations in convenience, grocery and liquor stores, gas stations, restaurants, and vending machines.  Participants recorded results on a summary sheet, and sent them back to Join Together for analysis and development of this report.  


<P>In twenty seven states, more than 500 volunteers (402 youth; 124 adults) were involved in counting tobacco outlets within a quarter-mile radius of over 200 schools.  These schools represented over 100 communities from across the country.  Communities as diverse as Anchorage, Alaska, Winner, South Dakota, Ellsworth, Maine, and Jupiter, Florida, representing all four corners of the United States, submitted results to Join Together.  
This tobacco outlet counting project generated a great deal of interest, enthusiasm, and participation among concerned citizens. 


<P><B>For instance:</B>

<UL>
 	<LI>Seventy-five youth, accompanied by three adults, counted the number of outlets near Boyne City Public Schools in Boyne City, Mich.; 
	<LI>Sixty-five youth, on their own,  counted the stores selling tobacco around a middle school in Creston, Ohio; 
	<LI>Thirty-five youth and three adults in Passaic, N.J., surveyed the area near an elementary school in their community;
	<LI>Twenty-five youth and four adults counted the outlets near a high school in Monroe, Louisiana.  
	<LI>A single volunteer in Laredo, Texas, surveyed 27 schools in his area; while another individual surveyed 22 schools in Leominster, Mass.; 
	<LI>A team of two adult volunteers in Martinsburg, WV counted the stores around 20 schools.
</UL>


<P><H3>Why are the results of this Tobacco Project important?</H3>


<UL>
	<li>Projects such as this one are important to raise public awareness about the problem of underage smoking. The fact is, more than 3,000 kids start smoking each day, and more than one million youngsters start each year. This number is on the rise, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Office on Smoking and Health. 


	<li>The most effective preventive programs to reduce youth smoking are communitywide ones that combine education and public policy approaches. The placement of tobacco retail outlets near schools (especially elementary schools) has potentially harmful implications for youth, since these factors give kids the message that it is OK to smoke.  This Join Together Tobacco Project is a first step in educating people about youth access to tobacco. It also sets the stage for further communitywide public policy action. 

<B>Geographic Information:</B>

<ul>
	<LI>Community teams selected a total of 222 schools for this project, approximately half (45%) of which were elementary schools.  Middle schools represented 30%, while high schools comprised 25% of the total number of schools surveyed.


	<LI>Half (49%) of the areas surveyed surrounding schools were classified as rural, while 28% of areas were classified as urban; the remaining areas, 23%, were classified as suburban.  This means that youth access to tobacco is not just a big city problem--it affects rural communities all across the country!   


	<LI>Almost two-thirds of communities described the area in which the school is located as mixed commercial & residential; one-third indicated the areas were residential.
</ul>
</UL>
<p><hr>

<P>For additional information about this Project, contact:<br>
ASTRID KOZEL  / <A HREF="mailto:astrid@jointogether.org">astrid@jointogether.org</A><br>
JOIN TOGETHER:  441 Stuart Street, Sixth Floor, Boston, MA  02116<br>
Tel:  617-437-1500 / Fax:  617-437-9394 / URL:  <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A>
<br><br><br><hr>

