<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Binge Drinking on College Campuses</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<H2><CENTER>BINGE DRINKING ON COLLEGE CAMPUSES <BR>
<HR></CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
As college students head back to school, many of them will be affected by
a serious problem: binge drinking. Today, nearly half of all college students
binge drink. This drinking leads to a number of problems on campuses, such
as violence, rapes, sexually-transmitted diseases and suicides. And even
though it is illegal for anyone under 21 to consume alcohol, many minors
getting served anyway. This is a pervasive problem not only for college
communities but for our nation's future leadership. We encourage you to
raise public awareness about the risks associated with binge drinking. To
help you do this, we have provided the following: 
<UL>
<LI>a <A HREF="Binge_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> that shows the scope of
college drinking nationwide, as well as the problems that occur when students
binge drink; 
<LI>some <A HREF="Binge_Action.html">Community Action Steps</A> to help
you find the local angle to describe the scope of college drinking in your
area and take action to help reduce the problem; 
<LI>a <A HREF="Binge_Letter.html">Sample Pitch Letter</A> you can send to
the editor of your local newspaper encouraging him or her to devote a back-to-school
piece looking at the drinking habits of local college students and the related
problems; 
<LI>a <A HREF="Binge_Op-Ed.html">Sample Op-Ed</A> your local newspaper can
run to create awareness about the effects of heavy drinking and to encourage
people to make smart choices. 

	<LI>A <A HREF="/JTO/news/press/cspi_binge.html">press release</A> detailing a recent initiative addressing irresponsible tavern ads in college newspapers.
</UL>
<HR>
<H3><CENTER>HOW TO USE THIS MONTHLY ACTION KIT:</CENTER>
</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Use the <A HREF="Binge_Facts.html">Fact Sheet</A> to educate reporters about the problem of binge drinking
on college campuses. Suggest that your local newspaper convene a focus group
of local college students to find out their reaction to these statistics
and how to discourage underage drinking. Arrange an Editorial Board Meeting
to ask the paper to encourage college administrators and alcohol servers
to set strict policies and take an active role in communitywide prevention
efforts. If you can, bring a representative from a local college to talk
about the relationship between alcohol and violence and crimes on campus.
<LI>Explore some of the resources listed on the <A HREF="Binge_Action.html">Finding the Local Angle</a>
sheet to find out the scope of college drinking in your community. By tailoring
your message to reflect what is happening locally, you will greatly increase
your chances of interesting reporters in covering this topic. While the
national picture is certainly interesting, the local picture affects each
citizen and your newspaper will therefore recognize this as valuable news.
<LI>Send the <A HREF="Binge_Letter.html">Pitch Letter</a> to an editor at your local newspaper (or television
or radio news directors) to entice him or her in covering this topic. Use
interesting and dramatic statistics to grab his or her attention. Show the
timeliness of the story and explain how the newspaper can help students
have a safer school year by raising public awareness about this issue. 
<LI>Add some local statistics to the <A HREF="Binge_Op-Ed.html">Sample Op-Ed</A> provided and ask your
newspaper to run it to alert people to the fact that college drinking can
be dangerous. Give readers some action steps that they can take to help
solve the problem. 
</OL>
