<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>The Fact Is</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>THE FACT IS. . . .<BR> </FONT></B></CENTER> <P> <B>Substance abuse prevention and treatment programs are critically lacking at every level of the criminal justice system.</B> <B>Consider the following statistics:<BR> </B> <UL> <LI>Over one million people are arrested each year on drug-related charges. <SUP>1</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>At least 45 percent of arrestees charged with violent crimes or robberies, burglaries and theft tested positive for the use of one or more drugs.<SUP> 2</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>The number of drug arrests <I><B>tripled</B></I><B> </B>during the 1980s -- from 471,000 in 1980 to 1,247,000 in 1989. <SUP>3</SUP> And if the jail population continues to grow at the current rate, by the year 2053 the United States will have more people in jail than out. <SUP>4</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>More than two-thirds of U.S. prison wardens surveyed think that correctional treatment options -- such as residential drug treatment programs, home detention, halfway houses and boot camps -- should be utilized more.<SUP> 5</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>Of all the money spent in the United States each year to reduce substance abuse, 78 percent goes to enforce laws, provide punishment, or to control drug trade. Only 22 percent is spent on prevention and treatment.<SUP> 6</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<P> <B>Treatment works.<BR> </B> <UL> <LI>Every dollar spent on treatment leads to a $7.46 reduction in crime-related spending and lost productivity. <SUP>7</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>In a follow-up study of treatment programs for incarcerated felony offenders, 79 percent of participants were employed upon release. And only 35 percent were rearrested, compared with a national rearrest rate of 63 percent. <SUP>8</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>Drug Courts -- which divert non-violent offenders from jail time to treatment -- could lower the recidivism rate, increase successful treatment outcomes, and save taxpayers $5,000 per defendant in jail costs alone. <SUP>9</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>A treatment program based in California&iacute;s Amity Prison, which separates substance abusers from the rest of the prison population to address the myriad of problems associated with addiction, has reduced the usual recidivism rate from 60 percent to 25 percent. <SUP>10</SUP> </UL>

<P>

<UL> <LI>A diversion program for offenders in Arizona found that only 11 percent of those that entered treatment between March 1989 and March 1990 had committed another crime by May of 1991. In contrast, 44 percent of the offenders who rejected the treatment option did commit other crimes in that same time period. <SUP>11</SUP> </UL>

<P> <CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>SOURCES<BR> <BR> </FONT></B></CENTER> <FONT SIZE="-1"><P> 1 -- From the<B> </B>1996 National Drug Control Strategy.<BR>

<P> 2 --  National Institute of Justice Reports, 1989.<BR>

<P> 3 -- Bureau of Justice Statistics &igrave; Drugs and Crime Facts 1990&icirc;.<BR>

<P> 4 -- Camille Gear and David Lewis, Locking Up the Drug Problem: Criminal and  Legal Responses to Drug Addiction, Center for Alcohol Addiction Studies, Brown  University, 1995.<BR>

<P> 5 --  National survey sponsored in 1994 by the Subcommittee on the Constitution, a  panel of the U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee. A full 157 prison wardens from  Department of Corrections in eight states (California, Delaware, Florida, Illinois,  Michigan, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Texas) participated.<BR>

<P> 6 --  Office of National Drug Control Policy 1995 Drug Control Strategy.<BR>

<P> 7 -- From a study conducted by the RAND Corporation for the Office of National  Drug Control Policy and the U.S. Army in 1994.<BR>

<P> 8 -- Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration. <BR>

<P> 9 -- U.S. Department of Justice, August, 1995.<BR>

<P> 10 National Institute of Justice report,<I> The Effectiveness of Treatment for Drug  Abusers Under the Criminal Justice System,</I> 1996. <BR>

<P> 11 --  From the Maricopa County Drug Reduction Program. Treatment was provided by  the Maricopa County Attorney/Treatment Alternatives to Street Crime Drug  Diversion Program in Maricopa County, Arizona.</FONT>


<BR> <BR> <B><A HREF="others.html">Next</A></B> page<BR><BR> <B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR> <BR> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> </BODY> </HTML>
