<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>Sample Pitch Letter</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>SAMPLE PITCH LETTER<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<I>You can tailor the following letter to interest an editor at
your local newspaper in doing an in-depth article or series examining
the link between substance abuse and crime and the need for treatment
in your community.<BR>
</I>
<P>
Dear Editor:<BR>

<P>
Many people feel safe simply locking criminals up in prisons.
But, if you take a closer look at the criminal justice system,
you'll see there is a false security in the &quot;lock-em up&quot;
solution.  <BR>

<P>
Alcohol and drug addictions are at the root of many crimes, particularly
domestic violence and homicide. Yet, instead of taking the time
to treat these addictions when criminals are in jail, these problem
are all too often ignored by the criminal justice system. That
means when the addicted prisoners are released, they return back
to society to commit further crimes. This jeopardizes our safety
and the safety of our children. <BR>

<P>
Recently, General Barry McCaffrey, the nation's new drug czar,
recognized this serious gap in America's drug strategy by announcing
that part of his 10-year plan to reduce drugs includes expanding
drug treatment in prisons.<BR>

<P>
Most offenders with addictions commit nonviolent crimes. Therefore,
it is less expensive -- and more effective -- to treat the addiction
than to house that person in jail. The price tag for treatment
is also less than the price associated with crime. A national
study conducted by the RAND Corporation for the Office of National
Drug Control Policy tells us that every dollar spent on treatment
leads to a $7 reduction in crime-related spending and lost-productivity.
Other studies collaborate this finding. <BR>

<P>
In fact, a recent national policy panel convened by the Boston
University School of Public Health recommends that non-violent
offenders with substance abuse addictions should be diverted to
drug courts, treatment programs and supervision, instead of or
along with, jail. This panel also recommends that police, courts,
judges and probation officers work more closely with treatment
providers and citizens to reduce crime.<BR>

<P>
A full 60 percent of all prisoners in the United States are in
prison because of alcohol and drug-related offenses. This is up
25 percent from a decade earlier. If the prison population continues
to grow at the current rate, experts predict we will have more
people in jail than out by the year 2053.<BR>

<P>
I urge you to look at the link between substance abuse and crime
in our community. I can put you in touch with some local sources.
You can reach me at (YOUR PHONE NUMBER). I will call you next
week to follow up.<BR>

<P>
Sincerely,<BR>

<P>
YOUR NAME
<P>
ORGANIZATION

<BR> <BR> <B><A HREF="oped.html">Next</A></B> page<BR><BR> <B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR> <BR> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> </BODY> </HTML>
</DOC>
