<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>Policy Panel</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>HOW TO CONVENE A LOCAL POLICY PANEL<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
Policy panels are an effective way to join together a group of
concerned leaders representing different vantage points of your
community around a timely policy issue. At the same time, local
policy panels can help to generate public awareness of substance
abuse problems. You may want to convene a policy panel in your
community to examine ways to reduce substance-related crime with
treatment and encourage the criminal justice system to work more
effective.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Getting Started<BR>
</B></U>
<P>
<I>The following steps can help you to start such a policy panel
in your area.<BR>
</I>
<UL>
<LI>Select several diverse leaders in the community to serve on
the panel. Ensure that they represent expertise and awareness
of the community. Select a chairperson to help guide your progress.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Outline the panel's mission so the members will focus on what
is expected of them. Agree on key questions for the panel to address.

</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Hold a public hearing to get input from citizens concerned
about this topic. Be sure to invite representatives from diverse
points of view. This will help the panel to see all sides of the
issue and also help it to move toward making its recommendations.
Invite the media to attend the hearing. In addition to covering
the proceedings, reporters can help you raise public awareness
about this issue.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>After the panel agrees on a series of recommendations, highlight
these in a final report you can release to the public and the
media. Include examples of ways these recommendations have been
implemented in other places, as well as resources people can use
to help them implement these suggestions locally.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Brief the media about your findings. You may use this as an
opportunity to reinforce existing relationships with local press
and also to make new allies. Consider arranging an editorial board
meeting and talk radio show interviews for panel members.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Be alert for other opportunities to promote your findings.
The panel chair and members may want to make presentations to
elected officials and local groups, such as civic clubs and neighborhood
organizations.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
For more information on how to convene a local policy panel, contact
Bob Downing at Join Together at (617) 437-1500 or <A HREF="mailto:bob@jointogether.org">bob@jointogether.org</A>
<BR> <BR><B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR> <BR> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> </BODY> </HTML>
