<TITLE>Drinking and Driving: Sample Op-Ed</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>


<H3>Drinking and Driving</H3>
<H2>Sample Op-Ed</H2></center>


<P>

<P>You can take the following body of this Op-Ed or Letter-to-the-Editor and add local examples and statistics. <br>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.

<FORM method=POST action="Alcohol_Op-EdOutput.nclk">
<hr>


<P>
<B>RESPONSIBLE DRIVERS ARE KEY TO HIGHWAY SAFETY THIS HOLIDAY SEASON</B>
	

<P>	The holidays are a time of joy for most people -- but for the relatives of people killed in fatal drunk driving crashes, this time of year is tinged with sorrow.<p>

Last year, 17,461 Americans died as a result of alcohol and drug-related drunk driving crashes, and 5,000 of them were under the age of 25, according to the National Highway Safety Administration.<p>

What makes these deaths especially tragic is the fact that many of them could have been prevented. Research has shown that states with tougher drunk driving laws have a lower death rate due to alcohol-related car crashes than states that do not crack down as hard on drunk drivers. <p>

In fact, a study published in the November-December issue of Public Health Reports, called &quot;Lower Legal Blood Alcohol Limits for Young Drivers,&quot; found that 375 fatal car crashes could be avoided each year if all states adopted laws making it illegal for people under the age of 21 to drive after drinking. <p>

The study found that the proportion of single vehicle fatal crashes at night declined by 20 percent in states that had lowered their legal Blood Alcohol Content limit (the amount of alcohol a person can legally have in his or her body when driving) to .00 or .02 for drivers under age 21 (Zero Tolerance Laws).<p>

Alcohol-related car crashes cost the nation $46 billion annually, according to NHTSA. These costs are associated with lost productivity, medical costs and property damage.<p>

And there is no way to put a dollar amount on the lifetime trauma endured by the family members of victims killed or injured in alcohol-related car crashes.<p>

That's why it is so important that residents urge their legislators to implement tougher BAC laws for all drivers in our state. <p>

In addition, there are several other steps that residents can take to prevent any unnecessary deaths in our community this holiday season.<p>

First, people should educate themselves and others about the risks of drinking and driving. They should also be responsible party hosts and offer non-alcoholic beverages to drivers. In addition, they should prevent any intoxicated guests from getting behind the wheel of a car. Finally, parents should not serve alcohol to minors, and should come up with an arrangement for their children to call home if they -- or someone else who is driving them -- has been drinking.<p>

If everyone makes the effort to be a responsible driver and host, we can significantly reduce the risk of deaths from drunk driving accidents in our community this holiday season.<p>
<P>For more information on how you can help make a difference, contact <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Organization" VALUE="Your Organization"> at <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">

<br><BR><BR>
<P>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Name" VALUE="Your name" SIZE=35><br>
<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Title" VALUE="Your Title"><br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><INPUT TYPE="submit" VALUE="Generate a letter">
<INPUT TYPE="reset" VALUE="Clear the letter"><br></center><p>

[<A HREF="Alcohol_Index.html">Back</A> to Drinking and Driving]
