<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>facts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>THE FACT IS. . .</CENTER>
</H2>

You can share these facts with parents, teachers and guidance counselors
when school resumes in the fall. You can also use these statistics as talking
points when speaking with reporters, being interviewed on television or
radio talk shows, and giving a presentation on this issue.<BR>
<UL>
<LI>More than 75,000 children in the 6th grade have tried marijuana. (PRIDE
Questionnaire Report: 1992-1993 National Summary-USE grades 6-12, National
Institute on Drug Abuse, Public Health Service, National Institute of Health,
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, 1994, p. 259.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Nearly one in every ten 8th graders and one out of every four high school
students uses marijuana. (NIDA. Monitoring the Future Study: Advance Data:
July 1995. U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>The average first-use age of marijuana is 13.9 years of age. (SAMHSA.
National Household Survey on Drug Abuse: Main Findings 1993, 1995, pp. 148.
U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>According to data accumulated over the past 20 years, the likelihood
of using a drug is affected by one's perceptions of harms associated with
that drug. (NIDA. National Survey Results on Drug Use From the Monitoring
the Future Study, 1975-1994, 1995, Table I, pp. 8. U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services.) For instance, the latest research shows that the increase
in marijuana use among youth was both preceded and accompanied by a decrease
in perceived risk. (Ibid., pp. 254.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Problems among young people that are associated with marijuana include:
school drop-out; not learning important interpersonal coping skills; problematic
relationships between parents and their children; poor role modeling for
younger siblings; and decreasing ability to make appropriate decisions,
solve problems and learn new, developmentally appropriate skills. (NIDA.
Marijuana: What Parents Need to Know, 1995, pp.19. U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>One in four youths entering juvenile detention test positive for marijuana.
(OJJDP. Juvenile Offenders and Victims; A National Report, August 1995,
pp.65. U.S. Dept. of Justice.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Between 1990 and 1994, marijuana-related emergency room episodes increased
by 155 percent -- from 15,700 to 40,100. (SAMHSA, Preliminary Estimates
from the Drug Abuse Warning Network, November 1995, pp. 17. U.S. Dept. of
Health and Human Services.)
</UL>
For more facts about marijuana, call the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol
and Drug Information at 1-800-729-6686 or visit the Reality Check web page
at http://www.health.org/reality<BR>
<BR>
