<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Sample Pitch Letter</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>Sample Pitch Letter</CENTER>
</H2>
Your local media outlets can be of valuable assistance in helping you get
the message out that marijuana use among young people is dangerous. But
it is important to keep in mind when approaching local reporters with a
story idea that establishing a relationship with them is a two-way street.
Just as they can provide widespread coverage of an issue, you can provide
them with valuable facts and other sources they can contact for more information
and interviews. Keep this in mind as you tailor the following pitch letter
with local examples and statistics and send it to a reporter or editor at
your local newspaper, or to an assignment editor at your local television
or radio station. 
<P><CENTER></CENTER>
<P><B>Dear (Media Contact):</B><BR>
<BR>
Did you know that some current forms of marijuana are &quot;spiked&quot;
with other illicit drugs like cocaine, crack cocaine, PCP and even embalming
fluid?<BR>
<BR>
This makes a dangerous drug even more dangerous. Especially when we realize
some of its users are as young as 9 or 10-years-old, according to recent
surveys. And more and more older kids are using marijuana. Marijuana usage
rates among older students -- ages 12 to 17 -- have almost doubled since
the early 1990s.<BR>
<BR>
This sends a clear message that we need to educate another generation about
the dangers of marijuana use. And we also need to educate their parents.
Part of what makes this issue so complex is that some of these parents used
marijuana themselves in the past, so they do not feel comfortable about
talking to their children about this serious issue.<BR>
<BR>
Nonetheless, the fact is that this drug impairs young people's judgment,
which can lead to unprotected sex, pregnancy and sexually-transmitted diseases,
including HIV/AIDS. It also contributes to accidents, violence and car crashes.
The 1995 Drug Abuse Warning Network report released last November shows
that medical emergency room episodes related to marijuana have increased
155 percent since 1990. In addition, this drug also negatively affects concentration
and schoolwork and can cause young users to be suspended, expelled, or get
a police record.<BR>
<BR>
You can help alert residents in our community about the growing problem
of marijuana use and the many dangers associated with this drug. I can provide
you with many statistics showing the scope of the problem, and the consequences.
I can also put you in touch with some parents, teachers and students to
get their input on this issue.<BR>
<BR>
You can reach me at (YOUR PHONE NUMBER). I will call you next week to follow
up. This is a serious issue and one we can no longer ignore. Thanks for
your time.<BR>
<BR>
Sincerely,<BR>
<BR>
YOUR NAME<BR>
TITLE<BR>
ORGANIZATION<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="psa.html">Next</A></B> page<BR><BR>
<B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR>
