</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Action Steps</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>What You Can Do About Inhalant Abuse</CENTER>
</H2>
Inhalant abuse is a widespread--and serious--problem among youth today.
In fact, as many as one in five students abuses regular household substances--such
as glue, hair spray, lighter fluid and paint thinner--to get high. And unlike
alcohol, tobacco and other drugs, these products are easy for kids to obtain
and do not make adults suspicious if they see a child using them.<BR>
<BR>
Nonetheless, these products can lead to a number of serious side affects
for users, including sudden death. And the problem is not getting better.
The rate of inhalant users continues to rise in states across the country,
prompting some schools to educate kids and parents about the dangers. But
unfortunately, many young inhalant users have dropped out of school or do
not attend classes. Therefore, these young people do not know the possible
consequences of their behavior. That's why it is crucial that we find ways
to warn them.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Here are some steps you can take:</B> 
<UL>
<LI>Involve a wide variety of local groups in your public education efforts.
You may want to include doctors, nurses, pharmacists, politicians, school
drug-education coordinators, law enforcement officers, teachers, youth,
parents, business owners, media representatives and clergy. Brainstorm together
ways to reach high-risk youth in your community. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Put up posters warning about the dangers of inhalant abuse in places
young people frequent, such as recreation centers, record stores, fast food
restaurants, pizza places, ice cream parlors, candy stores, movie theaters
and supermarkets. Be sure to list resources people can turn to for help.
<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask local radio stations that play music that appeals to youth to run
public service announcements about inhalant abuse and the associated risks.
<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask your local movie theaters to run a public service announcement about
inhalant abuse before each movie. See if a local corporation or business
that caters to youth will donate the money to produce the PSA. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask your local newspaper to run a full-page advertisement about the
dangers of inhalant abuse to warn parents and young people about the risks.
<BR>
<BR>
<LI>See if your local cable station will run an advertisement about the
dangers of inhalant abuse. Ask local students to write, direct, produce
and act in the ad. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask your local grocery stores to stuff fact sheets about inhalant abuse--and
how to get help--in customers bags. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask local businesses--such as the gas or phone company--to include bill
stuffers about the dangers of inhalant abuse.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask manufacturers of products that youth inhale to work with you to
find ways to reduce this abuse. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Plan ahead for &quot;National Inhalants &amp; Poisons Awareness Week,&quot;
which is sponsored by the National Inhalant Prevention Coalition/Texas Prevention
Partnership and is held the third week in March. Ask your mayor or city
council to sign a proclamation recognizing this week in your city or town
and plan some events to call attention to this serious problem. (For more
information about this week, see <A HREF="others.html">What Others Have
Done</A>.) <BR>
<BR>
<LI>Call the photo editor at your local newspaper and offer to set up a
photograph of some of the products that can be misused as inhalants. This
can help to alert parents that some &quot;innocent-looking&quot; household
products can actually be deadly. 
</UL>
<BR>
[<A HREF="../Inhalants/Inhalant_Index.html">Back</A> to Inhalants] <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> 
</BODY>
