<TITLE>THE FACT IS . . . .</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>

<H3>Prevention Works</H3>

<H2>THE FACT IS . . . .</H2>
</center>

<P>
<H3>SUBSTANCE ABUSE IS COSTLY:</H3> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>--The nation spends about $168 billion on alcohol and drug problems a year(FN-1)-- that's $675 for every man, woman and child in the country.(FN-2)


<P>--The amount the country spends on health care could be reduced by $90.4 billion if alcohol and other drug problems were prevented before they started.(FN-3)</BLOCKQUOTE>


<P><H3>PREVENTION WORKS TO REDUCE SUBSTANCE ABUSE:</H3> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>--The number of adolescents (ages 12 to 17) who drink alcohol has decreased by almost 3 million since 1979 -- from 37 percent to 20 percent.(FN-4)


<P>--There has also been a significant decrease in illicit drug use among adolescents -- from 18 percent in 1979 to less than 7 percent in 1991. This represents 2.5 million young people who have stayed away from drugs.(FN-5)


<P>--Prevention messages about the dangers of drinking and driving have been reaching young people. In fact, the number of fatal alcohol-related car crashes among teens has declined by 55 percent over the past 10 years. However, such crashes among young adults aged 21 - 35 have only fallen by 32 percent, indicating the need for more targeted efforts.(FN-6)


<P>--A 1994 study by Cornell University Researchers of 6,000 students in New York state found that the odds of drinking, smoking or using marijuana were 40 percent lower among kids who participated in a prevention program during 7th, 8th and 9th grades than their counterparts who did not. (FN-7)</BLOCKQUOTE>


<P><H3>DESPITE OUR SUCCESSES, WE NEED TO STEP UP PREVENTION EFFORTS:</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE> --A December 1994 study by the Harvard School of Public Health found that nearly half (44 percent) of all college students are binge drinkers, consuming five or more drinks at a time. On a national scale, this means that approximately 3 million students a year binge drink, and 1.3 billion do so more than once a week.(FN-8)


<P>--Fifty percent of binge drinkers in this study said they had ridden with a driver who was high or drunk, and 40 percent of the males said they had driven after five or more drinks.(FN-9)


<P>--Binge drinking affects not only the drinker but also his or her peers -- physical assault, sexual harassment and impaired sleep and study time are some of the &quot;secondhand binge&quot; effects experienced by non-binging students as the result of the heavy drinking of their classmates.(FN-10)


<P>--The 1994 Monitoring the Future Survey found that marijuana use is up among 8th, 10th and 12th graders, and anti-drug attitudes are deteriorating.(FN-11 )


<P> --Specifically, over the past two or three years marijuana use has doubled among 8th graders (to 13 percent), grown by two-thirds among 10th graders (to 25 percent), and grown by 40 percent among 12th graders (to 31 percent).(FN-12)


<P>--Other illicit drugs that have been on the rise among students -- including LSD, hallucinogens, inhalants, stimulants, barbiturates, cocaine and crack.(FN-13)


<P>--In other Monitoring the Future survey findings, binge drinking has remained constant among students in 8th, 10th and 12th grades.  One in seven 8th graders reported having five or more drinks in the past two weeks, as did nearly one in four 10th graders, and more than one in every four seniors.(FN-14)</BLOCKQUOTE>


<P><H3>PREVENTION EFFORTS WORK -- AND MUST INVOLVE THE WHOLE COMMUNITY:</H3> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>--Prevention works best when all parts of the community make it a priority and get involved together. That means community leaders, policy makes, educators, clergy, business leaders, volunteers, parents, employers, employees, youth and social service providers, children and youth, and representatives of the media.(FN-15) (See recommendation 2 from Join Together's Public Policy Panel on Preventing Substance Abuse.)


<P>--Many liquor stores in South Central Los Angeles that were closed down during the 1992 riots are being replaced with other businesses. This is due to the work of the Center for Substance Abuse Partnership grantee there that has mobilized the whole community in this effort.(FN-16)


<P>--Close to 600 drug locations in Tacoma, Washington, have been closed since 1989, thanks to Tacoma's Campaign for Safe Streets. This campaign brings together volunteers from over 30 neighborhoods working to reclaim their streets from drug dealers.(FN-17)


<P>--In the Liberty City section of Miami, known for its heavy drug trafficking, the Miami Coalition had succeeded in bringing together clergy, schools and police to organize community watches, shut drug houses, clean up parks, and start community service and neighborhood beautification programs.(FN-18)


<P> --Drug treatment is now readily available in the Marshall Heights section of Washington, D.C., thanks to the efforts of Marshall Heights Fighting Back, operated through the Marshall Heights Community Development Corporation. This area of the nation's capital, which has a high rate of drug use and crime, had no drug treatment       capacity, so the Fighting Back program organized key members of the community to help build a drug treatment and social service program right in the neighborhood.(FN-19)</BLOCKQUOTE>


<P>
<hr>

<P>
<H3>SOURCES</H3>


<P>1--Eigen, Lewis, Ed.D., Social and Economic Health Services, Ltd., using 1985 
economic costs  to society figures cited in U.S. Department of Health and
Human 
Services, Alcohol, Drug Abuse and Mental Health Administration, The Economic 
Costs of Alcohol and Drug Abuse and Mental Illness (Washington, 1992) and
adding
4 percent per year for inflation to arrive at the figure, which represents
1992.
        

<P>
2 --Ibid, and United States Census Bureau, 1990 Census of Population and 
Housing, Summary Population and Housing Characteristics, United States 
(Washington, 1990).


<P>3--The Economic Costs of Alcohol and Drug Abuse and Mental Illness, pp. 22-24.


<P>4 - 5--Center for Substance Abuse Prevention, from the Executive Summary of A 
Discussion Paper on Preventing Alcohol, Tobacco, and Other Drug Problems,
1993.


<P>6--National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 1994.


<P>7--Study by researchers at the Institute for Prevention Research at Cornell 
University Medical School released in the summer of 1994. Funding for the
study 
came from the National Institute on Drug Abuse. The study took six years to 
complete and nearly 6,000 students from 56 schools in New York state were 
surveyed. For more information about the study, call (212) 746-1270. (The
final 
report is not yet published.)


<P>8 -10 --Study of the &quot;Secondhand Effects of Binge Drinking&quot; conducted by 
researchers at the Harvard School of Public Health and published in the Dec.
7, 
1994 issue of The Journal of the American Medical Association. Funding for the
study was provided by The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation. To obtain a copy of 
the study, call (617) 432-1135.


<P>11 - 14 --The &quot;Monitoring the Future Study&quot; was conducted by scientists at the
University of Michigan Institute for Social Research for the Department of 
Health and Human Services and released on Dec. 8, 1994. Funding for the study 
was provided by the National Institute on Drug Abuse. To obtain a copy of the 
study, call (800) 729-6686.


<P>15 -16--Center for Substance Abuse Prevention, List of Alcohol and Other Drug 
Facts, 
Nov., 1992.


<P>17 --For information about the Safe Streets Campaign, call (206) 272-6824.


<P>18 --For information about the Miami Coalition for a Drug-Free Community, call
        (305) 375-8032.

<p>19--For information about Marshall Heights' efforts, call (202) 396-1200.

<p><br>
