<TITLE>Sample Op-Ed Or Letter-To-The-Editor</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>


<H3>Prevention Works</H3>
<H2>Sample Op-Ed Or Letter-To-The-Editor</H2>
</center>

<P>You can take the following body of this Op-Ed or Letter-to-the-
Editor and add local examples and statistics. <br>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.

<FORM method=POST action="Prevention_Op-EdOutput.nclk">
<hr>

<B>PREVENTING SUBSTANCE ABUSE IS YOUR BUSINESS</B>


<P>This is no time to cut prevention for illicit drug and alcohol abuse.


<P>Recent studies have shown us that more kids are using marijuana today. There's also widespread binge drinking on college campuses. And heroin dealers are having an introductory sale on a new, more powerful inhalable heroin to lure a new generation of customers.


<P>Other recent stories also bring news of new AIDS cases attributable to drug use and tell us that a large portion of our prison inmates have alcohol and drug addictions.


<P>Appropriately applied prevention strategies work to reduce illicit drug and alcohol use -- just as immunizations, when given, work to reduce the spread of other diseases. However, much of the progress we have made against illicit drugs and excessive alcohol in the last decade is at risk if we do not continue existing prevention efforts. And in order for prevention to be even more effective, all sectors of a community must join together.


<P>For example, volunteers from 30 neighborhoods in Tacoma, Washington, joined forces and were able to close down almost 600 drug dealing locations there. And a community-wide effort in South Central Los Angeles has been able to keep some liquor stores that closed during the 1992 riots from reopening. Some of these stores were replaced with other businesses.  


<P>A national panel examining the substance abuse problem in America recently recommended that all public and private organizations incorporate prevention principles and themes into their ongoing initiatives. In addition, the panel recommended that private sector and community groups work together on prevention efforts to amplify their impact. For instance, parents and schools should link their prevention efforts with those of police, businesses and religious groups. The panel also urged government and the private sector to support such efforts with long-term commitments in funding, training and other resources.


<P>Here are some other things that can really make a difference:<br>

Businesses, in conjunction with social service agencies, can create drug-free workplace policies and provide information about alcohol and drugs to their employees, many of whom are parents; Recreation programs and schools can work with kids to plan creative alternatives to drinking and drug use after school and on the weekends; Religious leaders can work with treatment providers to reach out through their congregations to those who need help; The media can host public forums for coalitions in their communities to find solutions to local substance abuse problems; Employers can make jobs available for high-risk youth and people coming out of treatment programs; and Law enforcement can work to mentor high-risk youth. Please act now to make sure that substance abuse prevention policies and programs are a priority in our community. 

<P>For more information on how you can help make a difference, contact <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Organization" VALUE="Your Organization"> at <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">

<br><BR><BR>
<P>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Name" VALUE="Your name" SIZE=35><br>
<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Title" VALUE="Your Title"><br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><INPUT TYPE="submit" VALUE="Generate a letter">
<INPUT TYPE="reset" VALUE="Clear the letter"><br></center>
