<TITLE>THE FACT IS. . .</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>



<H3>Treatment Works &amp; We Can Prove It</H3>
<H2>The Fact Is. . .</H2>

</center>
<B>Here are some key findings from recent surveys that illustrate how substance abuse
treatment saves money and leads to healthier communities:
</B>
<hr>
<P><H3>RECOVERY SERVICES: THE CALIFORNIA DRUG AND ALCOHOL TREATMENT ASSESSMENT 
(CALDATA).</H3>
The largest and most rigorous study done in California released in August surveyed 3,000 providers and participants in four types of treatment programs in the state between October 1991, and September 1992. In a second followup phase of the study, 1,850 treatment recipients were interviewed 15 months after treatment.
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> <B>FINDINGS</B>

<P><B>Cost benefits to taxpayers</B>. 
<p>For every dollar invested in treatment, taxpayers save $7.14 in future costs. The cost of treating approximately 150,000 participants represented in the CALDATA study in 1992 was $209 million, while the benefits received during  treatment and the first year afterwards were worth approximately $1.5 billion in cost savings to taxpayers  primarily through the avoidance of crime.


<P><B>Decline in criminal activities</B>. 
<p>Following treatment, the level of crime declined by two-thirds. The greater the length of time spent in treatment, the greater the reduction in criminal activities.


<P><B>Improvements in health and hospitalizations.</B> 
<p>Emergency room admissions were reduced by one third following treatment. A one-third reduction in hospitalizations was reported following treatment.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<P>


<P><H3>NASADAD: INVEST IN TREATMENT FOR ALCOHOL AND OTHER DRUG PROBLEMS: IT PAYS:</H3>


<P>The National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors gathered studies conducted by 14 state alcohol and drug abuse agencies on the effectiveness of treatment for alcohol and drug problems. These studies were submitted by state directors from 14 states.

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>Crime</B>
<p>Maine's Office of Substance Abuse compared client outcome status of 180 clients admitted to treatment programs between September, 1990, and October 1991 to determine their outcome status at least one year following treatment. The state found that 79 percent of clients who received substance abuse treatment were not arrested one year after the treatment. People who resumed drinking since treatment had a 31 percent arrest rate versus 8 percent for those who did not drink.


<P><B>Health Care</B> 
<p>Ohio did a one-year followup of 668 clients who had completed treatment, and found they had a 66 percent decrease in hospital admissions (from 32 percent to 11 percent) and a 41 decrease in emergency room visits (from 34 percent to 20 percent).


<P>Minnesota's State AOD Authority, which operates the Consolidated Chemical Dependency Treatment Fund to provide treatment services to more than 17,000 clients, has done an extensive evaluation of its programs and reports that these services have resulted in an abstinence rate of 64 percent for clients six months after treatment. For chemical dependency clients, the state estimates that it saves $22 million in annual health care costs by providing treatment.


<P>Iowa measured health-related outcomes for over 1,400 clients by comparing the number of hospitilizations a client had in the six months prior to treatment admission with the six month period before the followup assessment date. The results showed that clients who completed treatment had a 12 percent less hospitalization rate than their counterparts who did not treatment.


<P><B>Employment</B> 
<p>Ohio's Department of Alcohol and Drug Addiction Services contracted with New Standards, Inc. to conduct a Comprehensive Assessment Treatment Outcomes Registry (CATOR) analysis of 668 residents one year after completing treatment. The findings include a decrease in worker absenteeism by 89 percent, tardiness by 92 percent and on-the-job injuries by 57 percent.


<P>Colorado compared clients status at treatment admission with clients status nine to 23 months following discharge. For fiscal years 1990 and 1991, over 26,000 treatment admissions were represented in a stratified random sample of 868 clients. The state found the income of clients following treatment increased by an average of $2,760 a year. The percentage of clients employed also improved by 70 percent.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><H3><B>THE RUTGERS STUDY: SOCIOECONOMIC EVALUATIONS OF ADDICTIONS TREATMENT</B></H3>
 In the fall of 1992, researchers at Rutgers University were asked by the President's Commission on Model State Drug Laws to review existing scientific literature on the cost-offsets of providing addiction treatment in the United States. Five populations were examined  Blue Cross/Blue Shield and private insurance eligibles, Medicare/Medicaid eligibles, employee groups, criminal justice populations and pregnant women. Information was derived from a series of computerized and hand literature searches, as well as from materials provided by HMOs, employee assistance programs, major insurance carriers, and officials in state health departments and federal government. The report pulls together a number of points from all the literature in an integrated review.

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>FINDINGS:</B>


<P><B>Health care</B> 
<p>The average alcoholic or other drug addict is conservatively estimated to be using more than 20 times the medical services of a non-addict.


<P>On the average, untreated alcoholics generally incur general health care costs that are at least 100 percent higher than those of nonalcoholics. In the last 12 months before treatment, the alcoholics costs are close to 300 percent higher.


<P><B>Business</B>


<P>Untreated addictions cost American businesses from $50 billion to $100 billion each year in increased medical claims and disability costs from illnesses and injuries, theft, absenteeism and decreased productivity.


<P>Treatment results in a reduction in sick-claim benefits, a better than 50 percent reduction in absenteeism and a similar reduction in days on disability.


<P>After treatment, reduction in days lost due to illness, sickness claims and hospitalization dropped by around 50 percent.


<P><B>Cost Savings</B>


<P>Treatment has projected returns of anywhere from $2 to $10 for every dollar spent on treatment.


<P>Although estimates of the cost of untreated addiction run as high as $172 billion annually, dollars directed to supporting prevention and treatment amount to less than one percent of the annual cost of untreated addiction.


<P> Two reports published by the RAND Drug Policy Research Center, Modeling the Demand for Cocaine and Controlling Cocaine: Supply Versus Demand Programs, make the case that providing treatment is cost-effective. The research provided in the reports was sponsored by the Office of National Drug Control Policy, the U.S. Army, and RAND's Social Policy Department.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<hr>

<P><H3>Sources</H3>


<uL>
	<LI>1 From the California Department of Alcohol and Drug Programs report, Evaluating Recovery Services: The California Drug and Alcohol Treatment Assessment (CALDATA), 1994. This is largest and most rigorous study on treatment ever conducted in California.


	<LI>2 From two reports published by the RAND Drug Policy Research Center, Modeling the Demand for Cocaine and Controlling Cocaine: Supply Versus Demand Programs, 1994. The research provided in the reports was sponsored by the Office of National Drug Control Policy, the U.S. Army, and RAND's Social Policy Department.


	<LI>3 From research conducted by Rutgers University for the President's Commission on Model State Drug Laws published in a report called Socioeconomic Evaluations of Addictions Treatment, 1993. Researchers reviewed existing scientific literature on the cost-offsets of providing addiction treatment in the United States.


	<LI>4 Rand.


	<LI>5 Ibid.


	<LI>6 Ibid.


	<LI>7 CALDATA.


	<LI>8 From a report published by The National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors called Invest in Treatment for Alcohol and Other Drug Problems: It Pays, 1994. The report includes the results of studies conducted by alcohol and drug abuse agencies in 15 states on the effectiveness of alcohol and drug treatment.

	<LI>9 RUTGERS.

	<LI>10 RUTGERS.

	<LI>11 RUTGERS.

	<LI>12 CALDATA.

	<LI>13 NASADAD.

	<LI>14 NASADAD.

	<LI>15 NASADAD.

	<LI>16 RUTGERS.

	<LI>17 RUTGERS.

	<LI>18 NASADAD.

	<LI>19 NASADAD. <p>
</uL>

<p>
