<TITLE>The Fact Is ...</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>


<H3>Domestic Violence and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>The Fact Is ...</H2>
</center>

<UL>
	<LI>Every 12 seconds a woman is beaten by her partner, reports Women's Work, a public arts program funded through Liz Claiborne, Inc.


	<LI>More than 2.5 million women a year are victims of violence in the United States, according to the National Crime Victimization Survey done by the Bureau of Justice Statistics.


	<LI>Research shows that alcohol and drugs are associated with up to 50 percent of all spousal abuse cases.


	<LI>Experts suggest that men who batter women may drink in order to give themselves permission to be violent. Men also learn that violent behavior that occurs while drinking may be excused or even forgiven.


	<LI>Medical expenses from domestic violence total from $3 to $5 billion each year. Businesses lose another $100 million in lost wages, sick leave, absenteeism and lowered productivity, according to the Colorado Domestic Violence Coalition.


	<LI>The National Crime Victimization Survey found that domestic violence accounts for almost 100,000 days of hospitalization, 30,000 emergency room visits, and 40,000 doctors appointments each year.


	<LI>A study sponsored by the Sheriff's Department of Lemon Grove, Calif., found that domestic violence occurs more frequently in areas with high concentrations of liquor stores.


	<LI>A study of 234 men charged with assaulting their mates in Marion County, Indiana, found that 32 percent of the men had a drug problem and 22 percent had dual drug and alcohol problems.


	<LI>Studies have found that by treating substance abuse problems,


	<LI><P>incidences of domestic violence may be decreased.


	<LI>Counselors for batterers report that treatment for domestic violence alone is not enough --batterers with addictions must also receive substance abuse -treatment as well.
</UL>


[<A HREF="DV_Index.html">Back</A>]

<p><br>

<hr>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0"ISMAP ></A>
<BR>
