<TITLE>Sample Op-Ed Or Letter-To-The-Editor</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>


<H3>Domestic Violence and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>Sample Op-Ed Or Letter-To-The-Editor</H2>
</center>

<P>You can take the following body of this Op-Ed or Letter-to-the-
Editor and add local examples and statistics. <br>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.

<FORM method=POST action="DV_Op-EdOutput.nclk">
<hr>

<P><B>ALCOHOL AND DRUG Treatment is Crucial TO REDUCE  HOMELESSNESS</B>


<P>For many men, their homes are their castles. But for many women in the United States, these &quot;castles&quot; are filled with pain and fear. These women are the victims of domestic violence and most of them feel far from secure in their homes, knowing their spouses could strike at any time. While the attacks of battering are often unpredictable, many women know that when their husbands abuse alcohol and drugs, the beatings will be worse. In fact, alcohol and drugs are involved in up to 50 percent of all spousal abuse cases.


<P>Experts says that some men use these substances to give themselves permission to be more violent. Therefore, it is no surprise that such attacks are all the more severe.  Domestic violence actually accounts for almost 100,000 days of hospitalizations in this nation, 30,000 emergency room visits, and 40,000 doctors appointments each year, according to a national crime victimization survey done by the Department of Justice. Yet until recently, many victims have felt they could not tell medical personnel the truth behind their injuries, fearing for their own safety and for their children.  But today, more and more domestic violence victims are beginning to speak out -- and the country is beginning to listen. The brutal murder of domestic-violence victim Nicole Brown Simpson has made it impossible for people to look the other way anymore.


<P>While this growing attention to this issue is crucial, that alone is not enough. As a nation it is important that we not only create avenues for women to voice their ordeals, we need to respond with viable escapes from their ongoing nightmares. We can do this by treating batterers -- both for their violent patterns and for their substance abuse addictions. As the country reforms its health care system, we must ensure that proper substance abuse services are available to all who need them.

 
<P>For more information on how you can help make a difference, contact <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Organization" VALUE="Your Organization"> at <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">

<br><BR><BR>
<P>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Name" VALUE="Your name" SIZE=35><br>
<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Title" VALUE="Your Title"><br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><INPUT TYPE="submit" VALUE="Generate a letter">
<INPUT TYPE="reset" VALUE="Clear the letter"><br></center>
