<TITLE>FACTS ABOUT HOMELESSNESS</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>


<H3>Homelessness and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>FACTS ABOUT HOMELESSNESS</H2></center>


<P><B>The fact is. . .</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>--As many as 7 million people in the United States today are 
homeless, according to estimates by the federal government.


<P>--Half of all homeless adults--that is 3.5 million Americans--have 
a drug or alcohol problem, cites the National Coalition for the 
Homeless (NCH).


<P>--There are not enough alcohol and drug treatment services 
available for homeless people with addictions -- 80 percent of 
local treatment programs surveyed by the NCH were forced to turn 
people away. (What is the treatment capacity versus the need in 
your area?)


<P>--Homeless people with untreated substance abuse problems are at a 
higher risk for HIV infection and are more likely to have serious 
health problems and severe mental illness, reports NCH. Homeless 
people are more likely to be arrested, to be victimized on the 
streets or to suffer an early death.


<P>Many homeless people who undergo treatment for their addictions are 
able to move off the streets into temporary or permanent housing.  
For instance:


<P>--The Harbor House, a Salvation Army shelter in St. Louis, 
Missouri, provides two treatment programs for homeless people with 
substance abuse problems. Seventy-five percent of graduates from 
both programs go on to secure stable jobs and housing.


<P>--Clean and Sober Streets, a Washington. D.C.-based drug and 
alcohol treatment and rehabilitation community serving homeless 
people, said at least 70 percent of their graduates stay clean 
after graduating from the program and move into their own houses.


<P>--At the O'Hara Outreach Program for homeless men in Chicago, 95 
percent of the clients have diagnosable substance abuse problems. 
About half of these men receive treatment and of them, 75 percent 
successfully graduate and go on to obtain housing.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<br>
