<TITLE>SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>

<H3>Homelessness and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>
SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</H2></center>

If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.

<HR>
<FORM ACTION="Homeless_PressOutput.nclk" METHOD=POST>
CONTACT: <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Contact" VALUE="Your Name" SIZE=35><br>
PHONE:  <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">



<P>PROVIDING ALCOHOL AND DRUG TREATMENT REDUCES HOMELESSNESS


<P>BOSTON--Paul Smith makes his home on the streets. Most nights he can be found on a park bench, huddled beneath a 
tattered blanket with a whiskey bottle clutched close to his chest. 
(Replace with an example of homelessness in your area.)


<P>Although this is a lonely situation, Paul is far from alone. Close 
to seven million single adults in the United States today are 
homeless, according to statistics released by the federal 
government. And half--or about 3.5 million--of these men and women 
have alcohol and drug addictions, reports the National Coalition 
for the Homeless.


<P>But despite these high numbers, treatment options are very limited 
for people who can't afford to pay. And those programs that do 
exist can not begin to handle the pressing need for their services. 
In fact, a survey of homeless treatment programs conducted by the 
National Coalition found that fully 80 percent of them were forced 
to turn people away.


<P>This means that for a lot of homeless people, their chances of 
breaking the cycle of addiction and getting into permanent homes 
look bleak.  But for those men and women who are fortunate enough 
to get into a treatment program, their odds of getting off the 
streets greatly improve.


<P>For instance, 70 percent of the graduates of Clean and Sober 
Streets, a drug and alcohol treatment community for disadvantaged 


<P>people in Washington, D.C., kick their addictions and move into 
permanent housing. And the Harbor House, a Salvation Army homeless 
shelter in St. Louis. Missouri, has a 75 percent success rate for 
graduates of its two treatment programs.


<P>&quot;We know that treatment is effective in getting homeless people 
with addictions clean and into their own homes,&quot; said William 
Arena, director of Green's Shelter for Men in Boston. &quot;The problem 
is, many Americans say they don't want to pay to provide such 
services for the homeless. What they fail to realize is that they 
are paying for the problem anyway -- just in health care and 
disability,&quot; he said. (Replace with quote from director of your 
local shelter.)


<P>&quot;If we are going to tackle homelessness and other social problems 
facing our country today, people have to wake up and realize that 
now--as the country moves to develop a national health plan--we 
must ensure that substance abuse treatment services are available 
for all who need them,&quot; Green said.

<p><BR><HR>
