<TITLE>SAMPLE OP-ED</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>



<H3>Homelessness and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>SAMPLE OP-ED</H2></center>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.
<hr>

<FORM method=POST action="/JTO/issues/Homeless/Homeless_SampleOutput.nclk">
<P><B>ALCOHOL AND DRUG Treatment is Crucial TO REDUCE  HOMELESSNESS</B>


<P>For seven million Americans today, home is a cardboard box or a park bench or the back seat of an abandoned car. Or if they are lucky, a bed in an emergency shelter.Homelessness is sweeping the nation, as more and more people find it increasingly difficult to find affordable housing. And about half--or 3.5 million--of these men and women suffer from alcohol or drug addictions, according to the National Coalition for the Homeless, making it hard for them to hold down a job.


<P>Those with substance abuse problems who do make it into temporary shelters are steered by staff into detox programs, but severely limited space in these programs means that not everyone gets the services they need. In fact, a survey of treatment programs that serve homeless persons by NCH found that 80 percent of them are forced to turn people away.


<P>This means that for a lot of homeless people, their chances of breaking the cycle of addiction look bleak.  This is tragic, since many programs treating homeless alcoholics and addicts have been successful in getting them off the streets and into permanent homes.


<P>For instance, The Harbor House, a Salvation Army shelter in St. Louis, Missouri, provides two treatment programs for homeless people with substance abuse problems. Seventy-five percent of graduates from both programs go on to secure stable jobs and housing. And Clean and Sober Streets, a Washington. D.C.-based drug and alcohol treatment and rehabilitation community serving homeless people, said at least 70 percent of their graduates stay clean after graduating from the program and move into their own homes.


<P>But the waiting lists for programs like as these are long. And for those addicts who live on the streets, every day can feel like an eternity.


<P>That's why as the nation undertakes health care reform, we must make sure that adequate alcohol and drug treatment services are available for all Americans. You can help educate your public officials about the link between substance abuse problems and homelessness. The fact is, we all ay for substance abuse problems -- the choice is whether to pay to treat these problems and help people go on to lead productive lives and get permanent homes or whether we would rather pay for the disability and health care costs for men and women who remain homeless due to untreated addictions.


<P>For more information on how you can help make a difference, contact <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Organization" VALUE="Your Organization"> at <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">

<br><BR><BR>
<P>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Name" VALUE="Your name" SIZE=35><br>
<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Title" VALUE="Your Title"><br>
<br>
