<TITLE>SAMPLE OP-ED or LETTER TO THE EDITOR</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
<BR>

<HR>
<H3>HIV-Infection and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>SAMPLE OP-ED or LETTER TO THE EDITOR</H2></center>
<FORM ACTION="HIV_SampleOutput.nclk" METHOD=POST>

<P>You can take the following body of the Op-Ed or Letter to the Editor and add to it local examples and statistics to make it pertinent to your community.<br>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.


<hr>
<P><B>ALCOHOL AND DRUG TREATMENT IS CRUCIAL TO REDUCE THE SPREAD OF HIV</B>


<P>In the waiting room of the HIV clinic at Milwaukee Hospital, clients come from a wide range of backgrounds.


<P>But they are all hoping for the same thing -- to be told that they are not infected with HIV.


<P>Unfortunately, about one in every 250 men and women will not be so lucky.


<P>Today, close to one million men and women in the United States have HIV, the virus that leads to AIDS.  And about two million people put themselves at risk for contracting the virus every day. No longer considered the disease of only homosexual men, today the possibility of AIDS affects everybody.


<P>Researchers now know that injecting drugs and engaging in unprotected sex are two of the leading culprits that put people at risk for HIV.  This is because injecting drug users often share the same needle with other people and if there is any infected blood in the needle, it is easily passed between addicts. Close to 35 percent of people with HIV inject intravenous drugs, according to the Centers for Disease Control.


<P>But not all addicts who are HIV-positive inject drugs. Some people while drunk or high, may take more chances when they have sex and are less likely to use condoms. Recent studies by the CDC in New York and Miami found that young crack users who had never injected drugs or had male homosexual encounters were still at very high risk for HIV. And women were particularly vulnerable to the virus. This is because studies have shown that the virus is more easily transmitted from man to woman than from woman to man. Of those crack addicts surveyed, 32 percent of the women in New York tested positive for HIV and 45 percent of the women in Miami, compared with 11 percent of the men in both cities.


<P>Those who have already contracted HIV can only hope for a miracle. But for people with alcohol and drug problems who continue to engage in risky behaviors and thus far have managed to allude the virus, there is still time for them to seek treatment.


<P>That's why as the nation undergoes health reform, it is crucial that we ensure an adequate substance abuse benefit is available to all who need it. Somebody's life might be counting on it. You can get the message out about the link between substance abuse and HIV and the need to provide addicts with access to treatment.


<P>For more information on how you can help make a difference, contact <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Organization" VALUE="Your Organization"> at <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">

<br><br><br>
<P>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Name" VALUE="Your name" SIZE=35><br>
<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Title" VALUE="Your Title"><br>

<hr>
<center><INPUT TYPE="submit" VALUE="Generate a letter">
<INPUT TYPE="reset" VALUE="Clear the letter">
</center>
</FORM>
<p>
