<HEAD>

<TITLE>SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND OLDER AMERICANS: The Facts</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
</center>

<BR>

<H3>SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND OLDER AMERICANS</H3>
<H2>THE FACT IS...</H2>
<hr>
<UL>

<LI> Alcohol, the most abused substance in the United States, is the drug of choice for older Americans. (American Association of Retired Persons. 1994 fact sheet on Alcohol Abuse Among  Older People.)<BR><BR>


<LI> Between 1.1 and 2.3 million older Americans have problems with alcohol. (Alcoholism and Other Drug Dependencies, by Stanley Haugland, MD, in Primary Care. June 1989.)<BR><BR>
 

<LI> An estimated 70 percent of hospital admissions of older people in 1991 were for alcohol-related problems. (Report by the U.S. House of Representatives, Select Committee on Aging Hearing, Feb. 4, 1992.)<BR><BR>

 

<LI> Substance abuse among the elderly accounts for a full 23 percent of Medicare costs. (Study by the Center for Alcohol and Substance Addiction, released in May, 1994.)<BR><BR>

<LI> Taxpayers pick up the tab for older Americans who have alcohol-related problems. In fact, they spend more than $230 million a year in Medicare costs for these problems. (Alcohol Causes as Many Stays for Elderly as Heart Attacks, in The New York Times,  Sept. 12, 1993. p. 17.)<BR><BR>

<LI> A typical hospital stay for alcohol abuse costs more than $4,500 a year. (Ibid.)<BR><BR>
 

<LI> Alcohol-related problems put more older Americans in the hospital than heart attacks.(Ibid.)<BR><BR>
 

<LI> Presently, older Americans consume 25 to 30 percent of all prescription drugs. This consumption rate becomes problematic when prescription drugs are combined with alcohol and other nonprescriptions. (Drug Abuse Among the Elderly: Covert Problem, by S. L. Sheahan, J. Hendricks and S. J. Coons, 1989.)<BR><BR>

<LI> When people age, their metabolism slows down and alcohol and drugs remain in the body longer. This results in an increased risk of overdose. (National Institute on Drug Abuse.)<BR><BR>

<LI> Addiction experts say that 15 percent of Americans over age 65 will develop an alcohol problem when they retire or when their spouse dies. (Alcoholism Among the Elderly, by Judy Licht, in the Washington Post Special Section, April 26, 1994. p. 14.)<BR><BR>

<LI> Widowers over age 75 have the highest rate of alcoholism in the country. (U.S. House of Representatives.)<BR><BR>

<LI> Older alcoholics who suffer from depression are the highest risk group for committing suicide in the United States. (National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism, 1992.)<BR><BR>

 
<LI> Thirty percent of Alcoholics Anonymous members are over age 65. (Alcoholism and Other Drug Dependencies, by Stanley Haugland, MD, in Primary Care. June 1989.)<BR><BR>

<LI> Researchers have found that older people actually respond better to treatment for alcoholism than do younger drinkers. (National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism, 1992.)<BR><BR>


<CENTER>
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER>



</BODY>
