<TITLE>SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND OLDER AMERICANS: SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
</center>

<BR>
<center>
<H3>SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND OLDER AMERICANS</H3>

<H2>SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</H2>
</center>

<P>You can tailor the following press release with local examples and statistics and send it to your community newspaper with a note suggesting they do a story on this topic.
<p>
<hr>
<P>
<center>
<B>SOME SENIORS USE ALCOHOL TO DEAL WITH LONELINESS</B>
</center>


<P>	CHICAGO -- Since his wife died six months ago, Richard Moore, aged 76, has found himself drinking more and drinking earlier. Lately, he even forgets to shower and change his clothes. (REPLACE WITH A LOCAL EXAMPLE.)<br>
  Like Richard, between 1.1 and 2.3 million senior citizens use alcohol to deal with their loneliness and boredom. In fact, widowers over the age of 75 have the highest rate of alcoholism in the country, according to a report released in 1992 by the U.S. House of Representatives Select Committee on Aging.<br> Yet drinking problems among the elderly are often difficult for doctors to detect -- often because the symptoms mirror those of old age. However, such problems are crucial to address, since people's metabolism slows as they age and therefore, they are more strongly affected by alcohol than their younger counterparts.<br>
 	A 1993 study that appeared in the Journal of the American Medical Association 
found that alcoholism among older people is such a widespread problem that more 
seniors are hospitalized for alcohol-related problems that for heart attacks.
And older alcoholics who are depressed comprise the highest risk group for committing suicide, reports the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism (NIAAA). In addition, 30 percent of all Alcoholics Anonymous members are over 50 years of age. <br>
 The good news is that older people with alcohol addictions have the highest rate of success in becoming sober after treatment, NIAAA reports. The key is to educate people about the problem of alcohol abuse among older Americans and to make sure that there are adequate treatment options available to them.<br>
<p>
<p>
<hr>


