<HEAD>
    <TITLE>1995 National Survey: Fact Sheet</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>FACT SHEET: THE NATION'S SUBSTANCE ABUSE PROBLEM</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
--Each year, there are more deaths and disabilities from  substance abuse
than from any other preventable cause. Of the two million U.S. deaths each
year, one in four is attributable to alcohol, illicit drug or tobacco use.
(Substance Abuse: The Nation's Number One Health Problem, Brandeis University,
1993.)<BR>
<BR>
--Nearly one of every four Americans is directly affected by the alcohol
or drugdependency of a family member, friend or co-worker. (U.S. Department
of Health and Human Services, 1995.)<BR>
<BR>
--The latest National Household Survey on Drug Abuse found: 
<UL>
<LI>An estimated 13 million Americans use illegal drugs, and 10 million
use marijuana. 
<LI>13 million Americans had five or more drinks in one sitting on five
ormore occasions in one month. 60 million Americans -- including 4 million
people aged 12 to 17 -- smoke cigarettes. (1994 National Household Survey
on Drug Abuse.)
</UL>
<BR>
--Over a third of all eighth graders have used some illicit drug, including
inhalants, while over 40 percent of all 10th graders and nearly 50 percent
of all 12th graders have done so. (Office of Juvenile Justice Delinquency
and Prevention, 1995.)<BR>
<BR>
--Fewer youth today than in 1992 believe that marijuana use is harmful to
their health. (U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, 1995.)<BR>
<BR>
--During the mid-1980s, the public began to understand the devastation of
drug use and addiction. Nationwide, drug prevention efforts came together
in schools,media, the workplace, and communities, resulting in dramatic
shifts in attitudestoward drugs and declines of more than 50 percent in
the number of new triers and non-addicted users in all segments of the population.
(Partnership for a Drug-Free America, 1994.)<BR>
<BR>
--Despite this success, however, diminishing national leadership, public
focus and resource allocation threaten future success. (Partnership for
a Drug-Free America, 1994.)<BR>
<BR>
--The United States spends about $268 billion on alcohol and drug problems
a year -- that's $675 for every man, woman and child in the country. (Lewis,
Ed.D., Social and Health Economic Services, Ltd., 1992)<BR>
<BR>
--The amount this country spends of health care each year could be reduced
by $90.4 billion if alcohol and drug problems were prevented before they
started. (U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Alcohol, Drug Abuse
and Mental Health Administration, 1992.)<BR>
<BR>
--Each day 800,000 people receive services in a special alcohol or drug
program.Nevertheless, only about one-fourth of those needing alcohol or
drug treatment get it. (Substance Abuse: The Nation's Number One Health
Problem, Brandeis University, 1993.)<BR>
<BR>
--Alcohol-related driving crashes are the leading cause of death for adolescentsand
young adults in the United States. In fact, in 1993 approximately three
million people were injured in motor vehicle crashes and close to 40,000
died. (National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 1994.)<BR>
<BR>
--More than 1.7 million people are the victims of alcohol-related crimes
in the United States each year. And over 4,000 people die as a result of
alcohol-related violence annually. (National Public Research Institute,
1994)<BR>
<BR>
--As many as 83 percent of arrestees in the United States had used illicit
substances within the 48 hours prior to their arrest. (Drug Use Forecasting,
1993.)<BR>
<BR>
--About 70 percent of all illicit drug users are employed. (U.S. Department
of Labor, 1990.)<BR>
<BR>
--Close to 35 percent of all AIDS cases are associated with drug injection.
In addition, more than 80 percent of all HIV-positive women inject drugs
or have sexual partners who do. (Center for Disease Control, 1992.)<BR>
<BR>
Date:  11/6/95<BR>
