<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>1995 National Survey: Highlights</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>JOIN TOGETHER 1995 NATIONAL SURVEY HIGHLIGHTS </CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
Join Together surveyed 4,200 leaders of community anti-drug abuse coalitions
fighting substance abuse around the country last summer to learn about their
activities, views and impact. Here are some of the things respondents said:<BR>
<BR>
Local leaders believe the substance abuse problem is either not improving
(48%) or getting worse( 36%). For the first time, people in rural communities
are as concerned as those in the big cities. Only 16 % of community leaders
think the problem is improving.<BR>
<BR>
When asked to rate how key leaders are responding to increasing substance
abuse problems, the local coalition leaders charge that most key elected
officials arepaying LESS attention to this problem. Fifty four percent (54%)
say that Congress is paying less attention, and  37% say that their governors
and state elected officials are paying less attention to substance abuse
than 2 years ago.In contrast, 29% say that mayors have INCREASED  their
attention to substance abuse.<BR>
<BR>
Business and labor fared even worse from coalition leaders, with their performance
rated  fair to poor by 79% and 88% respectively. Media and religiousgroups
 also received fair to poor marks by 64% and 69% respectively.<BR>
<BR>
Community coalition leaders strongly support public policy changes to prevent
and reduce substance abuse: 90% support restrictions on alcohol advertising,
92%call for lower legal blood alcohol limits for drivers, and 80% support
immediateaccess to drug treatment for everyone who needs it. Further, 77%
strongly opposelegalization of drugs. <BR>
<BR>
Access to treatment is critical to solving substance abuse:  In communities
where access to treatment is increasing (31%), leaders are more likely to
say the problem is getting better or remaining the same; conversely, in
communities where access to treatment is decreasing (30%),  people say the
problem is getting worse.<BR>
<BR>
The Federal government's role in fostering the community coalition movement
is essential.  Many community coalitions (38%) are highly dependent on federal
money, which is currently on the chopping block. Only about 22% of coalition
funds comes from state governments.  Recognizing the need for additional
money, a growing number (24%)  of coalitions diversified their funding base
over the past two years.<BR>
<BR>
The American tradition of neighbors joining together to solve community
problems, like substance abuse, is flourishing. Over the last two years,
49% of coalition leaders report that citizen participation is growing and
new coalitions are forming to deal with substance abuse, and related problems
like HIV, teen smoking and gang violence.<BR>
<BR>
Date:  11/6/95<BR>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC=
"../../../MapServe/footer.gif" WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=
middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0"ISMAP ><BR>
