<HEAD>
    <TITLE>1995 National Survey: Press Release</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
You can localize the following press release with some examples of substance
abuse problems -- and solutions -- at work in your community. Send this
release along with a  copy of the key findings from the national survey
to the editor atyour local newspaper.<BR>
<BR>
MORE LOCAL GROUPS NEED TO JOIN IN ANTI-SUBSTANCE ABUSE EFFORTS<BR>
<BR>
STAMFORD, Conn.--Beer. Wine Coolers. Marijuana: These are some of the drugs
of choice for the kids who live in our community.  <BR>
<BR>
The fact is that substance abuse is on the rise among youth -- not only
here in Stamford (replace with your community's name) but also across the
country.   And just at a time when we need them the most, many key leaders
and institutionswhose support is crucial to successful anti-drug efforts
have been withdrawing from the fight.        <BR>
<BR>
A recent national survey documents this alarming trend and sends out a warning
call for these groups to rejoin the effort.  The survey, conducted by Join
Together, a national resource center helping communities fight substance
abuse, found that critical participation from some groups -- including politicians,
business leaders, labor, churches and the media--is lacking.        <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We will be losing another generation of our kids to alcohol and drugs
if these and other key groups do not help us get the message out about all
the dangers associated with substance abuse,&quot; said Michael Smith, head
of the local Anti-Substance Abuse Coalition, which is run through the Mayor's
Office (replace with your organization's name). <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Perhaps some of these groups assumed that the war on drugs was won
when abuse levels dropped in the 1980s, but the reality is that the problem
is increasing again among our children and we need everyone in the community
to take an activerole in our anti-substance abuse efforts to make them truly
effective,&quot; Smith said.<BR>
<BR>
Some groups in Stamford that are heavily involved in local efforts to reduce
alcohol and drug abuse have been able to accomplish great things. For instance
. . . .  (give some examples here of effective anti-substance abuse efforts
taken on by local business, recreation groups, clergy, etc.)         To
find out how you can help fight alcohol and drugs in Stamford (replace with
your community's name), call (your organization's name) at (your phone number).#
# #<BR>
<BR>
Date:  11/6/95<BR>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC=
"../../../MapServe/footer.gif" WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=
middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0"ISMAP ><BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="../../../default.html">JTO</A> | 
<A HREF="../../index.html">Index</A>
| <A HREF="../../search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="../../comments.html">Comments</A>
| <A HREF="../../help.html">Help</A><BR>
