<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Tobacco Survey: Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/policy.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/policy.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" ALIGN=bottom BORDER="0" ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/policy/policy.html">Policy</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/panel.html">Panels</A> | <A HREF="/jto/policy/surveys.html">Surveys</A> |<A HREF="/news/alerts/Latest_News.qry?MediaAction=True&Summaries=On&Max=7&Last=30">Alerts</A> | <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/pol">Archives</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/links.html">Links</A></FONT></CENTER>

<H2><CENTER>Surveys: <BR>
Tobacco Retail Outlet Counting Project</CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
<B>November 9, 1995 </B>
<H3>Hundreds of Volunteers Canvas<BR>
Neighborhoods Near Schools and <BR>
Find Over 1,000 Tobacco Outlets</H3>
<BR>
Join Together, a national resource for communities fighting substance abuse
funded by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, recently conducted a nationwide
survey on underage access to tobacco. Community volunteers acted individually,
or formed teams, and canvassed their neighborhoods to measure the extent
of cigarette availability within a quarter-mile radius of schools. They
counted the number of tobacco sales locations in convenience, grocery and
liquor stores, gas stations, restaurants, and vending machines. Community
teams recorded results on a summary sheet, and sent them back to Join Together
for analysis and development of this report. <BR>
<BR>
The importance of tobacco control projects centers around the fact that
each day, more than 3,000 young people begin to smoke-or more than 1 million
each year, and that number is on the rise. The Surgeon General has stated
that most effective preventive programs to reduce youth smoking are communitywide
ones that combine education and public policy approaches. The placement
of tobacco retail outlets near schools (proximity and advertising), especially
elementary schools, has potentially harmful implications for youth, since
these factors interact to encourage youth to take up the habit. This Join
Together project is a first step in raising the level of awareness as to
youth access to tobacco among community citizens and youth, as well as setting
the stage for further communitywide public policy action. <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="participant.html">Find Out Who Participated<BR>
</A><BR>
<A HREF="stats.html">Get the Survey Results<BR>
</A><BR>
<A HREF="stories.html">Read Stories From Communities</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="../../../forum/coffee.html">Discuss the Issue!</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
For additional information, contact:<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:astrid@jointogether.org">Astrid Kozel</A> of Join Together<BR><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER>
