    <TITLE>Join Together Tobacco Project</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H2><CENTER>JOIN TOGETHER TOBACCO PROJECT DESCRIPTION </CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
Purpose Of This Project: For communities to count the number of outlets
(i.e. convenience stores, drug stores, grocery stores, gas stations and
vending machines, etc.) that sell cigarettes within a quarter-mile radius
of a public school. You can then use this information to determine the underage
tobacco policies and priorities of these stores. 
<H3>Why You Should Participate:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To measure the extent of cigarette availability near schools in your
community. 
<LI>To release this information to the press. 
<LI>To raise public awareness in your community about underage smoking.
</OL>
<H3>HOW TO GET STARTED: </H3>
<OL>
<LI>Use the FACT SHEET, the PROJECT DESCRIPTION and the suggestions on HOW
TO ORGANIZE LOCAL GROUPS to alert residents to the problem of youth access
to tobacco and get them to join up with you to assess the extent of the
problem locally. Be sure to include youth in your efforts! 
<LI>Select a school (elementary, middle or high school) in your community
that will be your base. Pick a day and distribute copies of the WORKSHEET
we've provided to participants. Ask them to go out and count the number
of stores and vending machines within a quarter-mile radius of that school
that sell tobacco products and record their results of these worksheets.
Tally the results from all the worksheets onto the RESULTS FORM for the
scope of tobacco availability in this area. Disseminate the results to the
media and other interested groups and also fax a copy back to Join Together.
<LI>Use the SAMPLE PITCH LETTER to interest your local media in coming along
with you to compile this data. This could make a good news story in your
local paper or on a local television station. Suggest a newspaper photographer
accompany you as well. 
<LI>Arrange an editorial board meeting with the editorial editor of your
local newspaper and use the national statistics from the fact sheet, as
well as your local findings, as talking points. Ask the newspaper to run
an editorial suggesting ACTION STEPS the community can take to reduce the
problem. For instance, the editorial might urge retailers to remove cigarette
displays that appeal to youth and to place tobacco products behind counters
to make them less available. Tailor the SAMPLE OP-ED with your findings
and ask the newspaper to run it to encourage residents to get involved in
local efforts to reduce youth access to tobacco. 
<LI>Use the examples of WHAT OTHERS HAVE DONE for suggestions on how to
tackle the availability of tobacco in your area. Use the RESOURCES and FURTHER
READING to develop your own communitywide strategy. 
</OL>
<P><CENTER><BR>
<A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0" ISMAP
