    <TITLE>Tobacco and Youth: The Facts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<center><H3>Tobacco and Youth</H3>
<P><H2>THE FACT IS. . .</H2> <BR></center>
<BR>
--Each day, three thousand youth in the United States become regular smokers
- that's more than 1 million each year. Many of these youth will die prematurely
from smoking-related illnesses. 1 <BR>
<BR>
--Smoking among eighth graders increased by 30% between 1991 - 1994. 2 <BR>
<BR>
--Although it is now illegal in all states to sell cigarettes to persons
under age 18, kids have easy access to tobacco products. It has been estimated
that underage youth can purchase cigarettes successfully 70%-80% of the
time over the counter, and 90%-100% of the time through vending machines.
3 <BR>
<BR>
--Each year, merchants illegally sell minors 947 million packs of cigarettes
and 26 million containers of spitting tobacco. These products are worth
$1.26 billion, and they generate $221 million in tobacco industry profits.
4 <BR>
<BR>
--About 80 percent of adolescent smokers report having at least one close
friend who smokes. And about half of adolescent smokers have parents who
smoke. 5 <BR>
<BR>
--Cigarettes are seen as a &quot;gateway drug&quot; meaning cigarette use
is likely to precede the use of alcohol or illegal drugs. One recent study
found that current youth smokers, aged 12-21 years, were three times more
likely to have used alcohol within the past 30 days, and were thirteen times
more likely to have used marijuana than youth who had never smoked. 6 <BR>
<BR>
--Among young people, those with poorer grades and lower self images are
most likely to start using tobacco. 7 <BR>
<BR>
--Most young people who have smoked as few as 100 cigarettes in their lifetime
are addicted to nicotine and report that they want to quit but are unable
to do so. 8 <BR>
<BR>
--Since the start of the &quot;Old Joe&quot; campaign in 1988, Camel's share
of the illegal children's market has increased from 0.5% to 32.8%, representing
about $476 million in annual sales in 1991. (R.J. Reynolds spends an estimated
$22 million a year on Camel ads.) 9 <BR>
<BR>
SOURCES <BR>
<BR>
1--Pierce JP, Fiore MC, Novotny TE, et al. &quot;Trends in Cigarette Smoking
in the United States. Projections to the Year 2000.&quot; Journal of the
American Medical Association, Vol. 261, (1989). pp. 61-65. <BR>
<BR>
2--Monitoring the Future Study, released July, 1995. Conducted by the University
of Michigan Survey Research Center and funded under a series of research
grants from the National Institute on Drug Abuse. This study surveyed alcohol,
drug and tobacco use among high school seniors and eight- and tenth-grade
students. <BR>
<BR>
3-- &quot;Youth and Elders Against Tobacco Use-Youth Access To Tobacco Fact
Sheet.&quot; U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health
Service, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for
Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, Office on Smoking and Health,
March 1994. <BR>
<BR>
4-- Ibid. <BR>
<BR>
5 --Youth and Elders Against Tobacco Use. (See Footnote 3 above.) <BR>
<BR>
6 --Adapted by CESAR from data from JC Willard and CA Schoenborn. &quot;Relationship
Between Cigarette Smoking and Other Unhealthy Behaviors Among Our Nation's
Youth: United States, 1992.&quot; Advance Data, No. 263, April 1995. Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for Health Statistics.
<BR>
<BR>
7 --&quot;Preventing Tobacco Use Among Young People -- A Report of the Surgeon
General.&quot; U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health
Service, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for
Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, Office on Smoking and Health,
March 1994. <BR>
<BR>
8-- Ibid. <BR>
<BR>
9-- &quot;The Surgeon General's Report for Kids About Smoking.&quot; U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service, Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for Chronic Disease
Prevention and Health Promotion, Office on Smoking and Health, March 1994.
<BR>
<BR>
<center><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ISMAP><BR>
<BR>
