<TITLE>Tobacco: What Others Have Done</TITLE>

</HEAD>





	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>



<H3>Youth Access to Tobacco</H3>

<H2>WHAT OTHERS HAVE DONE. . .</H2>

</CENTER



<P>

Gloucester Prevention Network, Stop Using Nicotine (SUN) Coalition

Cigarette vending machines are banned in the sea-side town of Gloucester, Massachusetts, thanks to the efforts of four seventh grade girls there.  The girls, who wanted to keep their peers from smoking, circulated a petition among residents to get support for keeping vending machines out of the community. Then, with the help of the SUN Coalition, they submitted the petition to the city council and got them to pass a local ordinance. Now the neighboring town of Salem is also considering following Gloucester's lead. For more information, contact Phillip Salzman, Program Director of the Gloucester Prevention Network, or Pamela Dungan, Tobacco Control Coordinator, 96 Main Street, Gloucester, MA  01930.  Tel: (508) 281-0311.  





<P> "GROSS" -- Get Rid of Second Hand Smoke

Recognizing that illegal single cigarette sales lure youth to smoke, GROSS initiated a major letter writing campaign to state and federal agencies asking them to crack down on the problem.  The organization also sent copies of state laws to outlets that illegally sold single cigarettes, in an attempt to get them to stop. This campaign did successfully discourage many retailers from selling single cigarettes. For more information, contact Rob Perry or Joe Perry, Co-Chairmen, P.O. Box 765, Kiefer, OK  74041.  (918) 321-5077.





<P>The Uptown Coalition for Tobacco Control and Public Health.

A cigarette test-marketing campaign aimed at African American youth galvanized Philadelphia residents to action. Refusing to let their youngsters risk their health to sample the Uptown cigarettes, parents got together through the Uptown Coalition for Tobacco Control and Public Health and demanded the tobacco company  remove this product from their city. Supporting this effort were numerous local, state and national organizations. The coalition's efforts were ultimately successful: R.J. Reynolds finally agreed to remove Uptown cigarettes from the market.  For more information, contact Reverend Jesse Brown at (215) 225-5232.  





<P> "HORA" -- Hispanics On the Rise Again

The large number of cigarette advertisements on billboards in a Hispanic neighborhood in Perth Amboy, New Jersey, prompted a 17-year-old youth there to action. With the support of a group called HORA, he counted the number of cigarette billboards in his neighborhood and then went to the city council and asked them to replace these ads with ones that would send a more positive message to kids. (Source: "The Surgeon General's Report for Kids About Smoking." U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, Office on Smoking and Health,  March 1994.





<P>



<center>

<A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC=

"/MapServe/footer.gif" WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER=

"0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0" ISMAP ><BR>

