<TITLE>Tobacco: Further Reading</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
</center>

<BR>


<H3>Youth Access to Tobacco</H3>
<H2>FOR FURTHER READING:</H2>


<P>To learn more about the problem of underage access to tobacco, you may want to read some of the following books and articles:


<P><I>Preventing Tobacco Use Among Young People-A Report of the Surgeon General</I>, U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. Public Health Service.  Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 1994. Available from the CDC Office on Smoking and Health at (404) 488-5701


<P>"Youth & Tobacco Products Prevention Sourcebook." The Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP) in collaboration with the Office on Smoking and Health (OSH). Available from the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information: 
1-800-729-6686.


<P>"You Have the Right to Know: Tobacco." From National Families In Action,
2296 Henderson Mill Rd., Suite 204, Atlanta, GA  30345. (404) 934-6364.


<P>"Tobacco Free Youth: How to Reduce Sales to Minors In Your Community." Stanford Health Promotion Resource Center with the North Bay Health Resources Center, Petaluma, CA, 1992. Call (707) 762-4591.


<P>"Active Enforcement of Cigarette Control Laws in the Prevention of Cigarette Sales to Minors."  Jason JA, et al., Journal of the American Medical Association, December 11, 1991.  Vol. 266(22): pp. 3159-61.


<P>"Implementing Enforcement of Minors' Access to Tobacco Products and Other Youth Access Activities and Programs."  A Case Study presented by: Richard Boyd, Division of Alcohol and Tobacco, Department of Business and Professional Regulation, Tallahassee, FL; Marcia Nenno, American Cancer Society, Tampa, FL; and Jennie Hefelfinger, Office of Health Promotion and Wellness, Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services, Tallahassee, FL.  Contact R. Boyd at (904) 921-3034.


<P>"Media Strategies for Smoking Control-Guidelines." From a Consensus Workshop Conducted by The Advocacy Institute for the National Cancer Institute, January 1988.  
This publication addresses the basic principles of media advocacy, and includes strategies for gaining access to the media, and strategies for framing and seizing the symbols of the debate.  


<P>

