<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>College Alcohol Ads</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<H2>News Release</H2><HR>
May 7, 1996<BR>
<BR><B>Center for Science in the Public Interest</B><BR><BR>
CONTACT: <BR>George Hacker (202)332-9110 x343<BR>
Debra Erenberg (202)332-9110 x338<BR><BR>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>College Health Officials Flunk Tavern Ads That Promote Heavy Drinking</H2>

<H3>Demand Industry Standards for Responsible Advertising</H3></CENTER>

Bar and tavern advertisements that entice college students with the promise of cheap, abundant booze help fuel an epidemic in student binge drinking, according to an alliance concerned with alcohol abuse.<BR>

<BR>The Coalition to Reduce Binge Drinking today urged the National Licensed Beverage Association (NLBA) to adopt voluntary college newspaper advertising standards. It offered to work with the trade association to eliminate advertising that promotes heavy and daily drinking among students. The coalition letter was signed by 32 health officials from 27 college carnpuses. The NLBA is the national association representing bars, taverns, and other establishments licensed to serve alcohol.<BR>

<BR>"Too many campus newspapers fail to recognize that these binge-pushing ads and promotional gimmicks subvert the academic mission of the university and the well-being of students," said George Hacker, head of the Alcohol Policies Project of the Center for Science in the Public Interest (CSPI), which coordinates the coalition. Among promotions CSPI and the coalition cite as particularly targeted at encouraging heavy drinking:

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Penny- and nickel-drink nights
	<LI>All-you-can-drink specials
	<LI>Ladies' nights
	<LI>"Crawls" with specials at several different bars,
	<LI>Ads that expand drinking time to include traditional "study nights"
</UL>

The coalition also sent an <B><A HREF="/JTO/news/press/cspi_ltr.html">open letter</A></B> to the editors of college newspapers asking that they consider restricting or barring from their publications ads that promote irresponsible alcohol consumption.

<BR><BR>"We're not saying, 'stop advertising,' explained Janine Gracey, a prevention specialist at the University of Kansas and a member of the coalition, "but we want local bars to look for alternatives to telling kids it's okay to drink until they pass out."

<BR><BR>According to Dennis McBee, alcohol and drug education coordinator at the University of Vermont, "It' s hard enough to deal with student drinking problems without this constant assault of ads telling students to 'get tanked' or promoting discounts for women based on how short their skirts are. It' s infuriating to see the health and safety risks that these bars so glibly promote."

<BR><BR>"Newspapers at quite a few schools already choose either not to run alcohol ads at all or accept only those that promote responsible alcohol consumption," noted CSPI's Hacker. "We are calling on college editors to reject a binge culture that causes havoc on campus and contributes to countless personal and academic tragedies."

<BR><BR>The advertising standards proposed by the coalition are similar to voluntary guidelines currently adopted by national associations representing beer, wine, and distilled spirits producers, such as refraining from advertising "all-you-can-drink-nights" or free or discounted drinks in college newspapers. They would also include principles that have been adopted by responsible members of the hospitality industry, such as training beverage servers to recognize signs of intoxication and to refuse service to inebriated patrons.

<BR><BR>In a 1995 study, the Harvard University School of Public Health found that students who binge-drink suffer many adverse effects in addition to hangovers, among them hospitalization for alcohol overdose, trouble with police, property destruction, injury, unprotected sexual activity, and missed classes. Even non-binging students and others in the community are affected: in the Harvard study, 81 percent of students on "high-binging" campuses reported a sexual or other assault, property damage, having to "baby-sit" a drunken friend, or having study or sleep interrupted because of heavy drinking by other students.

<BR><BR>The study defined binge drinking as five or more consecutive drinks one or more times in two weeks for men and four or more consecutive drinks in two weeks for women. A campus was considered "high-binging" if more than half of all students reported binge-drinking.

<BR><BR>Responsible marketing of alcohol products has been a subject of increasing national concern. The White House cover letter to Congress introducing the 1996 National Drug Control Strategy, released on April 29, 1996, cites marketing to young people of products that "legitimate and elevate the use of alcohol, tobacco, and illicit drugs" as a reason young people continue to use drugs.

<BR><BR>CSPI is a leading nonprofit health-education and advocacy organization supported in large part by the 750,000 subscribers to its Nutrition Action Healthletter. It is widely recognized for studies in the fields of nutrition, food safety and alcohol policy.

</BODY>
</HTML>
