<HTML> <HEAD>

<TITLE>Open Letter</TITLE>

</HEAD> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H3>An Open Letter to the Editors of College Newspapers from the Coalition to Reduce Binge Drinking</H3></CENTER>

May 10, 1996<BR><BR>

Dear Student Editors:<BR><BR>


College and university-sponsored newspapers play a unique and important role in campus life. They serve the college community by informing students, giving voice to student concerns and raising issues for consideration and debate. In what you choose to publish, you influence student life and attitudes. It is because of this influence that we are asking you to adopt editorial policies (if your paper doesn't already have them) which would prohibit alcohol advertisements that promote heavy and abusive drinking.<BR><BR>

Binge drinking has reached epidemic levels in college communities across the country. A 1995 Harvard University study by Dr. Henry Wechsler and others found that almost half of all college students binge drink. In that context, advertisements by local bars that promote penny or nickel drinks, all-you-can-drink specials, ladies nights, and weeknight discounts represent an assault on the academic community and the purposes for which students attend college. Those ads encourage abusive alcohol consumption and contribute to alcohol-related problems that cause serious consequences for students and the community.<BR><BR>

According to the Harvard study, students who binge drink reported adverse effects including: hospitalization for alcohol overdose, trouble with police, damaging property, physical injury, unplanned or unprotected sexual activity, blackouts, falling behind on school work, missing classes, doing something they later regretted, arguing with friends, and hangovers.<BR><BR>

Binging also has "second-hand" effects on non-binging students and community members. 87% of students on "high-binging" campuses, where more than half of students binge drink, reported one or more of the following problems as a result of anothers' binge drinking: being the victim of sexual assault or "date rape"; being pushed, hit, or assaulted; having property damaged; being insulted or humiliated, being confronted with unwanted sexual advances; being in a serious argument or quarrel, having to "baby-sit" a drunken friend; and having study or sleep interrupted.<BR><BR>

Publishing advertisements for "bar crawls" or "quarter pitchers" sends the message that college and heavy drinking are inextricably linked. By refusing to accept ads that promote heavy drinking, you can help establish more sensible drinking norms, revitalize students' academic missions, and contribute to the health of the college community.<BR><BR>

For technical assistance in developing policies restricting alcohol advertising or for more information on binge drinking in general, please contact Debra Erenberg at the Alcohol Policies Project of the Center for Science in the Public Interest at 202-332-9100, ext. 338.<BR><BR>

Sincerely, <BR><BR><BR><B>The Coalition to Reduce Binge Drinking</B>
<BR>1875 Connecticut Ave, N. W., Suite 300<BR>
Washington, D.C. 20009-5728<BR><BR>


<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> </BODY> </HTML>
