<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>POP</TITLE>


</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<H3>Points of Presence (POP)</H3>
</CENTER>
Points of Presence is the number of local dial-up phone numbers a national ISP offers.   Almost always, each point of presence is actually a series of phone lines, each with a modem capable of connecting the customer's computer with the ISPs Internet gateway.  For example, if an ISP says it has 300 points of presence across the nation, it means that there are 300 local dial-up numbers in various cities and states.
<BR><BR>
<B>Caveat</B><BR>
While many major national providers own their POPs, some of them lease networks from other providers to supplement their national or regional POP coverage.  SprintNet and Compuserve's vast national modem networks are the two such networks that are commonly leased by other ISPs.  Usually, but not always, you will pay an hourly surcharge to access your ISP over another company's network connection.<BR><BR>

<A HREF="isptable.html"><B>Back</B></A> to ISP Table

