<HEAD>
    <TITLE>About Mailing Lists</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/forum.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/forum.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A></CENTER><P><CENTER><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/forum/coffee.html">Coffee House</A> | <A HREF="/jto/forum/lists/email.html">EmailLists</A> | <A HREF="/jto/forum/jtolink/links.html">Links</A></FONT></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>About Mailing Lists</CENTER>
</H2>

<BLOCKQUOTE><B>What are mailing lists?</B><BR>
Internet mailing lists are an easy and efficient method of conducting group
discussion on any topic between individuals across the nation
or even the world. A mailing list is organized around a specific topic (such
as substance abuse), and interested readers subscribe via their own e-mail
address to monitor and contribute to the ongoing discussion. For this reason,
mailing lists are often called Discussion Groups. <BR>
<BR>
<B>How do they work?</B><BR>
Internet email lists are a sort of &quot;closed circuit&quot; communication
device between subscribers with a common interest. Using regular Internet
email, subscribers send messages to a special email address on a computer
maintained by the organization managing the list. This computer then automatically
re-sends each message to the email address of every subscriber on the mailing
list, usually within a matter of minutes. <BR>
<BR>
Subscribers follow and contribute to the ongoing discussion simply by reading
and sending their personal email. If a subscriber wishes to comment on a
post to the mailing list, he or she has the option of sending a response
for broadcast to the entire group, or just to the person originally posting
the message. <BR>
<BR>
<B>SUBSCRIBING</B><BR>
<BR>
<B>Restricted Subscription</B><BR>
Some mailing lists (such as <A HREF="subabuse.html">Subabuse</A>) screen potential subscribers. You'll need to send
email to the list adminstrator
asking to be placed on the mailing list. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Listservs: automated subscribing</B><BR>
Many mailing lists have an automated subscription program called Listserv
that has it's own email address on the computer managing the mailing list.
To subscribe to these lists, you need two things: 
<UL>
<LI>the listserv address; and 
<LI>the name of the mailing list. 
</UL>
Listserve addresses usually look something like &quot;listserv@statecollege.edu&quot;.
List names are usually concise, one-word titles that suggest the general
discussion topic (e.g., a substance abuse discussion list might be named
&quot;drug-talk&quot;.)<BR>
<BR>
To sign up for the list, just send a piece of email to the Listserv address
with one line in the body of the letter: 
<BLOCKQUOTE>subscribe <B>listname yourname </B>(e.g., "subscribe drug-talk
Kay Smith")<BR>
<BR>
<I>Caution:</I> be sure to send your subscription message to the Listserv
address, not the discussion list address, or everyone on the list will read
it!</BLOCKQUOTE>

Watch for an automated reply welcoming you to the list. It will include
instructions about how to post messages, and how to remove yourself from
the list. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Other automated list servers</B> <BR>
Other mailing list servers (such as Majordomo) may use slightly different
language for subscribing. Most majordomo-type servers want your email address
instead of your name in the subscribe message you send. In almost all cases,
if your subscription request doesn't work, you'll get an automated reply
with instructions about the proper syntax needed.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="subabuse.html">Subabuse<BR></B>
</A>The mailing list maintained by Join Together.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="otherlists.html">Other Mailing Lists </A><BR></B>
Substance abuse-related lists managed elsewhere, with links for easy sign-up. <BR></BLOCKQUOTE>


