<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>What Groups Can Do</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>What Local Groups Can Do</CENTER>
</H2>
There are many groups in your community that can help spread the word that
marijuana use is dangerous. Some organizations you might want to partner
with include businesses, youth groups, mall management, coaches and parent/
teacher associations, civic and professional groups, doctors offices, health
clinics, movie theaters, video stores and restaurants. Here are some things
these groups can do:
<UL>
<LI>Hold brown bag lunches for employees and volunteers to present the latest
statistics on marijuana problems, describe the Reality Check campaign, and
discuss what different groups can do to promote marijuana prevention among
youth in your community.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask businesses to co-sponsor the campaign by providing their logo or
slogan so you can add it to some of the materials included in this kit.
You or they can reproduce these pieces and distribute them to employees,
board members, and other businesses in the area to show their support for
this effort.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Ask companies to use their newsletter or other printed materials to
let employees and customers or members know about the risks of marijuana
and what parents can do.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Present marijuana prevention sessions at conferences, workshops and
trainings related to substance abuse, health and safety, parenting, education,
child development, law enforcement or any other related topic.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Insert copies of marijuana prevention materials in employee payroll
envelopes, membership mailings, invoices, bills, and statements to customers
or members.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Organize volunteers to distribute prevention materials at health fairs,
sporting events and rock concerts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Incorporate prevention tips, information and messages on the harmful
effects of marijuana in newsletters, bulletins and other mailings to members
and constituents<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Develop a speakers bureau on this issue, make local law enforcement,
advocacy, and other speakers available for community gatherings and meetings.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Provide talking points to religious and civic leaders to incorporate
into sermons and speeches.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Hold an anti-marijuana essay, poster, slogan, rap music or video contest
for area youth. Ask local companies to help you advertise and provide prizes.
</UL>
<B><A HREF="facts.html">Next</A></B> page<BR><BR>
<B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR>
