<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>PSA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>Public Service Announcements</CENTER>
</H2>
The following public service announcement scripts about the problem of marijuana
use among young people are targeted to parents and are specifically tailored
to be run in the summer when kids are out of school. Provide a few of these
to your local radio station during the summer months and ask the station
manager to air them. You can also insert some local facts.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Subject: MAKE THIS SUMMER SAFE: TALK TO YOUR KIDS ABOUT MARIJUANA<BR>
</B><BR>
1) Keep things sailing smoothly this summer. Talk with your kids about the
dangers of using marijuana. In just one year, the number of eighth graders
who use marijuana has doubled. Don't let your child be part of next year's
statistics. Call the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information
at 1-800-729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
2) It's summertime and the going is easy. But some kids are going for the
wrong thing. They are going for marijuana. Marijuana use is a growing problem
among young people. Set your kids straight. Talk to them about marijuana.
To find out more, call the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information
at 1-800-729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
3) Help your kids stay on the right side of the fence this summer. Sit down
and have a heart-to-heart talk with them about the dangers of using marijuana.
Kids are under a lot of pressure as they get older. Pressures to do well
in school, pressures from parents, pressures from kids who use drugs. It's
never too early to talk to your kids about the dangers of using marijuana
and other drugs. Call the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information
at 1-800-729-6686. Marijuana: It's a drug. Help your kids understand.<BR>
<BR>
4) Don't let your kids rock the boat this summer. Talk to them about the
dangers of using marijuana now, before it's too late. More and more 12 to
17 year olds are using marijuana these days. Don't let your kids become
part of the growing numbers. Need some tips on what to say? Call the National
Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information at 1-800-729-6686. Marijuana:
It's a drug. Help your kids understand.<BR>
<BR>
5) Don't let your kids' dreams go up in smoke this summer. In just one year,
the number of eighth graders who use marijuana has doubled. That's why you
should talk to your kids about the dangers of drug use now, before it's
too late. Need tips? Call the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug
Information at 1-800-729-6686. Marijuana: It's a drug. Help your kids understand.<BR>
<BR>
<B>GENERAL PUBLIC SERVICE ANNOUNCEMENTS</B><BR>
<BR>
These Public Service Announcements are more general and can be run on radio
stations that parents listen to at any time of the year.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Starting Point <BR>
</B>Where would you start if you wanted to undermine the future of a generation?
What would you do first to make sure that kids did poorly in school, made
careless and dangerous decisions about their friendships and school activities?
How would you begin disrupting their communities, destroying traditions,
and threatening the stability of homes and families? Reality check: marijuana
is a drug. Help our kids understand. Call 1-800-729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
<B>A Terrible Thought <BR>
</B>Wouldn't it be terrible if kids used something they thought was harmless
but really caused a lot of trouble. Suppose it made them not care, made
it harder to pay attention and learn, harder to remember things, and harder
to make friends and get along with others? What if they believed that everybody
was using it, even though most kids really weren't? Reality check: marijuana's
a drug -- help our kids understand. Call 1-800-729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Company They Keep</B> <BR>
Marijuana is more harmful than we think. But here's another reality check:
it also exposes our kids to a drug culture. It puts them in touch with people
using and pushing other drugs, and these people may be involved in dangerous
activities. Like early and unsafe sex. Carrying weapons and starting fights.
Drug abuse, trafficking and addiction. Give kids what they need to avoid
marijuana and you may prevent a whole lot more. To find out how, call 1-800-729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Cause &amp; Effect</B> <BR>
If you think there is no scientific evidence that the use of one drug necessarily
causes the use of any other drug, you need a reality check. Among adolescents
who use illicit drugs such as cocaine and heroin--almost every one of them
used marijuana first. So if we prevent use of marijuana we might also prevent
other illicit drug use. Makes you think, doesn't it? For more information,
call 1-800-729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Bluntly Speaking<BR>
</B> Let's be blunt about marijuana. Did you know, like many kids do, that
&quot;blunt&quot; is street slang for a hollowed-out cigar filled with marijuana?
Sometimes blunts contain marijuana mixed with cocaine, crack, PCP, methamphetamine,
even embalming fluid. How's that for a reality check? Learn how to have
a blunt talk with your kids about drugs. Call 1-800-729-6686 for a free
copy of &quot;Keeping Youth Drug Free.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
