<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Sample Op-Ed</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> 
<H2><CENTER>Sample Op-Ed</CENTER>
</H2>
<I>You can tailor the following Op-Ed with some examples and statistics
from your community and send this to your local newspaper.<BR>
<P><CENTER></I><B>Don't Let Our Kids' Dreams Go Up in Smoke</B></CENTER>
<P>In the 60's and 70's, `marijuana use was &quot;cool.&quot; In the 80's,
it was &quot;out.&quot; But now, suddenly, in the mid-90's, marijuana is
making a big comeback. And its popularity is growing.<BR>
	<BR>
Recent studies have alerted us to the disturbing fact that even elementary
school students are using marijuana. And usage rates among older students
-- ages 12 to 17 -- have almost doubled since the early 1990s. This could
be in part because of the new pop culture that glamorizes marijuana and
other drugs. Movies, television shows, music videos, song lyrics and clothing
insignia carry pro-marijuana messages.<BR>
	<BR>
Complicating this problem is the fact that the parents of many of these
kids who use marijuana today may have tried the drug themselves in the past
and are reluctant to talk to their children about this controversial subject.
<BR>
	<BR>
As a result, we have a generation of young people who think marijuana is
&quot;no big deal.&quot; But the truth is, a number of harms can result
from its use. For instance, it impairs young people's judgment, which can
lead to unprotected sex, pregnancy and sexually-transmitted diseases, including
HIV/AIDS. <BR>
	<BR>
It also contributes to accidents, violence and car crashes. The 1995 Drug
Abuse Warning Network report released last November shows that medical emergency
room episodes related to marijuana have increased 155 percent since 1990
-- from 15,700 to 40,100. <BR>
<BR>
Use of this drug also negatively affects kids' concentration and schoolwork.
And using, buying or selling can result in a school suspension or expulsion
and a police record.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, some current forms of marijuana are &quot;spiked&quot; with
other illicit drugs like cocaine, crack cocaine, PCP and even embalming
fluid, making an already dangerous drug even more dangerous.<BR>
	<BR>
This is why now, more than ever, it is crucial for parents to know the facts,
and to feel comfortable sharing these facts with their children.<BR>
	<BR>
Some things parents can do include the following: be a good role model;
make sure your children feel safe sharing their fears and thoughts about
alcohol and drugs with you; use the media's portrayal of alcohol and marijuana
to start a dialogue with your kids about these substances; and help your
kids resist peer pressure by listening to their concerns and validating
them.<BR>
	<BR>
For more information about marijuana, contact the National Clearinghouse
for Alcohol and Drug Information at (800) 729-6686 (TDD 1-800-487-4889)
or visit their site on the World Wide Web at http://www.health.org. They
can provide free materials that can help adults and youth understand the
impact of marijuana and other drug use. Or call (YOUR ORGANIZATION at (PHONE
NUMBER).<BR>
<BR>
Sincerely,<BR>
YOUR NAME<BR>
TITLE<BR>
ORGANIZATION<BR>
<BR>
(You may want to add one sentence here explaining your organization's substance
abuse prevention activities.)<BR>
<BR>
