<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>What You Can Do</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>WHAT <B><FONT SIZE="5">YOU</FONT></B><B> CAN DO<BR>
</B></FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
You may wonder how <I>you</I> can make the case in your community
that providing treatment for nonviolent criminals with addictions
is essential to community safety<I>.<BR>
</I>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Here are some things you can do:<BR>
</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI>Get local crime statistics from your police department. Ask
your police chief what role alcohol and drugs played in these
crimes.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Find out what treatment options exist in your area. Talk to
local treatment providers and find out how many clients were incarcerated
before getting help. Ask providers about the nature of the violent
crimes clients committed. If most of the crimes were minor, this
will help make your case for providing treatment alternatives
to jail.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Read the police blotter in your community newspaper and see
if alcohol and/or drugs are mentioned in relationship to many
of the incidents. If not, talk to the editor and suggest that
the newspaper start including this information where it is pertinent.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Monitor the front page of the community newspaper to see for
yourself how many crimes are related in some way to substance
abuse.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Find out how much it costs per year to incarcerate a prisoner
in your community, county or state. Compare this figure to the
price of an average stay in a local treatment facility and see
what the savings are.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Are there drug courts or diversionary treatment programs in
your community? If so, find out how successful they have been.
Does the capacity meet the need in your community? If not, make
the case for expanding treatment options. If no such programs
exist locally, talk to other communities in your state who have
successfully implemented such options and learn how they started.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Talk to local judges, prison officials, prosecutors, probation
supervisors and treatment providers about your findings. Brainstorm
ways you can work more closely with them to provide substance
abuse treatment for criminals. 
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Remember that many residents care about safety and cost. Therefore,
keep these key issues in mind when you make your case for providing
such treatment options.  
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Look at what options exist for juvenile offenders with substance
abuse problems in your community. Suggest alternatives that could
prevent kids from being incarcerated and at the same time, treat
their substance abuse problems and teach them new skills.<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Convene a policy panel to examine local problems and make
recommendations on how your community can benefit by providing
treatment for criminals with addictions. (See &quot;How to Convene
a Local Policy Panel&quot; included in this Kit.)
</UL>


<BR> <BR> <B><A HREF="pitch.html">Next</A></B> page<BR><BR> <B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR> <BR> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></CENTER> </BODY> </HTML>
