<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>Resources</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<P> <CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>RESOURCES<BR> </FONT></B></CENTER> <P> <B>For more information about the link between crime and substance abuse, and how you can work with criminal justice agencies in your community to provide treatment for addicted offenders, you may want to contact the following organizations:<BR> </B> <P> <B>Federal Drugs, Alcohol and Crime Clearinghouse Network (800) 788-2800</B> <BR> The Federal Drugs, Alcohol and Crime Clearinghouse Network serves as a single point of entry for all federal alcohol and drug clearinghouses. The Network provides a wide array of information, resource material and other services related to substance abuse prevention and treatment. <BR>

<P> <B>The Sentencing Project      (202) 628-0871</B> <BR> The Sentencing Project has provided technical assistance and helped to establish alternative sentencing programs in more than 20 states. It offers training for court officials, and help in analyzing and assessing court and corrections needs for offenders.<BR>

<P> <B>Center for Substance Abuse Treatment (CSAT)    (302) 443-6533</B> <BR> CSAT collaborates with private and public treatment providers to develop and support policies, approaches and programs for people with alcohol and drug addictions. CSAT also funds a range of projects for juvenile and adult offenders with substance abuse problems. (To view CSAT's homepage on the world wide web, go to: http://www.samhsa.gov/CSAT.HTM) <BR>

<P> <B>Minnesota Citizens Council on Crime and Justice</B>  <B>(612) 340-5432</B> <BR> The Citizens Council, which is a national model in the field of criminal justice, is a research, advocacy and public education organization. It also provides direct services that assist over 15,000 people annually, including those affected by a broad range of crimes and those who are offenders or the families of inmates. <BR>

<P> <U><B>WORLD WIDE WEB RESOURCES:</B></U> <P> <B>Join Together Online             </B> <B><A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org/">http://www.jointogether.org/</A></B> <BR>Join Together Onlines is an electronic resource center that provides latest information in the substance abuse field, daily summaries of major news stories, policy information and funding news. <BR>

<P> <B>Cecil Greeks Criminal Justice Page</B>     <B> <A HREF="http://www.stpt.usf.edu/%7Egreek/cj.html">http://www.stpt.usf.edu/~greek/cj.html</A></B> <BR>Provides comprehensive listing and access to criminal justice resources on the Web.<BR>

<P> <B>Vera Institute of Justice</B>                <B><A HREF="http://broadway.vera.org">http://broadway.vera.org</A></B><BR>Vera works with government and local communities to design and implement programs that expand fairness and justice in public services and government policies. In addition, it also works to improve the quality of urban life.<BR>



