<TITLE>SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>

<H3>HIV-Infection and Substance Abuse</H3>

<H2>SAMPLE PRESS RELEASE</H2></center>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.
<hr>

<P>RELEASE DATE: 02/09/1997<br>


<FORM ACTION="HIV_PressOutput.nclk" METHOD=POST>
CONTACT: <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Contact" VALUE="Your Name" SIZE=35><br>
PHONE:  <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #">


<HR>


<P><B>PROVIDING ALCOHOL AND DRUG TREATMENT HELPS REDUCE THE RISK OF HIV-INFECTION</B>


<P>MILWAUKEE--&quot;I never thought it could happen to me,&quot; says 33-year- old Betty Johnson, an artist who found out last year that she is HIV-positive. (REPLACE WITH LOCAL EXAMPLE.)


<P>Until then, Johnson used to shoot up heroin with her friends, passing around a hypodermic needle that ultimately infected her with tainted blood.


<P>&quot;In those days, I never worried about AIDS. I was only thinking of my next high,&quot; Johnson admits.


<P>But today she is forced to worry about AIDS all the time.


<P>Like Johnson, about one million people in the United States are infected with the HIV virus, according to recent estimates by the Centers for Disease Control. This means that one person out of every 250 tests positive for the HIV antibodies that develop into six months after infection.


<P>And like Johnson, close to 35 percent of these men and women who are HIV-positive contracted the virus through intravenous drug use.


<P>&quot;I see cases like Johnson's all the time,&quot; says Dr. Paul Rubin, an infectious disease specialist at Milwaukee Hospital.  &quot;There are many people out there who injected drugs or got drunk and had unprotected sex and now they are paying for it dearly -- with their lives,&quot; he says.


<P>&quot;It is crucial that we stop this tragic disease in its tracks,&quot; stresses Rubin. &quot;While we don't have a cure yet for people who have the virus, we can work to prevent others from catching it,&quot; he says.


<P>Rubin points that one way to do this is to provide substance abuse treatment for all who need it.


<P>&quot;If we can educate people about how to have protected sex and help those with alcohol and drug problems to overcome their addictions, they would not put themselves at such high risk for HIV,&quot; he says, adding, &quot;That's why we must make sure that an adequate substance abuse benefit is included in any new health plan that is passed.&quot;
<p>
<hr>
<center><INPUT TYPE="submit" VALUE="Generate a letter">
<INPUT TYPE="reset" VALUE="Clear the letter">
</center>
</FORM>
<p>
