<HTML> <HEAD> <TITLE>What Others Have Done</TITLE> </HEAD> <BODY> 	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<P> <CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>WHAT OTHERS HAVE DONE<BR> </FONT></B></CENTER> <P> There are a number of ways communities -- and states -- across the nation are tackling crime and substance abuse. Things like implementing fair sentencing guidelines, providing drug courts that divert offenders to treatment, and creating community partnerships are proving successful. These approaches save taxpayers money and make our neighborhoods safer while giving offenders with addictions the help they need. <P> Here are a few examples of what works:<BR>

<P> <U><B>Drug Courts</B></U> <P> <B>Rochester:</B> A drug court steers non-violent offenders into treatment in Rochester, NY. This drug court employs treatment providers and case managers to link program participants with community services. In less than a year, this program has proved effective -- of 172 participants, only 12 have been rearrested. Funds for the program come from local foundations and the Monroe County Bar Association. For more information, contact: Nadine Spinell at (716) 428-2736.<BR>

<P> <B>Little Rock: </B>Treatment is far less expensive than jail in Little Rock, Arkansas. The Substance Abuse Treatment Education Program, known as STEP, allows offenders to opt for a suspended sentence and referral to social services and treatment -- which costs $3,000 a person -- instead of a stay in jail, which averages $30,000 a year.  To qualify, offenders must commit to completing the whole program. Upon graduating, their criminal record is erased. Those who fail to complete the program are sent back to court to be sentenced for their crimes. So far 40 clients have successfully graduated from STEP in 15 months and there has been no recidivism. For more information, contact: Terrel Rose, STEP project director, at (501) 374-7837. <BR>

<P> <U><B>Sentencing Guidelines<BR> </B></U> <P> Fair sentencing guidelines have helped Delaware keep the prison population in check. These guidelines establish five levels of accountability for people who have committed crimes -- ranging from unsupervised probation to prison. Since the guidelines were adopted in 1987, the number of people sent to jail for nonviolent offenses has dropped by 50 percent. In addition, in 1986 the prison population was growing at a rate of 11 percent, yet in 1990 it dropped to a 2.3 percent decline.  For more information, contact: Judge Myron Steele at the Court of Chancery at (302) 739-4397. <BR>

<P> <U><B>Community Partnerships</B></U> <P> Community partnerships are the weapon to fighting crime in Brooklyn, New York, and Portland, Oregon. In Brooklyn, the Kings County District Attorney divides the 23 police precincts into five zones. Prosecutors in each zone work closely with police officers and community organizations to improve law enforcement and prosecution. For more information, call the Brooklyn D.A.'s office at (718) 802-2000. In Portland, the Multnomah County District Attorney's office brings together local prosecutors and neighborhood safety committees to keep the community safe with activities like drug-free school and housing zones and a program that requires nonviolent criminals to serve their probation by performing community service. For more information, call the Multnomah County D.A.'s office at (503) 248-3162.<BR>


