<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Others</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>What Others Have Done</CENTER>
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Many innocent-looking substances stored in household cabinets, closets
and garages may actually be fatal. That's because young people abuse these
products to get high. That's the message from the National Inhalant Prevention
Coalition/Texas Prevention Partnership. They sponsor a week-long annual
campaign called, <I>&quot;National Inhalants &amp; Poisons Awareness Week:
They're Right Under Your Nose.&quot;</I> The goal of the campaign is to
alert communities to the danger of everyday products being inhaled or misused.
The campaign began in response to a 1992 Texas school survey that showed
one in four students have tried inhalants by the time they reach the seventh
grade. This national campaign relies on local groups to get the message
out in their communities. To do so, artwork, news releases and advertisements
are provided and can be tailored for individual schools, prevention coalitions,
cities and towns. In addition, videos and posters are available for a small
fee. In 1995, over 1,000 partners from almost every state joined the campaign.<B>
For more information, contact Harvey Weiss at (800) 269-4237.</B><BR>
<BR>
<LI>Illinois residents are getting a crash course in the dangers of inhalant
abuse, thanks to a statewide educational campaign there launched by the
lieutenant governor's office. The ongoing campaign, which began in 1994
and follows Texas' example, was sparked in response to survey findings that
inhalants are the fastest growing category of drug use in that state. In
fact, one in 10 Illinois teenagers abuses household projects to get high.
The statewide campaign, called &quot;Danger: Right Under Your Nose,&quot;
provides materials, tools and suggestions that communities can use to localize
the message. There is also an 800 number people can call for more information
about inhalants. The campaign has been very successful to date, raising
awareness about the problem and risks of inhalant abuse throughout the state.
<B>For more information about the campaign, call Debra Palandech at (312)
814-5220.<BR>
</B>
</UL>
OTHER RESOURCES ON INHALANT ABUSE: 
<UL>
<LI>The latest issue of The Prevention Forum, a newsletter put out by the
Prevention Network in Illinois, focuses on inhalant abuse. To obtain a copy,
contact Russell Stare at (217) 793-7353. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>The February issue of YM Magazine (Young and Modern) has a cover article
on inhalant abuse. This issue should be available at local bookstores and
magazine stands around the country. 
</UL>
<BR>
[<A HREF="../Inhalants/Inhalant_Index.html">Back</A> to Inhalants] <BR>
