<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Letter</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>Letter to the Editor</CENTER>
</H2>
<I>You can tailor the following letter--or use it as is--and send it to
the editor of your local newspaper</I>.<BR>
<HR>Dear Editor:<BR>
<BR>
White out. Glue. Nail polish remover. Lighter fluid. Paint. What do these
various household products all have in common? They all tragically kill
kids.<BR>
<BR>
Today, many young people in our community abuse such products that are readily
available in our medicine chests and on the shelves in our stores. They
inhale these and a host of other substances through the nose and/or mouth
to get a quick high.<BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, these kids are not aware of the high risks that come along
with this behavior. The fact is that each year hundreds of children die
from inhalant use--sometimes on their first try--yet many parents and educators
remain ignorant of this &quot;silent epidemic.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Inhalants are the third most abused substances among 12 to 14-year-olds
in the United States, coming in right behind alcohol and tobacco. And as
many as one in five students in the United States has sniffed or &quot;huffed&quot;
(inhaled through the mouth) such products as magic markers, gasoline and
air fresheners by the time they reach the seventh grade.<BR>
<BR>
Yet while many kids admit to sniffing toxic items, they do not consider
this to be &quot;inhalant abuse.&quot; These products are easily available,
free or inexpensive, legal and may give a pleasurable affect by depressing
the central nervous system.<BR>
<BR>
And those kids who do not die from inhalants still put themselves at a risk
for a number of other serious side affects, including permanent and severe
brain damage. Chronic inhalant abusers may permanently lose the ability
to perform everyday tasks like walking, talking and thinking.<BR>
<BR>
Please help to get the message out to parents and to kids that inhalants
are dangerous. If you suspect someone you know may be using inhalants, consult
a school counselor or a drug counseling center for help.<BR>
<BR>
Sincerely,<BR>
<BR>
YOUR NAME<BR>
TITLE<BR>
ORGANIZATION<BR>
PHONE NUMBER<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
[<A HREF="../Inhalants/Inhalant_Index.html">Back</A> to Inhalants] <BR>
<BR>
