<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Message</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> <CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER> <BR>
<H2><CENTER>How to Get the Message Out Locally</CENTER>
</H2>
The Reality Check campaign can serve as a valuable resource to you and to
your community. The campaign theme is:  <BR>
<H4><CENTER>Marijuana Is a Drug. Help Our Kids Understand. </CENTER>
</H4>
<BR>
You can take this message and localize it with your community name and/or
other specifics. (For instance, Help Milwuakee's Kids Understand.) You can
also tailor the message and scope of your campaign in other ways, depending
on the specific resources -- and needs -- of your particular region. For
instance, if marijuana is at the root of a problem of kids skipping school
and vandalizing public property, you may want to work closely with school
personnel and law enforcement in your city or town. Or there may a lack
of drug education on the local level. Then you could consider working with
the PTA (which is already a partner in this campaign) and school personnel
in your area to get materials and messages out to local youth. If there
are stores in your area that sell pro-marijuana paraphernalia and promote
pro-use messages to youth, you might approach some of the merchants and
provide them with new pro-health slogans and novelty items such as T-shirts
and key chains to help change community norms.  And working with the media
is vital, whatever your community issues and concerns.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Some things to remember:<BR>
</B>
<UL>
<LI>Involve students in your planning. They can be a good audience to test
your messages on and to advise you on what will have the most impact locally,
as well as how best to reach both kids at risk for marijuana use and their
parents.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Be sensitive to cultural issues and economic differences that exist
in your community.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Partner with other organizations to extend the reach of your campaign.
You can volunteer your time, skills and materials to other groups and ask
them to share their resources with you.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Get your message out in a number of ways. Target traditional media outlets
(your daily and weekly newspapers and television stations), as well as more
alternative places (church bulletins and newspapers, talk radio stations,
cable and specialty publications).<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Be sure to include a broad range of groups in your efforts. Invite participation
from schools, parents, volunteer groups, the faith community, health care
providers, law enforcement, prevention and treatment organizations, maternal
and child health services, legal and social services, organizations serving
low-income families, labor unions, neighborhood-based social clubs, and
American Legion Posts and/or other veteran organizations.
</UL>
Joining together with other groups is now easier than ever. CSAP has established
the National Coalition to Prevent Marijuana Use. For more information, contact
the National Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information at (800) 729-6686.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="do.html">Next</A></B> page<BR><BR>
<B><A HREF="intro.html">Back</A></B> to Introduction<BR>
