<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2></H2>
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | Letter | <A HREF="Summary.html">Summary</A> | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
| <A HREF="one.html">One</A> | <A HREF="two.html">Two</A> | <A HREF="three.html">Three</A>
| <A HREF="four.html">Four</A> | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| <A HREF="appendix.html">Appendix</A><HR></CENTER>
<H3>
<br><br><CENTER>Introduction </CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER>Calvin Hill, Chairman<BR>
Join Together National Advisory Committee</CENTER>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/Calvin.gif" WIDTH="138" HEIGHT="201" ALIGN=right
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
</H3>
You and your colleagues knew that tobacco, drug and alcohol use were on
the rise among youth well before the recent national reports alerted the
American public. And you also know that the only real way to reduce substance
abuse is from the ground up - through the community action and collaboration
that result when communities join together.<BR>
<BR>
President Clinton knows this, too. In an address before 800 community anti-drug
coalition leaders on November 2, 1995, the President urged every community
in America to have a coalition to reduce substance abuse &quot;because we
know that we can make a difference.&quot; He told these anti-drug groups
that &quot;it is simply not true that you cannot whip this problem. You
are living evidence of that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Join Together's Third National Survey of Communities Fighting Substance
Abuse demonstrates that the President's faith in coalitions is well placed.
You are driving up citizen participation, encouraging other groups in your
community to work together and changing public policies that are making
a difference.<BR>
<BR>
However, despite these solid gains in the coalition movement - from the
ground up - this survey carries a stern warning. Coalition leaders told
us that many of the institutions that have been traditional pillars of community
efforts - particularly elected officials such as governors, state legislators
and Congress - are now walking away from these problems at the very time
when their leadership is needed most.<BR>
<BR>
You also told us that you need more active partnerships from your local
businesses, clergy, parents and the media to prevent the next generation
from falling victim to drugs.<BR>
<BR>
We all need to challenge our leaders to view their prevention role in the
same way that businesses sell their products. Toy manufacturers know that
they have a new market for their products every several years. Drug pushers
and alcohol and tobacco advertisers also know they have a new market for
their products with each new generation of teens. This means that everyone
involved in the battle against substance abuse - from Congress right on
down to our local business leaders - must renew the commitment to combat
this terrible problem that exists in our own backyard.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="../../../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="../../../../../MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP
ISMAP><BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="../../../../../default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="../../../../jto/index.html">Index</A>
| <A HREF="../../../../jto/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="../../../../jto/comments.html">Comments</A>
| <A HREF="../../../../jto/help.html">Help</A><BR>
<BR>
<HR>Distributed by Join Together<BR>
<A HREF="www.jointogether.org/default.html">http://www.jointogether.org</A></CENTER>
