<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Section one: Coalitions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | <A HREF="hillLetter.html">Letter</A> | <A HREF="Summary.html">Summary</A> | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
| One | <A HREF="two.html">Two</A> | <A HREF="three.html">Three</A>
| <A HREF="four.html">Four</A> | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| <A HREF="appendix.html">Appendix</A><HR></CENTER>
<H3>
<br><br><CENTER>Section One: Coalitions - a growing and <BR>
important force in communities</CENTER>
</H3>
Join Together has purposely avoided assigning a single, rigid definition
of the term coalition to reflect the reality that various organizational
structures work effectively to reduce substance abuse in different communities.
In our surveys we have let communities determine whether or not they were
working in a coalition by asking: &quot;Does your organization lead, sponsor
or participate in a task force, consortium or coalition that plans and/or
directs alcohol or other drug-related programs, activities, policies and/or
resource allocation?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
We heard from 4177 organizations as of October 31, 1995 that either participate
in or lead community coalitions. Of these, 1910 respondents identified themselves
as leading or sponsoring community coalitions against substance abuse. This
report is based on the responses of these lead coalitions.<BR>
<BR>
Through our surveys and experience working with these groups across the
country, we are constantly struck by the rich diversity of the community
coalitions that have sprung up across America in recent years. In the Austin
district of Chicago, a community coalition has formed as an offshoot of
the police district there. In San Diego, a veterinarian took the lead in
forming a coalition whose purpose is to fight drugs and also educate and
support local parents. In Oswego, N.Y., a traffic crash that took the life
of a popular high school student was the catalyst to bring parents, teachers,
businesses, the media and youth together to build a safe and drug-free community.
And in Miami, a group of business people were convinced by their spouses
that they had a responsibility to help solve the drug problem. Their effort
became the Miami Coalition for a Drug-Free Community. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Types of Coalitions</B><BR>
<BR>
Coalitions participating in the third survey self-selected into different
types according to the way they described their sponsorship and membership.
Some are community action-based; others are located within government agencies;
and another major subset is found within health or social service settings.
In addition, there are coalitions organized around law enforcement agencies
that were not separately identified as a single type. <A HREF="gifs/table1.gif">Table
1</A> displays the relative distribution of the eight different types of
coalitions that participated in this survey. The box on page 10 provides
examples of each type. These differences are significant indicators of their
focus, their activities and their sources of funds.<BR>
<BR>
<B>What Do Coalitions Do?</B><BR>
<BR>
Coalitions bring different segments of a community together to solve social
problems. They connect individuals and groups with current information,
including success stories from other communities. As a result, issues can
be more effectively addressed than through single agencies working alone.
Coalitions focus on community environments, whereas many organizations that
participate in coalitions focus their energy on providing services to individuals.
Coalitions focus on systemwide change, whereas their members address specific
elements, such as treatment, shelter or youth employment.<BR>
<BR>
In each of our surveys, we have asked community coalitions to describe their
activities. We also asked them to describe the extent of their involvement
in these activities. The responses of coalitions in the third survey are
summarized in <A HREF="gifs/table2.gif">Table 2</A>. <BR>
<BR>
Coalitions are still much more extensively involved in prevention, public
awareness and systemwide planning than in other activities such as treatment/aftercare,
public policy or public safety. They remain about equally concerned about
alcohol and illicit drug use. Since 1993, there has been an increase in
the percentage of coalitions that are extensively involved in tobacco issues,
from 26% to 36%.<BR>
<BR>
To get a better idea of how coalitions have evolved and to learn the direction
their future programs might take, we asked the respondents to tell us how
their involvement in each of these activities had changed in the past two
years. We were curious to know whether it had increased, decreased or stayed
the same. The answers are also displayed in <A HREF="gifs/table2.gif">Table
2</A>.<BR>
<BR>
Coalitions are expanding their involvement in a broad range of substance
abuse activities without abandoning their core commitment to prevention,
planning and public awareness. For example, 42% of the coalitions increased
their efforts in prevention, whereas only 5% report a decrease in this area.
At the same time, 25% report increased involvement in treatment/aftercare,
and 35% said they had increased their activities in alcohol and drug-related
crime issues.<BR>
<BR>
Only 23% of the coalitions report extensive involvement in public policy
matters. However, 36% report that they have become more involved in public
policy in the past two years. We believe coalitions will become even more
involved in public policy issues in the future because that may be the most
effective way to alter the community environments that affect substance
abuse.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, <A HREF="gifs/table3.gif">Table 3</A> shows that there is a
relationship between what coalitions do and whether they think the substance
abuse situation is getting better or worse. For example, groups who report
the situation improving are more likely to be guided by a written plan,
report better citizen mobilization, more volunteers and an increase in substance
abuse treatment, police enforcement and prevention than those groups that
say the situation is getting worse.<BR>
The Special Case of CSAP-Sponsored Coalitions<BR>
<BR>
The Center for Substance Abuse Prevention has played a major role in fostering
the development of community coalitions. Between 1990 and 1995, the agency
invested more than $500 million in developing community-based partnerships.
Five-year grants were made to more than 250 locally based groups to develop
and implement prevention partnerships and strategies. Additional grants
were made to groups that focus on teen pregnancy or high-risk youths, and
for communicating with special populations. Two hundred and ten (210) organizations
in the third Join Together survey identified themselves as CSAP-sponsored
groups. Thus, we can report how this important set of coalitions compares
to the rest of the movement.<BR>
<BR>
The survey found that community coalitions sponsored by CSAP differ in significant
ways from other coalition types: 
<UL>
<LI>CSAP partnerships are more likely to be found in communities of all
sizes than are other types of coalitions. 
<LI>Membership in CSAP partnerships is more likely to have grown in the
past two years than is true for other groups (68% vs. 53%). 
<LI>CSAP partnerships have significantly more volunteers than do other groups.
Fifty-eight percent (58%) have more than 50 volunteers, whereas only 24%
of other lead coalitions report that many volunteers. 
<LI>CSAP partnerships spend twice the amount of money working with other
service agencies than do other community substance abuse groups. Sixty-five
percent (65%) of CSAP coalitions report influencing interorganizational
collaboration versus 47% of other lead coalitions. 
<LI>CSAP partnerships are younger than other groups leading community substance
abuse efforts. 
<LI>Almost half of all CSAP partnerships (46%) are extensively involved
in systemwide planning of substance abuse programs, compared to 40% of other
coalitions. 
<LI>CSAP partnerships are more likely to have a written strategy for their
work than are other groups (76% vs. 70%). 
</UL>
<BR>
The items included in <A HREF="gifs/table4.gif">Table 4</A> suggest two
distinct patterns of coalition activity. The CSAP groups and government
executive coalitions focus on changing community environments and policies,
whereas the government health and not-for-profit led coalitions focus more
on improving services within the existing policy framework.<BR>
<BR>
Although CSAP partnerships are extensively involved in public policy change
at about the same level as other groups leading community efforts (23%),
CSAP coalitions are more likely to have increased their involvement in this
area in the past two years than are other groups (51% vs. 36%). <BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalition Funding</B> <BR>
<BR>
Some coalitions have had enormous budget growth, whereas others have lost
core funding, from CSAP or another agency, that has not been replaced. On
average, coalition budgets have not grown since 1993. (See <A HREF="gifs/table5.gif">Table
5</A>.)<BR>
<BR>
The message on funding that comes through clearly from the third survey
is that the coalitions are being asked to accept enormous burdens with small
resource bases. Thirty-five percent (35%) spend less than $50,000 per year;
another 28% spend between $50,001 and $250,000; 15% spend between $250,001
and $500,000; and only 22% spend more than $500,000, and most of these are
government agency coalitions.<BR>
<BR>
Most coalitions are public-private partnerships, but they rely heavily on
government funding. In fact, 79% of them receive at least some funding from
a federal, state or local government agency. (See <A HREF="gifs/table6.gif">Table
6</A> for a description of where the different types of coalitions get their
money.) The federal government's role has been particularly important as
a catalyst for new coalitions. Forty-three percent (43%) of coalitions receive
money from the federal government. The coalitions receiving federal support
are younger and involve more volunteers than those that are more dependent
on state governments or other sources.<BR>
<BR>
This is a disturbing fact when considering that federal funding for substance
abuse prevention has been decreasing. <A HREF="gifs/table7.gif">Table 7</A>,
reprinted with permission of Drug Abuse Update, shows that as annual federal
drug prevention funds have decreased, the use of drugs, alcohol and tobacco
by youth has increased.<BR>
<BR>
State governments are the second most important source of funds. Twenty-four
percent (24%) of coalitions receive support from their state government.
Some of this funding comes through grants and contracts for services to
agencies for prevention and treatment, and some of it is in the form of
payments for treatment services provided to individuals with Medicaid coverage.<BR>
<BR>
Local governments are still not a major source of funding for coalitions.
However, they are playing a major role in some coalitions. Twelve percent
(12%) get some money from local government. <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="gifs/table8.gif">Table 8</A> shows that a majority of coalitions
(69%) now receive funds from multiple sources. This is particularly true
for coalitions that provide personal treatment services. <BR>
<BR>
Diversified funding is a major element in long-term survival and stability
for coalitions. The third survey results show that coalitions with more
than one source of funds have taken on a broader array of issues than those
with a single funding source. For instance, coalitions with multiple sources
of funds are more likely to participate in other coalitions within their
communities and are more likely to address treatment and aftercare, early
identification and HIV/AIDS.<BR>
<BR>
Coalitions are finding many creative and unusual sources of additional funding.
Join Together Online offers a Funding News Forum for communities to share
ideas about tapping new funding sources. Here is one example from the <A HREF="/jto/funding/funding.html">Funding
News Forum</A>: 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><CENTER>Gas Bills Add Up to Big Money in Mobile, Ala.</CENTER>
<P>Fighting drugs in Mobile, Ala., is as easy for residents as paying their
gas bill. That's because the Drug Education Council there asks all 85,000
Mobile Gas Company customers in the area to donate money to them by simply
checking off a box on their monthly gas bills. Businesses are asked to donate
$10 a month and residents $2. These small amounts add up quickly for the
Council; it collects about $45,000 a year, about one-third of its annual
budget. Because this campaign has been such a success, the Council is now
looking to start a similar one with the Mobile Area Water Authority. <BR>
For more information, contact Virginia Guy at (334) 433-5456.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B>Membership and Governance Differences Among Coalitions</B><BR>
<BR>
The persistent differences in activity and funding for the various types
of coalitions caused us to closely examine variation in the membership and
governance of coalitions. <A HREF="gifs/table9.gif">Table 9</A> illustrates
that a majority of all coalitions report that their membership includes
equal representation of lay people and professionals. However, there is
significant variation in membership composition and governance, depending
on the type of coalition. For example, CSAP, community action and non-profit
coalitions are more likely to be governed by an equal representation of
professional and lay members than the other types of coalitions.<BR>
<BR>
A full two-thirds (66%) of CSAP coalitions have equal representation of
citizens and professionals. In contrast, only 41% of government health agency
sponsored coalitions have this type of balanced representation. <BR>
<BR>
These differences matter because coalitions with equal representation are
more likely to have written strategic plans, focus on community change,
report increasing citizen participation in their work, and report a direct
impact on reducing illicit drugs and excessive alcohol use than are coalitions
led mostly by professionals and government officials. <A HREF="gifs/table10.gif">Table
10 </A>displays these key differences.<BR>
<BR>
<B>What Will Happen If Federal Funding Is Cut Significantly?</B><BR>
<BR>
As this survey was being completed, federal budget bills in both the House
and the Senate reduced support for drug and alcohol programs by between
72% in the House bill and 35% in the Senate bill. Newspaper reports, such
as in the Wall Street Journal (August 14, 1995), said these actions were
influenced by beer industry lobbyists who oppose the work of CSAP.<BR>
<BR>
In a survey in February 1995, Join Together asked community coalition leaders
what they thought would happen in their community if federal funds for crime
and drug prevention are substantially reduced. More than 90% of the 1,250
coalition leaders who participated in that survey predicted that drug- and
alcohol-related crime in their communities would increase if funds were
cut.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalitions of Government Officials</B> <BR>
<BR>
One hundred and six coalitions of various types report that they are composed
mostly of government officials. There is substantial evidence throughout
the survey that these coalitions have a different perspective on their communities
than other coalitions, and that they may work in greater isolation than
their counterparts. For example, they consistently give government agencies,
especially the courts, higher performance ratings than do other coalitions.<BR>
<BR>
We are particularly struck by the finding that government-led coalitions
are less likely to have written strategic plans than are partnership-type
coalitions. Most government agencies are bound by annual appropriation cycles
and existing legislative mandates. Broad strategic planning is beyond the
scope of many specialized public agencies, even when they are working in
coalitions with other agencies. We believe this finding strengthens the
argument that communities should have public-private strategic partnerships.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Multiple Coalitions in Communities</B><BR>
<BR>
It is unrealistic to assume that there will be only one overriding coalition
in each community. Multiple overlapping coalitions are likely to be the
most common pattern, even in relatively small towns. More than one group
identified itself as a coalition against substance abuse in a majority of
communities of all sizes in the third national survey. In fact, 86% of all
coalitions in the survey report that they participate in other community
coalitions. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Multiple Coalitions Are Found in Some Communities</B><BR>
<BR>
In communities where there are several community coalitions working on substance
abuse, these groups often have different memberships and purposes. For example,
in Dothan, Ala., a city of 55,000 people, two groups identified themselves
as lead coalitions in the third survey. One was a school-based coalition
and the other was a community-based group working out of the Boys' Club.
In Brooklyn, N.Y., we heard from eight lead coalitions. Most of them cover
a specific neighborhood, but others are school, religious or health-based
coalitions that operate throughout the community. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalitions Have Become a More Common Way to Address Social Issues</B><BR>
<BR>
We have always believed that communities that had successfully fought substance
abuse through the efforts of a coalition would also form additional coalitions
to address other important issues. We asked survey participants if they
knew about the emergence of any new coalitions in their communities to address
substance abuse, tobacco use, violence or HIV/AIDS. The response was overwhelming.
(See <A HREF="gifs/table11.gif">Table 11</A>.) During the past two years,
new community coalitions to address major social problems have been established
in every state in the nation.
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="../../../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="../../../../../MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP
