<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Section Three: Community Report Card</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | <A HREF="hillLetter.html">Letter</A> | <A HREF="Summary.html">Summary</A> | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
 <A HREF="one.html">One</A> | <A HREF="two.html">Two</A> | Three
| <A HREF="four.html">Four</A> | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| <A HREF="appendix.html">Appendix</A><HR></CENTER>
<H3>
<br><br><CENTER>Section Three: Community Report Card - <BR>
how coalitions rate the performance of <BR>
major community institutions</CENTER>
</H3>
Although citizens have become more involved and easier to mobilize against
substance abuse in the past two years, the federal and state governments
and local school systems receive significantly lower performance ratings
from the 1910 lead coalitions in our survey. The scores for all other institutions
remain unchanged from their ratings in earlier surveys. The national picture,
however, masks considerable change within specific communities. <BR>
<BR>
All community institutions must be involved if permanent progress against
substance abuse is to occur. Therefore, we have asked community coalition
leaders, in each of our surveys, to assess the current efforts of major
institutions in addressing substance abuse in their communities. Respondents
could give a grade of poor, fair, good or excellent. Table 18 summarizes
the key responses. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Elected Officials Can Make a Difference</B><BR>
<BR>
Elected officials are reported to have increased their attention to substance
abuse issues in those communities where the situation is reported to be
getting better. Conversely, elected officials are more likely to have decreased
their attention in communities where the situation is reported as getting
worse. <BR>
<BR>
Local law enforcement and schools continue to get the highest marks in the
survey, despite the decline in the positive ratings for the schools. The
results suggest that community leaders give their local schools credit for
remaining involved in substance abuse but are critical because substance
use among teens is increasing in most communities. It is also true that
most school systems have had less money to spend on drug and alcohol prevention
in the past two years. Community leaders see and report the deterioration
in the number of programs. <BR>
<BR>
Business, labor, religious, civic and fraternal organizations get the same
poor ratings they received in our past surveys. Fewer than 6% of community
coalition leaders believe these groups are doing an excellent job in their
towns, whereas up to 43% give these groups a poor rating. <BR>
<BR>
In past surveys, however, government institutions received more excellent
than poor ratings. That has now reversed for the state and federal governments,
as well as the courts. For example, 8% of coalition leaders in this latest
survey give the federal government an excellent rating, whereas 17% think
its performance has been poor. <BR>
<BR>
The trend among government agencies toward poor performance against substance
abuse is confirmed by another set of questions in this survey. We asked
if certain elected officials are more or less interested in substance abuse
issues now than two years ago. More than half (54%) of the coalition leaders
believe Congress is less interested and more than one-third (37%) think
state elected officials are less interested now than two years ago. Also,
37% think their governors are less interested in substance abuse now than
in 1993.<BR>
<BR>
As a final check on this disturbing finding, we compare the ratings provided
by the 652 coalitions that participated in both the 1993 survey and this
latest survey. These coalitions also give lower ratings to the state and
federal governments and the schools this time. <BR>
<BR>
The national picture described above masks considerable change over the
past two years within specific communities. An analysis of the ratings provided
by the coalitions in both the second and third surveys shows that local
action in some communities has improved although it has deteriorated in
others. For example, 16% of these 652 coalitions improve the ratings by
two or more categories they give to local law enforcement, whereas 24% have
lowered the score by two or more categories. The lesson is clear. Leadership
and participation must continually be renewed. If an especially active (or
difficult) official leaves, coalitions have an opportunity to get the new
official fully committed.<BR>
<BR>
More than half (54%) of the coalition leaders believe Congress is less interested
and more than one-third (37%) think state elected officials are less interested
in substance abuse now than two years ago. 
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="../../../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="../../../../../MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP
ISMAP><BR>
