<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Joe Camel vs. Frogs</TITLE>


</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

<H2>Sample Op-Ed</H2>
</CENTER>

<I>You can ask your Editorial Page Editor at your local newspaper to run the following Op-Ed -- either as is or tailored to fit your community.</I>

<CENTER><H3>Joe Camel vs. the Budweiser Frogs</H3></CENTER>

Last summer you couldn't watch television or read a newspaper without hearing about the rising number of teenage smokers. And when the executive branch of the federal government decided to launch an all-out attack on the problem --complete with a presidential press conference-- regulating tobacco advertising was one of the first measures the Clinton administration proposed.<BR>

<BR>
Does anyone believe that the Budweiser frogs appeal to kids any less than Joe Camel?
<BR><BR>
Yet the silence is deafening when it comes to the equally obvious links between alcohol advertising and underage drinking, despite the fact that nearly 30 percent of our high school seniors have had five or more drinks in a row in just the last few weeks. That's about the same percentage as say they smoked a cigarette within the past month.
<BR><BR>
Beer ads may be even more problematic because they're still broadcast through television and seen by kids more likely to channel surf than thumb through a magazine. Congress, however, couldn't care less; it has twice killed legislation that would have balanced the glamorous appeal of beer advertising with public health messages.
<BR><BR>
Tobacco advertising makes a less controversial target for regulation because there is probably not an American alive who does not admit that smoking can be dangerous to your health. Plus, Congress already acknowledged the role advertising played in hooking citizens of all ages on nicotine when it banned cigarette commercials on television nearly 30 years ago.
<BR><BR>
So why is the federal government so far behind the learning curve when it comes to alcohol? For one thing, the alcohol beverage industry has a powerful lobby in Washington. When the House of Representatives passed legislation late last year to reduce funding for the Center for Substance Abuse Prevention, the Wall Street Journal reported that key players on Capitol Hill received "thank you six packs" from the National Beer Wholesaler's Association, as well as from Coors Brewing.
<BR><BR>
Just as significant, the alcoholic beverage industry has been extremely skillful in manipulating public attitudes about drinking. Public Health advocates who express statistically supported concerns about alcohol abuse are denounced as "neoprohibitionists" who want to end the sale of alcohol when saving lives and preventing alcohol-related problems such as fatal car crashes and family violence are their real agenda.
<BR><BR>
Nor has the alcoholic beverage industry been hesitant to use advertising to try to persuade the American public that its product is for adults only. But does the industry mean what it says? Sales figures speak much more loudly than words and images crafted by public relations professionals : junior and senior high school students drink more than a billion cans of beer every year and they buy 35 percent of all wine coolers!
<BR><BR>
(INSERT NAME OF YOUR ORGANIZATION) is not suggesting that kids drinking should be taken more seriously than their smoking, but consider this startling fact from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services: the most likely cause of death for a 16-year-old in this country is alcohol.
<BR><BR>
If we are truly concerned about the health of our nation's youth, we'd better start applying the same standards to the Budweiser frog as we do to Joe Camel.
<BR><BR><BR>
YOUR NAME 
<BR>
ORGANIZATION
<BR>

<BR>
