<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Section Two: Coalition Impact</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | <A HREF="hillLetter.html">Letter</A> | <A HREF="Summary.html">Summary</A> | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
 <A HREF="one.html">One</A> | Two | <A HREF="three.html">Three</A>
| <A HREF="four.html">Four</A> | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| <A HREF="appendix.html">Appendix</A><HR>

<br><br><br> <H3>Section Two: Coalition Impact</CENTER>
</H3>
In community organizing, as in life, it is not so much what you do, but
rather, what you get done. The third survey explored the actual accomplishments
of community coalitions in preventing and reducing substance abuse in several
ways. Outcome, not process, will validate the movement. Processes such as
strategic planning may improve a community's chances for success, but it
is the results that matter.<BR>
<BR>
To assess the actual results of coalitions' work, we used three sets of
questions. First, we asked if they had been influential in bringing about
the activities communities often engage in to deal with substance abuse
problems. Next, we asked if they had been involved in state or local public
policy changes related to substance abuse. Finally, we asked if they could
report they had a direct impact on reducing substance abuse in their community,
and if so, how they knew. The answers are displayed in <A HREF="gifs/table12.gif">Table
12</A>, <A HREF="gifs/table13.gif">Table 13</A> and <A HREF="gifs/table14.gif">Table
14</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalition Influence</B><BR>
<BR>
Eighty-eight percent (88%) of the coalitions report that they have been
influential in bringing about better interorganizational collaboration.
Only 7% of the coalitions believe interorganizational collaboration has
not improved at all. Similarly, 88% believe they were influential in increasing
prevention programs, and only 6% think prevention has not increased at all.
More than half (61%) report influencing an increase in citizen participation.
Almost a quarter of respondents (22%) think they have had no effect on increasing
participation, and 17% say it has not occurred at all in their communities.
(See <A HREF="gifs/table12.gif">Table 12</A>.)<BR>
<BR>
Almost half of the coalitions (44%) report influencing an increase in treatment.
An additional 29% report they have no influence on the matter. Another 27%
report that there had not been any increase in treatment in their communities
at all.<BR>
<BR>
Over half (60%) of the coalitions say they have been influential in establishing
or increasing alcohol- or drug-free workplace programs. These programs address
the reality that the majority of illicit drug and alcohol abusers are employed.
They are also used as an appropriate way for coalitions to reach out to
get businesses and labor organizations interested in their work. Business
and labor involvement in coalitions can make a great deal of difference.<BR>
<BR>
Having a job is an essential element of successful recovery for most people
with drug and alcohol problems. Only 21% of the coalitions think they have
had any influence in this area, and 38% think job creation for people in
recovery in their communities has not happened at all. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Fighting Drugs Is All In A Day's Work In Tacoma, Wash.</B> <BR>
<BR>
Labor unions are working hard to fight gang violence and drug trafficking
in Tacoma, Wash. These groups mentor high-risk youth and provide them with
apprenticeships, run food drives for the needy and build kids' self-esteem
by displaying their artwork and essays in local businesses. <BR>
<BR>
The unions became involved in these efforts through the Safe Streets Campaign,
a local coalition fighting substance abuse in the community. &quot;We got
these groups involved by meeting them in their own space and around their
own agenda,&quot; says Priscilla Lisicich, director of the Campaign. &quot;We
explained to the union members the impact substance abuse has on their families
and neighborhoods and the kinds of benefits they would get as individuals
by joining with Safe Streets.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
For more information, call Lisicich at (206) 272-6824.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Involvement in Public Policy Change</B><BR>
<BR>
Public policy change has a major effect on how successful a community can
be in preventing and reducing substance abuse. Therefore, we asked if there
had been changes in public policy in coalitions' communities and if they
had been involved in these changes. More than half the coalitions report
that there have been changes in drinking and driving laws and tobacco use
regulations in the past two years. One-third report changes in alcohol regulation.
About one-quarter of the coalitions report tobacco tax increases in their
communities, and 14% report alcohol tax increases. <BR>
<BR>
Fewer than half of the coalitions were involved in passing the public policy
changes they report. An average of 44% say they were involved in tobacco,
alcohol and drunk driving changes. Only about a quarter have been involved
in implementing tax increases. (See <A HREF="gifs/table13.gif">Table 13</A>.)<BR>
<BR>
<I>Warning:</I> Even though the economy has been growing for the past four
years, 38% of the coalitions report that nothing has happened to create
new jobs for people with substance abuse problems. The situation is likely
to get worse as new welfare regulations take effect that create barriers
for people with drug and alcohol disabilities from receiving money and other
disability benefits. If our society cannot produce new jobs at a higher
rate than community coalition leaders report in the survey, many people
will slide back into addiction or will never see the hope they need to pull
themselves into sustained recovery. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalitions' Direct Impact on Substance Abuse</B><BR>
<BR>
It is a real challenge for community coalitions to measure the direct impact
of their work against substance abuse. With limited funds, coalitions are
expected to run their programs and &quot;prove&quot; that what they have
done prevented or reduced substance abuse. In many ways, this is an impossible
task because communities are dynamic, with many forces acting in conflicting
directions at the same time. All of these factors affect the civic environment
and, ultimately, the level of substance abuse.<BR>
<BR>
Therefore, it is very hard to &quot;prove&quot; causality for any single
endeavor. Process evaluation - that is, measuring the inputs to a program
- has been a frustrating substitute for understanding the impact of coalitions
and other anti-substance abuse efforts. <BR>
<BR>
In the third survey, we took a more direct approach. We asked the coalitions
to tell us if they thought they were having a direct impact on substance
abuse in their communities. (See <A HREF="gifs/table14.gif">Table 14</A>.)
If they did, we asked them to tell us how they knew. Coalitions responded
to these difficult questions with remarkable candor. <BR>
<BR>
More than half of the coalitions (54%) think they are having a direct impact
on reducing alcohol abuse; 48% think they are reducing illicit drug use;
35% think they are reducing tobacco use; and 30% report an impact on inhalant
use. About 10% report that they are having no impact at all on either alcohol
or illicit drugs. Between 37% and 55% (depending on the specific issue)
told us that they just do not know or cannot document whether they are having
a direct impact on these problems.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Measuring and Reporting Success</B> <BR>
<BR>
The answers we got to our request that coalitions tell us how they measure
success show the wide range of outcome and process measures that coalitions
cobble together to determine how they are doing. The responses are summarized
in <A HREF="gifs/table15.gif">Table 15</A>. We believe it to be an impressive
and important sign of the maturity of the coalitions that so many are able
to report serious efforts to measure their impact.<BR>
<BR>
Some coalitions track changes in objective measures over time. These include
school and community-use surveys, monitoring studies or official statistics
such as crime or emergency room reports. Others report success because there
are new substance abuse prevention or treatment programs in their communities,
which would lead to reductions in substance abuse. Other coalitions rely
on feedback from the community or continued funding as evidence of their
impact on the problem. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A Handbook for Developing Measures of Success</B><BR>
<BR>
Join Together, in conjunction with the Heller School at Brandeis University,
has published a handbook of substance abuse indicators that community coalitions
can use to track their success or failure. It is entitled How Do We Know
We Are Making a Difference? A Community Substance Abuse Indicators Manual.
Communities' experience implementing each of the indicators is being documented
and reported on Join Together Online. The handbook can be ordered by contacting
Join Together. Single copies are free; additional copies are $10 each.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Key Elements in Successful Coalitions</B><BR>
<BR>
Written strategies and equal participation by lay people and professionals
are key markers of coalitions that have been able to report success in their
communities. Common components of coalitions' strategies are displayed in
<A HREF="gifs/table16.gif">Table 16</A> on page 24. There is substantial
evidence from the survey that community coalitions with written strategic
plans to guide their work are more effective in reaching their goals than
are groups that do not have such plans.<BR>
<BR>
Coalitions with written plans are significantly more likely to report involvement
in successful efforts to increase prevention or treatment in their communities;
improve interagency collaboration; or change a policy than are groups operating
without such strategies. Seventy-seven percent (77%) of the coalitions that
say they have had a direct impact on reducing substance abuse have written
strategic plans, compared with the 23% of coalitions that have no written
strategic plan but still had an impact. (See <A HREF="gifs/table17.gif">Table
17</A>.)<BR>
<BR>
This finding is given more weight by the fact that the groups with the most
comprehensive strategies report success in the most areas. We ranked the
coalitions by the number of strategic elements they report in their plans,
and also by the number of successful change efforts in which they are involved.
When we compared the rankings, we found a significant positive correlation
between a higher number of strategic elements and reported involvement in
more successful efforts.<BR>
<BR>
To further test the impact of strategic planning, we linked the strategic
plan elements listed in the questionnaire with activities and involvements
coalitions report in other sections of the questionnaire. For example, we
matched the inclusion of a prevention plan in a coalition's plan with extensive
involvement in prevention programs and influence in increasing prevention
programs by that coalition. In 19 of 23 combinations we tested, the coalitions
that included an element in their strategic plan are extensively engaged
in the related activity or report that they have been very influential in
a related policy change.<BR>
<BR>
Although it is clear that strategy makes a difference, it is also important
to recognize that many coalitions are active in their communities without
having written strategies. They, too, report extensive involvement in many
different activities. For example, 69% of the coalitions without plans report
extensive activity in prevention, and 26% said they are extensively involved
in treatment programs.<BR>
<BR>
Further, many groups with strategies engage in activities that are outside
of their plans. For example, two-thirds of the coalitions are extensively
involved in alcohol issues, but fewer than one-third of them have a specific
written plan dealing with alcohol regulation.<BR>
<BR>
<B>What Is a Strategy Anyway?</B><BR>
<BR>
A strategic plan usually includes: 
<UL>
<LI>Specific goals for the coalition. For example: &quot;The percentage
of kids who try or use marijuana should go down every year.&quot; 
<LI>Programs that are related to achieving established goals. For example:
student and parent marijuana prevention education, anti-marijuana media
spots, youth-run activities, targeted action against sellers of paraphernalia
and cigarette papers, etc. 
<LI>Ways to monitor progress toward the goals. For example: regular school
surveys that measure use of marijuana by young people in the community.
<LI>A regular public report of the progress made and a description of the
process for reviewing current goals and programs and for adjusting them
to changing circumstances. For example: an annual public hearing by the
city council to review the community strategy and discuss the progress report.
</UL>
<B>Written Strategy Helps Lake Tahoe, Calif., Overcome Substance Abuse</B><BR>
<BR>
Identifying risk factors - and developing ways to overcome them - is what
Tahoe Prevention Network's (TPN) written strategy is all about. This strategy,
which focuses on systemwide change, is based on the results of a community
needs assessment conducted in Lake Tahoe, Calif., in 1990. <BR>
<BR>
The assessment identified four areas that TPN focuses on: community, schools,
family and individuals/peers. For each of these areas, TPN develops projects
that build resiliency to lower the risks of substance abuse. <BR>
<BR>
For instance, in the South Lake Tahoe schools, one risk factor is the high
level of student turnover due to the transient nature of the area. TPN tackled
this problem by creating a welcome center that helps new students quickly
assimilate into school and by requiring parents to meet with social service
providers as part of the enrollment process. There are a total of 25 such
projects within TPN's communitywide written plan. <BR>
<BR>
For more information, call Roger Volker at (916) 577-2677. 
<BR><BR>
