<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Summary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | <A HREF="hillLetter.html">Letter</A> | Summary | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
| <A HREF="one.html">One</A> | <A HREF="two.html">Two</A> | <A HREF="three.html">Three</A>
| <A HREF="four.html">Four</A> | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| <A HREF="appendix.html">Appendix</A><HR></CENTER>
<H3>
<br><br><CENTER>Executive Summary</CENTER>
</H3>
Almost 200 years ago, Alexis deTocqueville (Alexis deTocqueville, Democracy
in America, transl. George Lawrence (Harper &amp; Row, 1966).) wrote that
one of the unique characteristics of Americans was their willingness to
join together with their neighbors to solve community problems. The Third
National Join Together Survey, conducted from July through September 1995,
shows that this tradition continues to thrive. New coalitions to address
substance abuse, violence, tobacco use and HIV/AIDS have been formed in
every state since 1993. Nineteen hundred and ten community coalitions organized
against drugs participated in the third survey, 73% more than participated
in our 1992 and 1993 surveys combined. <BR>
<BR>
This third survey indicates that community coalitions, especially those
with comprehensive strategies, report that they have had a direct impact
on substance abuse in their communities. In hundreds of cities and towns,
the work of community groups, parents and even young people themselves is
preventing youth from experimenting with alcohol, tobacco or illegal drugs.
More than 200,000 volunteers are involved in these efforts. That's the good
news.<BR>
<BR>
The bad news is that substance abuse is getting worse in many communities,
yet the leaders of major government institutions are paying LESS attention
and doing a worse job than they did two years ago to address substance abuse
problems. <BR>
<BR>
The third survey findings are a warning to the nation. Elected officials,
business leaders, clergy, law enforcement personnel, school officials and
others must support the work being done by the community leaders and coalitions
or we will lose another generation of kids to drugs. Community mobilization,
prevention and treatment, as well as effective local law enforcement, must
be expanded or there will be even more drug use and crime in five years
than there is today.<BR>
<BR>
In the first National Join Together Survey, <I>Who Is Really Fighting the
War on Drugs</I> (1992), we documented the existence of community coalitions
that fight substance abuse in the majority of American communities. One
year later, the second national survey, Community Leaders Speak Out on Substance
Abuse, showed that the movement had expanded. We were able to describe the
activities undertaken by coalitions, including the adoption of comprehensive
strategies. Now, in the third survey, we can report the impact that coalitions
say they are having on their communities.<BR>
<BR>
There are two striking ironies in this survey. First, the movement can show
it has had an impact, but many of its leaders report that substance abuse
is getting worse in their communities anyway. Even the most effective coalitions
are only one factor among many community dynamics. The second irony is that
the movement is strong and growing, but it continues to depend heavily on
a federal government that is no longer committed to preventing or reducing
substance abuse in communities. As a consequence, federal funding for one
of the best approaches to prevent and reduce substance abuse - community
mobilization - may be cut down at the very time it is needed most.<BR>
<BR>
Additional principal findings, based on the responses of the <BR>
1910 lead coalitions and described more fully in this report, include the
following: 
<UL>
<LI>More than one-third (36%) of the coalition leaders report that substance
abuse is getting worse in their communities. However, 17% of the coalitions
think the problem is getting better. 
<LI>Coalition leaders who report the situation is improving were more likely
to also report increased citizen mobilization and volunteers, improved access
to treatment, expanded local law enforcement and increased prevention programs.
They also engaged in better coordination among agencies, and adopted comprehensive
strategies. These actions were significantly less likely to have occurred
where leaders reported the situation was getting worse. 
<LI>Many key elected officials are paying LESS attention to this problem
than they were two years ago, according to community coalition leaders.
Fifty-four percent (54%) say that Congress is paying less attention, and
37% say that their governors and state-elected officials are paying less
attention to substance abuse than they did two years ago. In contrast, 27%
say that mayors have increased their attention to substance abuse. 
<LI>Business and labor are doing as bad a job as we reported two years ago.
Coalition leaders rated their performance fair or poor by 79% and 88%, respectively.
The media and religious groups also continue to receive fair or poor marks
by 63% and 69% of the coalition leaders, respectively. 
<LI>Community coalition leaders are virtually unanimous in their support
for specific public policy changes to prevent and reduce substance abuse:
98% support restrictions on alcohol and tobacco advertising; 87% call for
lower legal blood alcohol limits for drivers; 94% want mandatory treatment
instead of prison for nonviolent offenders with drug and alcohol problems;
and 96% support immediate access to drug treatment for everyone who needs
it. Further, 79% oppose decriminalization of drug possession. 
<LI>The current survey shows how essential the federal government's role
has been in fostering the community coalition movement. The federal government
has funded new groups that have engaged new people to tackle this problem
and have taken a fresh community-oriented approach. About half of the community
coalitions receive some federal money directly or indirectly. Only 24% of
coalition funds come from state governments. Recognizing the need for longer-term
stability, a growing number (69%) of coalitions have diversified their funding
base, now relying on more than one funding source. 
</UL>
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="../../../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="../../../../../MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP
ISMAP><BR>
