<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Section Four: Public Policy Views</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | <A HREF="hillLetter.html">Letter</A> | <A HREF="Summary.html">Summary</A> | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
 <A HREF="one.html">One</A> | <A HREF="two.html">Two</A> | <A HREF="three.html">Three</A>
| Four | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| <A HREF="appendix.html">Appendix</A><HR></CENTER>
<H3>
<br><BR><CENTER>Section Four: Public Policy <BR>
Views of Coalition Leaders</CENTER>
</H3>
The leaders of the nation's movement against substance abuse have a clear
and sometimes unanimous view of the policies they need in order to be more
effective. The answers they give to the public policy choices listed in
the third survey show they believe a broad-based approach is needed. They
do not believe that a policy focusing on only one element will work. They
want their own prevention work supported by strong regulatory policies.
They favor expanded local law enforcement, and even stronger illicit drug
and alcohol laws. However, these leaders are just as firmly committed to
providing treatment to people with drug and alcohol problems. Finally, they
are willing to accept additional responsibility for reducing substance abuse
in their communities, and they urge the federal government to revamp its
spending priorities to make that possible. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Policies to Support Prevention</B><BR>
<BR>
Community coalition leaders believe their prevention work must be supported
by public policies that send strong and consistent social messages against
illicit drugs and excessive alcohol use. Ninety-eight percent (98%) favor
additional restrictions on alcohol and tobacco advertising. They do not
believe industry claims that marketing is not aimed at young people. Ninety-five
percent (95%) want increased taxes on alcohol because higher prices will
reduce use by young people. Low beer prices sometimes make it cheaper for
teens to drink beer than soft drinks, and this may be a subtle message of
encouragement that higher taxes will counteract. Eighty percent (80%) support
random drug testing in the workplace. This is important because a majority
of drug users are employed. Fear of losing a job is a strong social message
that drug use and drinking at work are unacceptable. A majority (70%) support
similar drug testing in the schools to send the same message. <A HREF="gifs/table19.gif">Table
19 </A>on the next page highlights the policy changes coalition leaders
support.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Law Enforcement Policies</B><BR>
<BR>
Community coalition leaders firmly oppose legalizing drugs. A full 95% support
increased local police enforcement of drug, alcohol and tobacco laws; 79%
oppose decriminalizing possession and 87% oppose decriminalizing sales of
currently illicit drugs; 82% favor increased penalties for sales of illicit
drugs; and 73% want stronger penalties for possession. <A HREF="gifs/table20.gif">Table
20</A> shows policies coalitions oppose.<BR>
<BR>
Ninety-seven percent (97%) support legislation to make it illegal for adolescents
to drive after drinking. Twenty-eight states have already enacted this law,
and a federal law has now been adopted that will force the rest of the states
to enact similar limits. Eighty-seven percent (87%) also favor lowering
legal blood alcohol limits for adults. Thirteen states have lowered the
legal blood alcohol concentration (BAC) standard from .10% to .08% - the
equivalent of four drinks in an hour on an empty stomach for a 155-pound
man. No state has yet to adopt the .05% standard used in Australia, New
Zealand and several European countries.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Policies to Support Treatment</B><BR>
<BR>
Coalition leaders' support for strong law enforcement should not be seen
as a &quot;lock them up and throw away the key&quot; approach. In fact,
support for access to drug and alcohol treatment is stronger in the third
survey than in earlier surveys. Fifty five percent (55%) of the community
coalition leaders strongly support that &quot;treatment be available for
everyone who needs it, immediately.&quot; This is up from 47% in 1993.<BR>
<BR>
Ninety-four percent (94%) also believe that treatment should be mandatory
for non-violent offenders who have drug or alcohol problems. They know that
drug offenders will be returning to the community and they want them back
- treated. Community coalition leaders know that offenders who receive treatment
are far less likely to return to crime than are those who go through the
criminal justice system without getting substance abuse treatment. <BR>
<BR>
Sixty-eight percent (68%) of community coalition leaders also favor &quot;needle
exchange&quot; programs for street addicts to prevent the spread of HIV.
They do not see support for this as contradicting their strong enforcement
preferences or their opposition to legalization.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Accepting Responsibility</B><BR>
<BR>
Over half (54%) of the community coalition leaders are willing to work with
others in their communities in a new youth development block grant proposed
by Congress that would replace current categorical prevention programs.
If such a program is adopted, 79% believe it should go directly to communities,
not to state or local government agencies exclusively.<BR>
<BR>
If community coalition leaders were in charge of the fight against substance
abuse, they would spend the money differently. We asked coalition leaders
how they would spend the federal anti-drug budget. They would make a dramatic
shift away from international interdiction toward prevention, treatment
and support for local law enforcement. <A HREF="gifs/table21.gif">Tables
21</A> and <A HREF="gifs/table2.gif">22</A> clearly show these differences
by comparing the fiscal year 1995 federal budget allocation with the budget
allocation preferred by community coalition leaders.
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF="../../../../../Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="../../../../../MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP
ISMAP><BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="../../../../../default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="../../../../jto/index.html">Index</A>
| <A HREF="../../../../jto/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="../../../../jto/comments.html">Comments</A>
| <A HREF="../../../../jto/help.html">Help</A><BR>
<BR>
