<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Appendix</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logoSmall.gif" WIDTH="187" HEIGHT="145" ALIGN=
left NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Leading from the Ground Up:</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3><CENTER>The Third National Survey of <BR>
the Community Movement Against Substance Abuse</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="title.html">Contents</A> | <A HREF="hillLetter.html">Letter</A> | <A HREF="Summary.html">Summary</A> | <A HREF="Acknowledge.html">Acknowledgements</A>
<BR>
 <A HREF="one.html">One</A> | <A HREF="two.html">Two</A> | <A HREF="three.html">Three</A>
| <A HREF="four.html">Four</A> | <A HREF="recommend.html">Recommendations</A>
| Appendix<HR></CENTER>
<H3>
<br><br><CENTER>Appendix </CENTER>
</H3>
The methodology for Join Together's Third National Survey was similar to
that of our 1992 and 1993 surveys. We replicated our initial efforts at
attempting to identify every community coalition in the nation by contacting
the following agencies and organizations in every state. We asked them to
provide us with a list of all task forces, coalitions, consortia, partnerships
and citizen action groups that they work with to address substance abuse
problems. They include: 
<UL>
<LI>State alcohol and drug agencies 
<LI>State Departments of Public Safety 
<LI>State juvenile justice agencies 
<LI>State education agencies 
<LI>State Departments of Mental Health and Mental Retardation 
<LI>State health and social services agencies 
<LI>State alcohol and drug services 
<LI>State Highway Safety Agencies 
<LI>National groups, such as MADD and NHTSA 
</UL>
<BR>
In July 1995, we mailed 31,500 surveys to organizations that were identified
by these agencies and the Join Together database of community coalitions.
One follow-up mailing was done for the cohort that participated in both
previous surveys to increase their response rate and to provide us with
an opportunity to denote trends. See the next page for a copy of the questionnaire.<BR>
<BR>
This report, however, is based primarily on the 1910 agencies that report
leading or sponsoring anti-substance abuse coalitions as opposed to agencies
that participate in coalitions headed by other groups. <BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Join Together Resources as of December 1995</B></CENTER>
<P>Join Together has a number of resources available to assist coalitions
and other community-based efforts to prevent and reduce substance abuse.<BR>
<BR>
<B>General Coalition Information</B><BR>
<BR>
Working from your own desk, Join Together Online (available on the Internet)
will help you identify and work with other communities fighting substance
abuse across the nation. Through Join Together Online you can access daily
summaries of major newspaper and wire service articles about substance abuse;
find facts, coalition stories and ideas for strengthening your organization
and measuring its success; and join a discussion group to exchange ideas
and get answers to questions from other coalitions and experts in the field.<BR>
A National Events Calendar will let you search for events locally or nationally
or contribute your own. You can also search our database of over 60,000
people to find others in your town, state or anywhere in the United States
with whom you can collaborate.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalition Funding Information</B><BR>
<BR>
Join Together Online has a special section devoted to <A HREF="/jto/funding/funding.html">Funding
News</A>. Updated daily, it gives you access to the full text of Federal
Register announcements, foundation profiles and tips on finding grants.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Coalition Impact</B><BR>
<BR>
How Do We Know We Are Making a Difference? A Community Substance Abuse Indicators
Handbook provides measures for communities to assess substance abuse problems.
These indicators can be powerful tools in local efforts to reduce substance
abuse. The first copy of this 86-page manual is free; additional copies
are $10 each.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Public Policy Materials</B><BR>
<BR>
Join Together has convened five national panels to examine how public policies
can be improved to support community-based efforts to reduce substance abuse.
Copies of the reports outlining recommendations made by these panels and
action steps that communities can take are available. Your community may
want to adopt a similar format to address your own policy issues. 
<UL>
<LI>Save Lives! Report, Recommendations and Action Steps of the Join Together
Public Policy on Underage Access to Alcohol-updated in 1995 
<LI>Health Reform for Communities: Recommendations on Financing Substance
Abuse Services 
<LI>Alcohol and Drug Abuse in America: Policies for Prevention and Community
Action Guide 
</UL>
Two other reports are being prepared as this survey is being published.
The first outlines recommendations and action steps that communities can
implement to make policies pertaining to the criminal justice system more
supportive of efforts to reduce substance abuse. The second report details
suggested policy changes and related action steps to make block grant policies
more supportive of community anti-substance abuse initiatives. Both reports
will be available for distribution in early 1996. 
<BR><BR>
