<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>1995 National Survey: Op-Ed</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H3><CENTER>SAMPLE OP-ED</CENTER>
</H3>
You can tailor the following op-ed with local examples and statistics and
send it to newspapers in your area. <BR>
<BR>
KEY INSTITUTIONS NEED TO JOIN ANTI-SUBSTANCE ABUSE EFFORTS        <BR>
<BR>
Missing in action: that's the status of elected officials, businesses, labor,
media and religious groups in the nation's war against drugs.        <BR>
<BR>
This finding comes from a recent national survey of 4,200 community coalitions
fighting substance abuse. When asked to rate the performance of such key
institutions, respondents said they are NOT as involved in anti-substance
abuse efforts as they could be.        <BR>
<BR>
This is alarming news; especially since alcohol and drug problems are on
the rise in communities like ours across the country.        <BR>
<BR>
In Stamford (replace with your community's name),  many programs are hard
at work battling substance abuse and related problems -- such as violent
crime, fatal car crashes, domestic violence, homelessness and HIV infection.
But these programs can not win this battle without support from other groups.
        <BR>
<BR>
Some of the ways you can help: ask your company to start a drug-free workplace
program; help schools bring kids and parents together to talk openly about
alcohol and drugs; write to legislators demanding they make substance abuse
problems a priority; ask your church or temple to sponsor events to raise
money for substance abuse programs; brainstorm with neighbors about ways
to keep your street drug-free; ask the media to recognize outstanding people
in the communitywho are making a difference; or volunteer a few hours a
week to help a local substance abuse organization.        <BR>
For more information about how to get involved in local efforts, call the
Stamford Substance Abuse Coalition at  (203) 555-1234. (Replace with your
organization's name and number).<BR>
<BR>
Sincerely,<BR>
<BR>
YOUR NAMEORGANIZATION<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Date:  11/6/95<BR>
