<TITLE>SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND OLDER AMERICANS: SAMPLE OP-ED</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>


<BR>


<H3>SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND OLDER AMERICANS</H3>
<H2>SAMPLE OP-ED</H2>
</center>

<P><I>You can submit the following Op-Ed as is to your community newspaper or localize it with examples and statistics of substance abuse among the elderly in your city or town. You can sign this with your name or ask one of your board members to sign it.</I>

<hr>

<P><H3>SUBSTANCE ABUSE PROBLEMS DON'T DISCRIMINATE BY AGE</H3>
		Many Americans look forward to their "golden years" -- that time when they can retire from work and concentrate on leisure activities. But for some, those years are lost in an alcohol or prescription-drug induced blur.<br>
	People over age 65 make up about 12 percent of the United States population, but this age group consumes more than 30 of all prescription drugs and 70 percent of over-the-counter remedies. And the risk of becoming dependent on some of these medications is high. Changes in absorption, distribution and metabolism as people age can alter a body's reaction to such substances.<br>
	The same is true with alcohol. Diminished liver function means that older adults get higher blood alcohol levels than younger counterparts who consume the same amount of alcohol. And people with untreated alcohol addictions will carry these addictions into old age. In addition, experts say that at least 15 percent of older Americans will develop a drinking problem when they retire or when a spouse dies.<br>
	Such addictions prove costly to the United States. Medicare spends more than $230 million a year for alcohol-related problems. And a typical hospital stay for alcohol abuse costs more than $4,500 a year, according to Medicare figures. Overall, 23 percent of Medicare costs are attributable to alcohol, drugs or tobacco addictions. And a recent study by the Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse in New York estimates that more than $1 trillion will be drained from the Medicare system by problems related to substance abuse.<br>
	While taxpayers will be forced to foot the bill for such costs, older addicts also suffer by having a severely reduced quality of life. This is why it is essential we help treat these addictions, rather than just paying the price for them. We need to ensure that substance abuse treatment is available for every person who needs it -- whether it is a 16-year-old daughter or a 75-year-old grandfather.<br>
	People must take the opportunity to let their legislators know that providing substance abuse treatment for all Americans -- including older Americans -- is a crucial component of health care.<br>


<P>Your name<br>
Title<br>
Organization<br>

<p><p><br>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"  WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0"ISMAP ></A>
