<TITLE>Tobacco: Sample Op-Ed</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H3>Youth Access to Tobacco</H3>
<H2>SAMPLE OP-ED</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>You can tailor the following Op-Ed with your findings about tobacco availability in your community and submit it to your local newspaper. Sign this with your name or ask an influential board members to author it.
<hr><br>

<P>TOBACCO PRODUCTS MAY BE TOO AVAILABLE TO YOUTH


<P>What is it about smoker's breath, nicotine-stained teeth and a hacking cough that draws more than one million kids each year to start smoking? 
	

<P>Perhaps it is the easy availability of tobacco in places near our schools that makes it easy for teens to try cigarettes. Consider the alarming fact that in the quarter-mile radius around Kendall Middle School there are 12 stores and vending machines selling tobacco. (REPLACE WITH YOUR LOCAL DATA.) This sends a subtle message to our youth that smoking for them is socially acceptable. And many of those who smoke will die prematurely from smoking-related illnesses.
	

<P>It is illegal for anyone under 18 to purchase tobacco, yet studies have found that this law is rarely a deterrent to keep youth from buying. The fact is that youth can purchase cigarettes successfully 70%-80% of the time over the counter, and 90%-100% of the time through vending machines. And each year merchants illegally sell 947 million packs of cigarettes to minors and 26 million containers of spitting tobacco. These products are worth $1.26 billion, and they generate $221 million in tobacco industry profits.
	

<P>The latest Monitoring the Future Study (released by the University of Michigan in July) found that smoking has increased by 30 percent among eighth graders over the past four years. This sends a clear signal that we need to reinvigorate our efforts to educate youth about the dangers of tobacco use and also to make sure that it is less available to them.
	

<P>Some of the ways we can do this include: "stings" -- sending youth under cover to find out which stores will sell them cigarettes; seeing if stores use displays that appeal to kids; providing tobacco retailer training for store owners and youth; counting cigarette advertisements near schools, including signs, posters, billboards and promotional giveaways; asking the city council to ban vending machines in our community; and asking store owners to partner with others to prevent kids from smoking in our community.
	

<P>We can keep kids from smoking -- and putting themselves in danger of premature death from cigarette-related illnesses -- if we all work together. 
	

<P>If you are interested in joining a communitywide effort to reduce the availability of cigarettes to kids, please contact (YOUR ORGANIZATION) at (YOUR PHONE NUMBER).


<P>Sincerely,<br>


<FORM ACTION="NetForms.acgi" METHOD=POST>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Name" VALUE="Your Name" SIZE=40 MAX=40><br>

<INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="text" VALUE="Your Organization" SIZE=40 MAX=40>

<p>
</FORM>
