<TITLE>The Fact Is. . .</TITLE>
</HEAD>


	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>





<H3>Drinking and Driving</H3>
<H2>The Fact Is. . .</H2></center>


<UL>

			<LI>Alcohol-related highway crashes are the leading cause of death for adolescents 	and young adults in the United States. (From the <A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">National Highway Traffic Safety Administration</A>'s 3-D Campaign)


			<LI>About two in every five Americans will be involved in an alcohol-related crash at 	some time in their lives. (<A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">NHTSA</A>, Traffic Safety Facts 1993 - Alcohol)


			<LI>Approximately 17,461 Americans died in alcohol-related crashes in 1993, and about one-third of them under the age of 25. This figure accounts for 44 percent 	of all traffic fatalities that occurred that year. (NHTSA 3-D)


		<LI>Among young people (aged 15 to 20), 5,905 died in motor vehicle crashes in 	1993. Forty percent (2,364) of these crashes were alcohol-related.  (<A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">NHTSA</A>, 	Youth Fatal Crash and Alcohol Facts 1993)


		<LI>Alcohol-related motor vehicle crashes cost the nation $46 billion annually in lost 	productivity (63.4%), medical costs (12%), property damage (18%), and other 	direct expenditures (6.6%). Over $5 billion of these costs are for health care. 	(<A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">NHTSA</A> 3-D)


			<LI>Many young people report riding with a driver who had been drinking, says the 	Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. In fact, 11.3 percent of 12 to 13-	year-olds said they had been driven by someone who had been drinking in the 	past month; the same was true of 21.7 percent of 14 to 17-year-olds; and 34.5 	percent of 18 to 21-year-olds. (<A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">NHTSA</A> 3-D)


			<LI>Even when they haven't been drinking, young drivers (age 15 - 20) have a higher 	crash risk than other drivers -- this risk increases more with each drink than for 	drivers age 21 and older. (Zador, P., Journal of Studies on Alcohol, 1991 )
</UL>


<P><H3>PREVENTION WORKS TO SAVE LIVES</H3>


<UL>
	<LI>The number of alcohol-related car crashes has declined by 26 percent in the last 	decade. (<A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">NHTSA</A>, Traffic Safety Facts) 


	<LI>All states and the District of Columbia now have a minimum drinking age of 21. 	These laws have reduced fatal car crashes involving drivers age 18 to 20 by 13 	percent and have saved an estimated 13,968 lives since 1975. (<A HREF="http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/">NHTSA</A>, Traffic Safety Facts) 


	<LI>If all states adopted .00 or .02 legal Blood Alcohol Content limits for drivers 	under 21 (Zero Tolerance Laws), each year 375 fatal car crashes would be 	prevented. However, 26 states still have not adopted zero tolerance laws (From a study called &quot;Lower Legal Blood Alcohol Limits for Young Drivers,&quot; 	published in the November-December 1994  issue of Public Health Reports)
</UL>
		

<p>


[<A HREF="Alcohol_Index.html">Back</A> to Drinking and Driving]
<p>

