    <HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Alerts</TITLE></HEAD><!-Default-><BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/policy.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/policy.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" ALIGN=bottom BORDER="0" ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/policy/policy.html">Policy</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/panel.html">Panels</A> | <A HREF="/jto/policy/surveys.html">Surveys</A> |<A HREF="/news/alerts/Latest_News.qry?MediaAction=True&Summaries=On&Max=7&Last=30">Alerts</A> | <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/pol">Archives</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/links.html">Links</A></FONT></CENTER><H1>Action Alert</H1><p><TABLE WIDTH = "90%" CELLSPACING = "0"><TR><TD WIDTH = "60%"><h2>Updated Alert on Senate Alcohol TV Ads Hearings</h2></TD><TD></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN = "2"><FONT COLOR = "BLACK">From Center on Alcohol Advertising<br><br>February 5, 1997<br>For more information, contact: <A HREF="mailto:lleiber@traumafdn.org">Laurie Leiber</A>, (510) 649-8942<br><br><b>Updated Alert on Senate Hearings -- NOTE NEW DATE<br>We Don't Need More Alcohol Ads on Television</b><br><br>In June, 1996, Seagram's broke a 48 year voluntary joint agreement between broadcasters and distilled spirit producers that kept liquor commercials off radio and television. DISCUS (Distilled Spirits Council of the US) followed Seagram's unilateral action last October by officially ending their participation in the voluntary ban. The national broadcasters continue to observe the ban but local affiliate and independent stations have begun to air liquor ads in several markets.<br><br>Both the President and FCC chairman Reed Hundt asked Seagram's to remove their ads. Congressman Joe Kennedy (D-Mass) introduced a bill to make the previously voluntary ban mandatory. Numerous public health and prevention organizations including MADD, CSPI, and the American Academy of Pediatrics publicly oppose broadcast liquor ads. The NCADD Board voted to propose counter ads rather than directly dispute liquor ads on TV and radio.<br><br>DISCUS has launched a major public relations campaign defending their right to advertise using the broadcast media. Broadcasters assert that the FCC has no authority and have blasted Reed Hundt for speaking out on the issue. The FTC announced an inquiry into the new liquor ads and a Stroh's malt liquor commercial that aired during "My So-Called Life", a popular children's show on MTV.<br><br>Meanwhile, Anheuser-Busch tried to slink quietly off MTV on Christmas eve. One week later, both AdAge and The Wall Street Journal (January 6) published a one week analyses of current audience demographics for some TV beer ads. AdAge revealed that 40 early and prime time beer ads (including 27 Budweiser ads) aired on MTV when the underage audience was as high as 56%. The Wall Street Journal showed that beer ads shown on MTV, E! and BET reached audiences as high as 69% underage (Beavis and Butthead).<br><br><b>An Opportunity for Action</b><br><br>Aggressive promotion of alcoholic beverages to children is nothing new. Liquor makers' recent move to add liquor commercials to the broadcast media has raised the issue for public debate. Public health advocates can use this opportunity to advance a rational policy that will protect children from all alcohol ads on TV and radio. Our first goal should be to maintain the status quo, that is, keep liquor ads off. Then public health advocates should demand full disclosure of how broadcast alcohol ads already reach underage viewers. Broadcasters use detailed audience demographic data to price their advertising time. Advertisers use the same type of information to select audiences for their commercials. Policy-makers need this information to make appropriate policy decisions.<br><br><b>Senate Hearings Scheduled for February 25</b><br><br>The Subcommittee on Communications of the Senate Commerce Committee will hold hearings to discuss alcoholic beverage ads on TV and radio on February 25, 1997. Campaign contributions are pouring into Congress from broadcasters, liquor makers, brewers and beer wholesalers. Donations guarantee these business interests access to policy makers, most will be represented at the hearing. Only two public health advocates are invited to testify. Your calls and letters can force the Senate to do more than pretend to consider the public health impacts of unchecked alcohol advertising on our broadcast media.<br><br><b>WHAT YOU CAN DO</b><br><br>Call or write your Senators and ask them to:<UL><LI>Support keeping liquor ads off TV and radio. Demand that the liquor industry go back to its long-standing voluntary ban and ask broadcasters to refuse liquor ads.<LI>Support full disclosure of the current audience for all alcohol ads on TV and radio. Support expanded inquiries by the Federal Trade and Federal Communications Commissions.</UL>###<br><br><b>See also:</b>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI> <A HREF="http://www.senate.gov/senator/index.html?81,7">Senators of the 105th Congress</A>
</UL></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>02/07/1997</TD><TD ALIGN="RIGHT"><b>Source: Join Together Online</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><I>Distributed by <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">Join Together Online</A>.</I></P>    <P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle  ISMAP><BR><BR></A><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A><BR><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="/">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></B></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
