<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Tobacco Survey: Statistics</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/policy.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/policy.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" ALIGN=bottom BORDER="0" ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/policy/policy.html">Policy</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/panel.html">Panels</A> | <A HREF="/jto/policy/surveys.html">Surveys</A> |<A HREF="/news/alerts/Latest_News.qry?MediaAction=True&Summaries=On&Max=7&Last=30">Alerts</A> | <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/pol">Archives</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/links.html">Links</A></FONT></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>Surveys: <BR>
Tobacco Retail Outlet Counting Project</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3>Survey Results:</H3>
<BR>
There were <B>over 1,200 tobacco retail outlets</B> found within a quarter-mile
radius of these 222 schools. Just seven percent (7%) of the total number
of schools surveyed reported that there were no outlets within the quarter
mile radius! This represents an average of approximately 6 outlets located
near each school. As the chart below indicates, convenience and grocery
stores which sell tobacco were most commonly found near schools. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Type of Outlet | Number | Percentag</B>e
<UL>
<LI>Convenience Store | 300 | 24%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Grocery Store | 261 | 21%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Gas Station | 188 | 15%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Restaurant | 153 | 12%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>* Other | 112 | 9%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Liquor Store | 106 | 9%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Drug Store | 72 | 6%<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Vending Machine | 44 | 4% 
</UL>
<BR>
<B>TOTAL</B> <B>| 1,236 | 100%</B><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
* On the survey form, teams recorded &quot;other&quot; tobacco outlets.
Some of these other tobacco retail outlets listed included <B>laundromats,
candy stores, card stores, bowling </B>alleys, paper stores, take-out pizza
/ deli establishments, and thrift stores. Clearly, children frequent these
types of establishments, and sell products which appeal to children. Among
youths aged 12-17 years who usually bought their own cigarettes in 1989,
about 85% often or sometimes bought them from a small store, 50% from a
large store, and 15% from a vending machine.<BR>
<BR>
(&quot;Youth and Elders Against Tobacco Use - Youth Access to Tobacco Fact
Sheet.&quot; US Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service,
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for Chronic
Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, Office on Smoking and Health, March,
1994.) <BR>
<BR>
