<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Tobacco Survey: Participants</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/policy.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/policy.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" ALIGN=bottom BORDER="0" ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/policy/policy.html">Policy</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/panel.html">Panels</A> | <A HREF="/jto/policy/surveys.html">Surveys</A> |<A HREF="/news/alerts/Latest_News.qry?MediaAction=True&Summaries=On&Max=7&Last=30">Alerts</A> | <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/pol">Archives</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/links.html">Links</A></FONT></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>Surveys: <BR>
Tobacco Retail Outlet Counting Project</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3>Participants:</H3>
In twenty seven states, more than 500 volunteers (402 youth; 124 adults)
were involved in counting tobacco outlets within a quarter-mile radius of
over 200 schools. These schools represented over 100 communities from across
the country. Communities as diverse as Anchorage, Alaska, Winner, South
Dakota, Ellsworth, Maine, and Jupiter, Florida, representing all four corners
of the U.S., submitted results to Join Together. <BR>
<BR>
This tobacco outlet counting project generated a great deal of interest,
enthusiasm, and participation among concerned citizens. For example: 
<UL>
<LI>75 youth, accompanied by 3 adults surveyed Boyne City Public Schools
in Boyne City, MI; 
<LI>64 youth on their own surveyed a middle school in Creston, OH; 
<LI>35 youth and 3 adults in Passaic, NJ surveyed an elementary school in
their community; 
<LI>25 youth and 4 adults surveyed a high school in Monroe, LA. 
<LI>A single volunteer in Laredo, TX surveyed 27 schools in his area; while
another one surveyed 22 schools in Leominster, MA; 
<LI>A team of two adult volunteers in Martinsburg, WV surveyed 20 schools.
</UL>
GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION:<BR>
<BR>
Community teams selected a total of 222 schools for this project, approximately
half (45%) of which were elementary schools. Middle schools represented
30%, while high schools comprised 25% of the total number of schools surveyed.<BR>
<BR>
Half (49%) of the areas surveyed surrounding schools were classified as
rural, while 28% of areas were classified as urban; the remaining areas,
23%, were classified as suburban. This means that youth access to tobacco
is not just a big city problem--it affects rural communities all across
the country! <BR>
<BR>
Almost two-thirds of communities described the area in which the school
is located as mixed commercial &amp; residential; one-third indicated the
areas were residential.<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="intro.html">Return to Tobacco Survey Introduction.</A><BR><BR>
