<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Tobacco Survey: Stories</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/policy.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/policy.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" ALIGN=bottom BORDER="0" ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/policy/policy.html">Policy</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/panel.html">Panels</A> | <A HREF="/jto/policy/surveys.html">Surveys</A> |<A HREF="/news/alerts/Latest_News.qry?MediaAction=True&Summaries=On&Max=7&Last=30">Alerts</A> | <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/pol">Archives</A>| <A HREF="/jto/policy/links.html">Links</A></FONT></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER>Surveys: <BR>
Tobacco Retail Outlet Counting Project</CENTER>
</H2>
<H3>Interesting Stories:</H3>
<BR>
The community teams we worked with presented us with some interesting stories
and comments. Here are just a few: 
<UL>
<LI>At a convenience store in Newport, NH, a team of seven students reported
that &quot;individual packs on a rack in the store were readily <B>accessible
to teens</B>, and that they could easily be shoplifted.&quot; The team leader,
a school nurse, and the student team brought this problem to the attention
of the store employees, and the rack was moved behind the counter. The team
confirmed that this is a store where their friends and other students would
go to purchase cigarettes.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>In Boone, Iowa, the team reported that <B>almost all establishments</B>
(which sold tobacco products)<B> had in-store single pack displays in front
of the counter</B>. Again, the implication is that underage youth could
easily steal the packs. When a team member (who happened to be a local sheriff)
brought this fact to the attention of a store employee, he replied &quot;What
do I care? The tobacco industry pays for this display, so any loss due to
shoplifting doesn't come out of our pocket.&quot; This team plans to release
its findings to the two local newspapers, and to the local radio station.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>While some rural communities indicated that none to few tobacco outlets
exist within a quarter-mile radius of schools, others, like the team from
Passaic, NJ indicated that there were a total of <B>76 tobacco outlets surrounding
one school, including candy </B>stores! The Director of the Passaic Alliance
for the Prevention of Substance Abuse told us that this project was very
enlightening for the kids who conducted the survey. &quot;The kids were
shocked to find this incredibly high number of tobacco outlets on the streets
surrounding their school! Also noteworthy, many of the stores which sold
cigarettes were mom &amp; pop-type stores, which often sell candy and items
that appeal to youth.&quot; Additionally, the Director plans to submit the
survey results to the local newspaper, in order to increase citizens' awareness.<BR>
<BR>
<LI>Several communities, such as Mount Vernon, OH indicated that they had
previously conducted sting operations, whereby minors attempt to purchase
tobacco products. The team from Mount Vernon has reported that during the
first sting, tobacco retailers illegally sold tobacco products to minors
44% of the time; during the second sting, the percentage dropped to 33%.
By having conducted the tobacco retail outlet counting project, other communities
may decide to follow-up with a sting operation as well. <BR>
<BR>
<LI>A high school football coach in Oshkosh, WI conducted a survey in his
community, polling 6 schools. The coach reported that &quot;students admitted
that it is easier to purchase cigarettes during certain hours...the kids
know who is working during certain shifts (friends or lenient store employees),
and will go to those stores during those times.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<LI>In New Haven, CT, the team found that in many of the tobacco retail
outlets, &quot;loosies&quot; or single cigarettes were being sold. The youth
team confirmed to one of the adults who worked with them that &quot;it is
<B>much easier for underage kids to buy </B>loosies.&quot; In this community,
the adult volunteer stated, &quot;single cigarette sales is a huge problem.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
<LI>In Fayetteville, NC, an adult volunteer reported that, &quot;the availability
of tobacco near schools in their community is immense, as is advertising
for tobacco products. But more surprising is the fact that there were zero
vending machines--efforts should therefore focus on convenience stores and
gas stations.&quot; Volunteers plan to address these issues when planning
follow-up steps. <BR>
</UL>
<A HREF="intro.html">Return to Tobacco Survey Introduction.</A><BR><BR>
