    <TITLE>Tobacco And Youth: How to Organize other Groups</TITLE>
</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/issues.map"><IMGSRC="/Mapserve/issues.gif"WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75" BORDER="0 ALIGN=middle"ISMAP ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>

<H2><CENTER><BR>
HOW TO ORGANIZE LOCAL GROUPS </CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
It is easier to bring about lasting change when you have the support of
a cross-section of organizations and people representing your community.
That's why it is important to try to involve as many groups of people as
possible in your efforts to count the number of stores and outlets that
sell tobacco within a quarter-mile of a local public school. <BR>
<BR>
In addition to helping you with this project, these groups can also offer
valuable resources to help your organization be more successful. <BR>
<BR>
Some groups that can assist your efforts: 
<UL>
<LI>Students 
<LI>Parents 
<LI>Teachers 
<LI>Parent/Teacher Organizations 
<LI>Teachers' Unions 
<LI>Highway Safety Agencies 
<LI>Insurance Companies 
<LI>Health Care Workers 
<LI>Public Health Care Officials 
<LI>Police 
<LI>Media 
<LI>MADD 
<LI>SADD 
<LI>Neighborhood groups 
<LI>Civic organizations 
<LI>Chamber of Commerce 
<LI>Local legislators 
<LI>Religious groups 
<LI>Senior Citizens 
</UL>
Some ways to get these groups to join you: 
<OL>
<LI>Publicize your event in the calendar section of your local newspaper
and ask your local radio station to mention it on the air. 
<LI>Call representatives from these groups and extend a personal invitation.
<LI>Send a written announcement in the mail. 
<LI>Put up posters in schools, grocery stores and churches 
<LI>Announce this project in your organization's newsletter, in the school
newspaper, and through a mailing to parents and the media. 
</OL>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"
WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle CENECASCALEIMAGE="0" ISMAP
