</DOCHDR>
    <HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Press Releases</TITLE></HEAD><!-Default-><BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/newsban.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/newsban.gif" WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75"BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A></CENTER><BR><CENTER><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/news/news.html">News &amp; Communications</A> | <A HREF="/news/jto/Latest_News.qry">News</A>| <A HREF="/news/releases/Latest_News.qry?PressReleases=True&Summaries=On&Max=150&Last=30">Releases</A>| <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/news">Archives</A> | <A HREF="/URLs/JTO/URL_Show.qry?header=news&filter=drugs&Category=Media&Summaries=on">Links</A></FONT></CENTER><p><TABLE WIDTH = "90%" CELLSPACING = "0"><TR><TD WIDTH = "60%"><h2>Tobacco Giants Sue Alaska</h2></TD><TD></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN = "2"><FONT COLOR = "BLACK">From the State of Alaska, Office of the Governor<br><br>For immediate release: January 12, 1997<br><br>For more information, contact: <A HREF="mailto:Bob_King@gov.state.ak.us">Bob King</A> or <A HREF="mailto:Claire_Richardson@gov.state.ak.us">Claire Richardson</A>, (907) 465-3500, (fax) (907) 465-3533<br><br><b>Tobacco Giants Sue Alaska<br>Knowles Seeks to Recover Health Care Costs From Cigarette Industry</b><br><br>Gov. Tony Knowles announced today the State of Alaska has been sued by four tobacco companies in an attempt to prevent the state from recovering millions of dollars in state and Medicaid funds spent providing for Alaskans seriously and fatally injured by cigarettes and smokeless tobacco. The four firms -- Philip Morris; Brown & Williamson; Lorillard; and R. J. Reynolds -- filed suit against Attorney General Bruce Botelho in federal district court in Anchorage on Wednesday.<br><br>"I hope this proves to be the straw that breaks Joe Camel's back," Knowles said. "This lawsuit is the tobacco industry's attempt to avoid financial responsibility for the injuries its products have caused Alaskans. The industry has targeted Alaska children, deliberately withheld safer products and has misled the public about the addiction and danger of smoking. It's outrageous that the tobacco industry would try to silence the state just because we were thinking about filing a suit, but now that they've fired the first shot, I'll gladly go into the battle."<br><br>The lawsuit comes as an apparent preemptive strike to prevent Alaska from joining other states that have filed lawsuits against the tobacco industry. Knowles has been considering a suit to recover the state's costs to treat smoking related illnesses and in December, Attorney General Botelho wrote selected law firms experienced in complex litigation, seeking proposals to undertake such litigation on a contingency fee basis.<br><br>In its lawsuit, the tobacco companies seek to block any such state action. Among other claims, the tobacco companies argue that warning labels on cigarette packs exempt the companies from any responsibility for harm caused by their product, that a state lawsuit would violate the tobacco companies First Amendment right to say that nicotine is not addictive, and that a state lawsuit would "severely and adversely impact interstate commerce in the sale of cigarettes."<br><br>"The tobacco industry has filed similar preemptive lawsuits against other states and has never won," said Attorney General Bruce Botelho. "We also expect to prevail in this lawsuit which will pave the way for recovering monetary damages from the tobacco industry for injuries their products have caused and the costs to the state Medicaid system. This litigation is also important because it entitles the State of Alaska to participate in any global resolution of nationwide tobacco litigation that is now pending."<br><br>"This lawsuit is important to every Alaskan," Knowles said. "As state revenues become scarce, we cannot stand by and allow an industry to market dangerous products that cause millions of dollars in damages which have to be paid for with state Medicaid funds and by every employer and employee that contributes to a medical plan. The industry cannot be allowed to continue to prey on Alaska children by marketing cigarettes and smokeless tobacco directly to them."<br><br>Knowles cited several statistics on the effect of smoking in Alaska:<UL><LI>72 percent of Alaska high school students report having tried smoking, resulting in 21.1 percent becoming frequent cigarette users. The national average among high school students is 13.8 percent;<LI>Tobacco use among Alaska adults, 28.9 percent, is the second highest in the nation;<LI>Smoking-related illnesses result in the deaths of 470 Alaskans a year, and direct medical care costs estimated at $96.5 million annually.<LI>When indirect costs such as lost earnings and productivity are included, the total estimated economic impact of smoking on Alaska is estimated at $300 million annually.<LI>Cigarette smoking caused more deaths in Alaska from 1992 to 1994 than AIDS, alcohol, airplane crashes, falls, fires, firearms, and motor vehicle crashes combined.</UL>"Litigation alone will not adequately address the smoking problem in Alaska," Knowles said. "Education comes first in my three step plan. We need to work with schools to educate children about the dangers of smoking and educate communities about the real costs of tobacco. Secondly, the legislature needs to take action on my dollar a pack increase in the state's tobacco tax. This tax is a proven measure which will reduce teen smoking. And then comes litigation to recover the costs that smoking and smokeless tobacco has incurred on the state treasury."<br><br>Knowles will introduce legislation calling for a dollar a pack increase in the tobacco tax tomorrow, the first day of the 20th Alaska Legislature.<br><br>###<br><br>
<b>See also:</b>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI> <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org/news/jto/Show_News.qry?News_uid=9804"> Alaska Will File Medicaid Suit</A></UL>
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>01/13/1997</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><I>Distributed by <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">Join Together Online</A>.</I></P>    <P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle  ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A></FONT><BR><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="/">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></B></CENTER></BODY>
