    <HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Press Releases</TITLE></HEAD><!-Default-><BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/newsban.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/newsban.gif" WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75"BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A></CENTER><BR><CENTER><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/news/news.html">News &amp; Communications</A> | <A HREF="/news/jto/Latest_News.qry">News</A>| <A HREF="/news/releases/Latest_News.qry?PressReleases=True&Summaries=On&Max=150&Last=30">Releases</A>| <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/news">Archives</A> | <A HREF="/URLs/JTO/URL_Show.qry?header=news&filter=drugs&Category=Media&Summaries=on">Links</A></FONT></CENTER><p><TABLE WIDTH = "90%" CELLSPACING = "0"><TR><TD WIDTH = "60%"><h2>McCaffrey Deeply Concerned About Colombian Court&#146;s Light Sentences For Drug Criminals</h2></TD><TD></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN = "2"><FONT COLOR = "BLACK">From the Office of National Drug Control Policy<br><br>For immediate release: January 19, 1997<br>For more information, contact: Don Maple or Bob Weiner, (202) 395-6618<br><br><b>White House Drug Policy Director McCaffrey Deeply Concerned About Colombian Court&#146;s Light Sentences For Drug Criminals</b><br><br>WASHINGTON, DC -- White House Drug Policy Director Barry R. McCaffrey has reacted strongly to the action of a Colombian court in leniently sentencing the notorious Rodriguez Orejuela brothers, leaders of the powerful Cali drug cartel. These minimal sentences based upon sentence reduction provisions of Colombian law, mean that Gilberto Rodriguez Orejuela and his brother Miguel, already in pre-sentence confinement, could serve as little as three to five years additional incarceration for their convictions on drug trafficking charges.<br><br>Director McCaffrey stated: "Illegal drugs have killed 100,000 Americans and cost us $300 billion over the last decade. Colombia's people, police, armed forces, and news media have suffered incredibly from this criminal activity. These artificial sentences for the Rodriguez Orejuela brothers are indicative of inadequate support for the brave efforts of Colombia's law enforcement officials and the international community, and they are wholly out of line with the seriousness of their crimes."<br><br>The United States has urged support for a justice system that would protect Colombians and Americans alike from the menace of the drug cartels. These light sentences demonstrate the urgent need for Colombia to pass sentencing reform legislation as soon as possible. The Cali cartel has continued to exert strong influence throughout government. Even when they have been convicted, drug lords have been imprisoned in facilities from which they were allowed to continue running their criminal empire.<br><br>In further demonstration of our intent to confront the power of Colombian drug gangs, the Department of Treasury&#146;s U.S. Office of Foreign Assets Control, working together with the Department of Justice, this week released the names of another 78 Colombian businesses and individuals that front for drug trafficking organizations, bringing to 359 the total identified to date. All now face severe economic sanctions by the United States.<br><br>###<br><br></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>01/21/1997</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><I>Distributed by <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">Join Together Online</A>.</I></P>    <P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle  ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A></FONT><BR><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="/">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></B></CENTER></BODY>
