    <HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Press Releases</TITLE></HEAD><!-Default-><BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/newsban.map"><IMG SRC="/Mapserve/newsban.gif" WIDTH="450" HEIGHT="75"BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle ISMAP></A></CENTER><BR><CENTER><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/jto/news/news.html">News &amp; Communications</A> | <A HREF="/news/jto/Latest_News.qry">News</A>| <A HREF="/news/releases/Latest_News.qry?PressReleases=True&Summaries=On&Max=150&Last=30">Releases</A>| <A HREF="/go.qry?gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:7003/11/news">Archives</A> | <A HREF="/URLs/JTO/URL_Show.qry?header=news&filter=drugs&Category=Media&Summaries=on">Links</A></FONT></CENTER><p><TABLE WIDTH = "90%" CELLSPACING = "0"><TR><TD WIDTH = "60%"><h2>New Approaches Prepared to Curb Underage Drinking</h2></TD><TD></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN = "2"><FONT COLOR = "BLACK">From the American Medical Association<br><br>Embargoed for release: January 21, 1997<br>For more information, contact: <A HREF="mailto:Arnold_Collins@ama-assn.org">Arnold Collins</A>, AMA, (312) 464-4430; <A HREF="mailto:jkh@rwjf.org">Joan Hollendonner</A>, RWJF, (609) 243-5928<br><br><b>New Approaches Prepared to Curb Underage Drinking<br>AMA Announces 11 Coalitions Launching Innovative Alcohol Reduction Programs</b><br><br>CHICAGO, Jan. 2l -- From Puerto Rico to Oregon, 11 groups dedicated to the better health of young Americans are launching major campaigns this month to reduce underage drinking of alcohol. The groups, selected by the American Medical Association and The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, will combine -- and build upon -- hundreds of smaller organizations, to change the environment in which young people learn about drinking.<br><br>The new campaigns -- around policies, alcohol advertising and public attitudes -- will focus on various segments of the public and, to a degree not tried before, will involve young people and broader sections of American communities.<br><br>"With the launch of this new program, we are finally taking decisive action against a major public health crisis that has taken a huge toll in the lives and futures of young Americans," said Percy Wootton, M.D., AMA president-elect. "These are powerful groups with innovative plans that can put a cork into underage drinking."<br><br>"For each of the 11 projects, an impressive number of diverse organizations have come together to collaborate and coordinate their efforts," said Steven A. Schroeder, M.D., president of The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation. "The common goal for these newly formed coalitions is to decrease the number of health, safety, and social problems caused by underage alcohol use."<br><br>The coalitions plan actions as diverse as reducing the marketing, sales and accessibility of alcohol to young people, increasing surveillance of young drivers, educating police and judges, and creating a corps of youth leaders to influence adults and peers.<br><br>The program, entitled "Reducing Underage Drinking Through Coalitions," complements a major university high-risk drinking program announced by the AMA in October. Both programs, funded by The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation (RWJF), of Princeton, N J, are directed by the American Medical Association.<br><br>Alcohol is a major cause of premature deaths in the United States, implicated in at least one-third of fatal car accidents -- the leading cause of death for teenagers. It poses risks for assault, rape, drowning, recreational injury and sexually transmitted disease, and -- though most high school and college students cannot purchase alcohol legally -- studies show that 25% of 8th graders, 51% of 12th graders and 68% of college students drink.<br><br>The 11 coalitions selected to participate in the $10.2 million, four-year program are:<UL><LI>Aspira, Inc. of Puerto Rico<LI>DC Community Prevention Partnership, Inc.<LI>Ecumenical Ministries of Oregon<LI>Governors Institute on Alcohol and Substance Abuse, Inc. (NC)<LI>Governors Partnership to Protect Connecticut's Workforce, Inc.<LI>Indiana Communities for Drug-Free Youth, Inc.<LI>Metropolitan Atlanta Council on Alcohol and Drugs, Inc.<LI>Minnesota Institute of Public Health<LI>Missouri Association of Community Task Forces<LI>Mothers Against Drunk Driving, Louisiana<LI>Pennsylvania Liquor Control Board</UL>Of 5l interested coalitions, the AMA, RWJF and a national advisory committee have chosen 11 promising groups. Each will receive up to $946,000 over a four-year period. None of the coalitions had worked together before as presently constituted, and none has addressed alcohol abuse with a broad, environmental focus. For half of them, this is the first time that youth will play a major role. The new program will be administered by the AMA's Office of Alcohol and Other Substances and evaluated under an independent university contract. Richard Yoast, Ph.D. is director of the AMA office. Johnnetta Davis is deputy director.<br><br>For further information, and a summary of individual coalition plans, contact: Arnold Collins, (312) 464-4430 or Joan Hollendonner, (609) 243-5928.<br><br>###<br><br></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>01/24/1997</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><I>Distributed by <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">Join Together Online</A>.</I></P>    <P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle  ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Comments</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/help.html">Help</A></FONT><BR><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="-1">Distributed by Join Together<BR><A HREF="/">http://www.jointogether.org</A></FONT></B></CENTER></BODY>
