<BR>
<H3>Domestic Violence and Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>Sample Press Release</H2></center>
If you wish, you can generate a ready to print letter by filling in the form boxes and pressing [Generate] at the bottom.

<HR>
<FORM ACTION="DV_PressOutput.nclk" METHOD=POST>
RELEASE DATE: 02/09/1997<br>
CONTACT: <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Contact" VALUE="Your Name" SIZE=35><br>
PHONE:  <INPUT TYPE="text" NAME="Phone" VALUE="Phone #"><p>


<P>ALCOHOL AND DRUG TREATMENT HELPS REDUCE DOMESTIC VIOLENCE


<P>BOSTON -- &quot;When my husband gets drunk, he slaps me around,&quot; says Ruth, a soft-spoken woman in her late 40's, with visible bruises on her arms and her neck. &quot;He gets into these rages and you never know where they will lead,&quot; she says, her voice quivering as she speaks. &quot;Like last week, he went out drinking with his friends and when he came home, he punched me so hard that I fell to the floor and I couldn't get up.&quot;


<P>Every 12 seconds in the United States a woman is battered by her mate, according to Women's Work, a public arts program run by the women's clothing manufacturer, Liz Claiborne, Inc. And many of these incidents are related to alcohol and drug abuse.  But until recently, many women were afraid to talk about their ordeals -- fearing for their safety or that of their children.  The recent brutal murder of Nicole Simpson, the ex-wife of athlete and sportscaster O.J. Simpson, brought the issue of domestic violence into the national spotlight. O.J. has been charged with Nicole's death.


<P>&quot;How many people have to die to get this country to recognize and do something about the very real problem of domestic violence?&quot; asks Lila Brown, director of the local Coalition Against Alcohol and Drug Abuse. &quot;We know that more than 2.5 million women are victims of violence in this country every year, and that alcohol and drugs are associated with up to 50 percent of all spousal attacks. Isn't it time we woke up and did something about this?&quot;


<P>While not all batterers consume alcohol, studies have shown that for those who drink, alcohol increases the chance and severity of an attack.  And it is of no surprise that the most severe batterers tend to be the heaviest drinkers. Experts explain that men who batter women drink to give themselves permission to be violent.  Medical expenses for domestic violence total from $3 to $5 billion each year, according to the Colorado Domestic Violence Coalition. And businesses lose another $100 million in lost wages, sick leave, absenteeism and reduced productivity related to domestic violence.  In fact, a survey by the Department of Justice found that domestic violence accounts for 100,000 days of hospitalization, 30,000 emergency room visits, and 40,000 doctors appointments a year.


<P>&quot;The fact is, we can't afford not to treat substance abuse and the related domestic violence that so often results against women,&quot; Brown says. She points out that for substance abusers, treatment for domestic violence alone will not be effective without simultaneously providing treatment for the alcohol and/or drug addictions.  &quot;It is cost-effective to treat the substance abuse problem, rather than just paying for the damage that results,&quot; Brown says, adding that the damage is measured not only in money but also in lives. &quot;That's why as the nation looks to implement a new health plan, it is absolutely essential that substance abuse treatment be included in this plan for all those who need it.&quot;<p>


<p><BR><HR>
