br>"Tobacco, alcohol and drug abuse slips its hands deep in the taxpayers' pockets, while our lawmakers look the other way," said Califano, president of The National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University (CASA)*. The CASA study on federal entitlements and substance abuse, which will be released in its entirety this spring, finds that:<UL><LI>Spending on federal entitlement programs linked to drug, alcohol and tobacco abuse will be about $70 billion in 1997.<LI>Medicare alone will spend at least $30 billion in 1997 to treat injuries due to substance abuse, largely smoking.<LI>Social security disability will write more than $5 billion in checks to individuals disabled by tobacco, alcohol and drugs (80 percent due to tobacco).<LI>At least 20 percent of welfare recipients -- about one million mothers -- have drug and alcohol problems severe enough to require treatment before they will be able to benefit from literacy and job training, or hold a job.</UL>"Yet neither the Clinton Administration nor the Republican Congress provides any funds in their reform packages to treat these women that are to be moved off the welfare rolls," Califano said. "Cutting off their benefits without offering them treatment will only scatter more homeless individuals on our streets and produce more crime and more abused and neglected children."<br><br>The CASA study on federal entitlement programs will assess the cost of substance abuse to Medicare; Medicaid; Veterans, Federal employee, and other health programs; Social Security Disability Insurance; Temporary Assistance to Needy Families; Food Stamps, and Supplemental Security Income for indigent individuals who are aged, blind or disabled.<br><br>Califano, who as President Johnson's chief domestic policy advisor was an architect of the Great Society program, said that government alone will never solve the problem of substance abuse and addiction. "Indeed I believe that government's responsibility, significant as it is, is not paramount here."<br><br>"The road to a drug free America lies not in the executive agencies, congressional committees and government programs, but in our children and their parents; in their trust in God and in each other; in their acceptance of the moral and spiritual values that should guide their lives," said Califano. "There's a lot of work that needs to be done on that road. And most of that work is a mom and pop operation," he added.<br><br>The National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University is the only national organization that brings together under one roof all the professional disciplines needed to study and combat all types of substance abuse as they affect all aspects of society. CASA's goals are: to inform Americans of the economic and social costs of substance abuse and its impact on their lives; to assess what works in prevention, treatment and law enforcement; and to encourage individuals and institutions to take responsibility to combat substance abuse and addiction.<br><br>For more information, visit <A HREF="http://www.casacolumbia.org">CASA's website</A>.<br><br>* The National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University is neither affiliated with, nor sponsored by, the National Court Appointed Special Advocate Association (also known as "CASA") or any of its member organizations, or any other organization with the name of "CASA".<br><br>###<br><br></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><FONT SIZE = "-1"><TABLE WIDTH ="100%"><TR><TD WIDTH="30%"><B>Date:   </B>02/05/1997</TD></TR></TABLE></FONT><P><I>Distributed by <A HREF="http://www.jointogether.org">Join Together Online</A>.</I></P>    <P><CENTER><A HREF="/Mapserve/footer.map"><IMG SRC="/MapServe/footer.gif"WIDTH="441" HEIGHT="27" BORDER="0" ALIGN=middle  ISMAP></A><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="/default.html">JTO</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/index.html">Index</A>| <A HREF="/JTO/search.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="/JTO/comments.html">Com